column3: Java zip distribution includes an incompatible htlmunit-driver with bundled htlmunit
column4: With [version 2.53 you decided to not redistribute `htmlunit-driver`](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/master/java/CHANGELOG). When updating to 3.4.0 I've realized there is again a [`htmlunit-driver.jar` bundled with the .zip distribution](http://selenium-release.storage.googleapis.com/3.4/selenium-java-3.4.0.zip), with a `htmlunit-2.26.jar` dependency included. I though I could use it, but when executing any test using `HtmlUnitDriver` I got: ``` java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError: com/gargoylesoftware/htmlunit/InteractivePage     at org.openqa.selenium.htmlunit.HtmlUnitDriver$HtmlUnitTargetLocator.activeElement(HtmlUnitDriver.java:1335)     at org.openqa.selenium.htmlunit.HtmlUnitWebElement.switchFocusToThisIfNeeded(HtmlUnitWebElement.java:292)     at org.openqa.selenium.htmlunit.HtmlUnitWebElement.sendKeys(HtmlUnitWebElement.java:319)     at org.openqa.selenium.htmlunit.HtmlUnitWebElement.sendKeys(HtmlUnitWebElement.java:311) .... ```  Which there is no such class in `htmlunit-2.26.jar`. My surprise is that `htmlunit-driver.jar`'s pom file indicates that depends on... 2.23 version, not 2.26 as it is bundled.

column3: [python] provide element locator in the error when element is invisible
column4: When we're trying to interact with invisible element from Python library we got an exception with the following message: `You may only interact with visible elements`. When this message is showing to user it doesn't help him to debug this situation because it miss the information about element itself.  I'm suggesting to include element locator in the error message, for example: `Element id=my-bth is invisible. You may only interact with visible elements`.  (I was initially reported this to the Selenium2Library (https://github.com/robotframework/Selenium2Library/issues/769) but author has said that this is Selenium issue.)

column3: Fix Firefox location detection on Windows_x64
column4: When searching for firefox.exe Selenium would not properly detect Firefox x64 installations under 32-bit Ruby on x64 Windows (10?). For Windows x64 with Ruby x86 the current code would always detect only "C:\Program Files (x86)", since both 'PROGRAMFILES' and 'ProgramFiles(x86)' ENV variables dynamically map to "C:\Program Files (x86)" because of the Ruby x86 bitness. Due to that Firefox x64 would not be auto-detected with error "Selenium::WebDriver::Error::WebDriverError: Could not find Firefox binary (os=windows). Make sure Firefox is installed or set the path manually with Selenium::WebDriver::Firefox::Binary.path=".   The Firefox x64 executable is actually located under "C:\Program Files' but Selenium would look only under "C:\\Program Files (x86)".  The fix is to introduce a new environment variable poll for "ProgramW6432" (https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/aa384274(v=vs.85).aspx) which will return the proper "\\Program Files" directory on a Windows x64 machine with Ruby x86.  To easily check that solution works: - On Windows x64 machine with Ruby x86 run 'irb' - Type `` `set` `` and observe the presence of ProgramW6432  - [X] By placing an `X` in the preceding checkbox, I verify that I have signed the [Contributor License Agreement](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#step-6-sign-the-cla)

column3: Boolean command line arguments should be `true` if present
column4: When launching a selenium server process using  java 3.0.1-server.jar -debug 10:14:44.427 INFO - Selenium build info: version: '3.0.1', revision: '1969d75' 10:14:44.428 INFO - Launching a standalone Selenium Server ... ```  So the same command does not work with 3.1.0+.  ```shell $> java 3.1.0-server.jar -debug Exception in thread "main" com.beust.jcommander.ParameterException: Expected a value after parameter -debug         at com.beust.jcommander.JCommander.processFixedArity(JCommander.java:883)         at com.beust.jcommander.JCommander.processFixedArity(JCommander.java:857)         at com.beust.jcommander.JCommander.parseValues(JCommander.java:725)         at com.beust.jcommander.JCommander.parse(JCommander.java:282)         at com.beust.jcommander.JCommander.parse(JCommander.java:265)         at com.beust.jcommander.JCommander.(JCommander.java:210)         at org.openqa.grid.selenium.GridLauncherV3$1.setConfiguration(GridLauncherV3.java:227)         at org.openqa.grid.selenium.GridLauncherV3.buildLauncher(GridLauncherV3.java:155)         at org.openqa.grid.selenium.GridLauncherV3.main(GridLauncherV3.java:75) ```  In order to get it to work again, a user must using something like  ```shell $> java 3.1.0-server.jar -debug true 10:19:12.394 INFO - Selenium build info: version: '3.1.0', revision: '86a5d70' 10:19:12.394 INFO - Launching a standalone Selenium Server ... ```  With https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/commit/705be71ce9ec7e3825cb1633d3da40ab75a8819f, that behavior was changed. That change was never called out in the release notes via the [CHANGELOG](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/4fcbef7f486d74a741a441482e0a1676f9d959ae/java/CHANGELOG) or in the [GitHub release](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/releases/tag/selenium-3.1.0).  Can you please update the release notes to reflect the changes?

column3: Invalid "Content-Encoding: None" header when downloading "IEDriverServer_x64_3.4.0.zip" from SeleniumHQ
column4: When downloading e.g. this file: http://selenium-release.storage.googleapis.com/3.4/IEDriverServer_x64_3.4.0.zip from the SeleniumHQ website, the server sends a `Content-Encoding: None` HTTP header.  This header causes our build script (backed by Maven Wagon, backed by Apache HttpClient) to throw an exception. `None` does not seem to be a valid Content-Encoding, see e.g. [here](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/Content-Encoding), probably it should rather be `identity`?  Any chance fixing this?

column3: Suggestion: Support for DriverService "run as" username/password
column4: When creating tests for Windows, there is occasionally a need to run the same test, while switching between different users (like, rung line 1-10 using windows user A, then run line 11-20 using user B, etc). This is useful for testing workflow applications for example, with **integrated windows security**  To be able to properly test this, one needs to logon different users and re-launch the driver using those. This pull request adds support for launching driver under a specific user (the underlying OS support is already there, it just exposes those fields as optional properties). Means, there is a "StartupInfo", but not all properties of it can now be set by user; this suggestion adds username/password to the list of available properties.  We needed this functionality in our project, that is basically a long workflow. Other examples where it may be needed (from stackoverflow):  https://stackoverflow.com/questions/16590207/how-to-impersonate-a-specific-user-with-selenium-webdriver https://stackoverflow.com/questions/28045870/how-can-i-run-internet-explorer-selenium-tests-as-a-specific-domain-user https://stackoverflow.com/questions/9951377/using-impersonation-to-launch-processes-indirectly-in-c-sharp https://sqa.stackexchange.com/questions/2277/using-selenium-webdriver-with-windows-authentication  Pull request: #4354   Usage example:              var service = ChromeDriverService.CreateDefaultService();              service.StartupDomain = "contoso";              service.StartupUserName = "john.doe";              var pwd = new SecureString();             foreach (var c in "P@ssword")                 pwd.AppendChar(c);              service.StartupPassword = pwd;              service.Start();              var options = new ChromeOptions();             options.AddArgument("--no-sandbox");              var driver = new RemoteWebDriver(service.ServiceUrl, options);

column3: Also define stdin or it will crash on Python + cx_Freeze: WindowsErro…
column4: Using Python + cx_Freeze will result into an exception:  > OSError: [WinError 6] The handle is invalid  This is because there is no stdin defined in the service.py file for the `subprocess.Popen()` command. Underwater the subprocess tries to create a handle which also looks for stdin under Windows this gets a bit tricky when using Bash or cx_Freeze. So, I defined `stdin` as well, and the crash is gone. Optionally you can also use: ```python FNULL = open(os.devnull, 'r') subprocess.Popen(.... ,stdin=FNULL) ```   - [x] By placing an `X` in the preceding checkbox, I verify that I have signed the [Contributor License Agreement](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#step-6-sign-the-cla)  Trying to fix #536 & #547 as well.

column3: [Feature Request] PageFactory support for nested Page Objects
column4: Using a custom FieldDecorator, I can get PageFactory to populate nested PageObjects that are themselves annotated with FindBy  e.g.   ``` public class GooglePage {  	@FindBy(name = "q") 	WebElement search;  	@FindBy(css="#res .g") 	List searchItems; 	 	public WebElement getSearch() { 		return search; 	}  	public List getSearchItems() { 		return searchItems; 	}  } ``` ``` public class GoogleSearchItem {  	@FindBy(css=".r a") 	WebElement title;  	@FindBy(className="st") 	WebElement description;  	public WebElement getTitle() { 		return title; 	}  	public WebElement getDescription() { 		return description; 	}  }  ```  In this example, initialising the elements in `GooglePage` will recursively initialise the elements for `GoogleSearchItem`. I think this is a very powerful design pattern and is considered best practice within my organisation.   I think this should be the default behaviour of the PageFactory, more specifically, of `DefaultFieldDecorator`.   I'd be happy to do the work but I just wanted to hear from others first - is there good reason to not have this feature?

column3: Conform to the api of urllib2 for adding header for a request
column4: urllib2 capitalize the header key and relies on this capitalization to decide if the 'Content-type' field is filled in and if not, fill it in with the default of 'application/x-www-form-urlencoded'. A recent change causes the header in the request named 'Content-type' to change to 'Content-Type' and urllib2 assumes the 'Content-type' field in the request header is not filled in, so tests are using the default instead and are giving the error: : Message: Given content type 'application/x-www-form-urlencoded' is not 'application/json;charset=UTF-8'.  - [X ] By placing an `X` in the preceding checkbox, I verify that I have signed the [Contributor License Agreement](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#step-6-sign-the-cla)

column3: Update atoms to reflect Chrome TouchEvent support.
column4: Update atoms to reflect Chrome TouchEvent support. The previous events.js logic breaks mobile Safari because initTouchEvent.length == 0 on mobile Safari, causing it to go erroneously down the Chrome/Android path. This logic used to break Chrome Mobile Emulation of ios, but not that Chrome now lacks the initTouchEvent entirely (relies completely on the TouchEvent constructor), we can return to the original user agent checks without breaking Chrome Mobile Emulation.  - [X] By placing an `X` in the preceding checkbox, I verify that I have signed the [Contributor License Agreement](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#step-6-sign-the-cla)   --- This change is [](https://reviewable.io/reviews/seleniumhq/selenium/4528)

column3: WebDriverException typo
column4: Ubuntu 14.04 (Travis) Selenium Python bindings 3.4.0 (latest) Mozilla Firefox 53.0 (latest) geckodriver v0.16.1 (latest)  There is a typo in the WebDriverException message template, for example: `marionette was not a the name of a known capability or a valid extension capability`.  Should instead be something like `marionette is not a known capability ...`  Following up on #3915.

column3: WebDriverException: Message: marionette was not a the name of a known capability or a valid extension capability
column4: Ubuntu 14.04 (Travis) Selenium Python bindings 3.4.0 (latest) Mozilla Firefox 53.0 (latest) geckodriver v0.16.1 (latest)  I originally commented on https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/issues/3890#issuecomment-296695933 because it appeared to be the same issue, but the [latest geckodriver release](https://github.com/mozilla/geckodriver/releases/tag/v0.16.1) did not address it for me.  The above combination of versions causes every one of our tests to fail on Firefox with `WebDriverException: Message: marionette was not a the name of a known capability or a valid extension capability`. Please see https://travis-ci.org/EFForg/privacybadger/jobs/226049565 for the full stack trace. Downgrading to Python bindings < 3.4.0 resolves the issue.  Here is the pull request where I run into this problem: https://github.com/EFForg/privacybadger/pull/1343.  Here is the branch where I check to see if it's fixed in geckodriver v0.16.1 (it is not): https://github.com/EFForg/privacybadger/compare/upgrade-selenium.

column3: Add support for W3C actions to node client
column4: tl;dr Please implement the W3C actions API for the node client.  Using the latest selenium-webdriver node client (3.5) to drive a local instance of the latest Firefox (55) on Linux, calling the user interactions API results in the infamous `UnknownCommandError: POST /session/[...]/moveto did not match a known command` error.  To my understanding, [Firefox / geckodriver has implemented the W3C actions API](https://github.com/mozilla/geckodriver/issues/233), while the node client at the moment only supports an older version of the API (having a quick look at [http.js](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/javascript/node/selenium-webdriver/lib/http.js), the `/actions` endpoint is missing).  It seems this has already been implemented in other language bindings, for example [the Java client](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/commit/e8a2a65d2e6e6b7592d6d89742f5907ca4359cd6). It would be awesome if we could get W3C action support for the node bindings to :) .  PS: Thanks for your great work on Selenium!

column3: Switching to frame element is broken in Selenium standalone
column4: This was broken at commit e32b83dc4321b05ecf9c7a9bbe21722a06b046ad. It worked at the preceding commit (2775361b783993421ab5addda734ff021438d9f6).  ## Steps to reproduce - 1. Start the Selenium standalone server. 2. Locate a  element. 3. Attempt to switch to that frame element.  Here's a bash script to reproduce, which should make clear what JSON commands are being exchanged: https://gist.github.com/juangj/837229df708abbd3a5f91e39017d1d2c  I don't know for sure that this isn't broken in other settings (e.g., just using the Java client), but this is the first way I reproduced it.  The relevant commands look like this: ``` $ curl -s -d '{"using": "css selector", "value": "#left"}' http://localhost:4444/wd/hub/session/abe4894a-b6ab-4925-8907-46b9a09d2d17/element {"state":"success", ..., "value":{"ELEMENT":"0"}, ...}  $ curl -s -d '{"id": {"ELEMENT": "0"}}' http://localhost:4444/wd/hub/session/abe4894a-b6ab-4925-8907-46b9a09d2d17/frame {"state":"no such frame", ... ```

column3: License issue: GPL code in deps
column4: This project is licensed under Apache License 2.0, but it depends on GPL code.  To reproduce: switch to a clean directory, `npm i selenium-webdriver`.  File `node_modules/adm-zip/methods/deflater.js` has the following header: ``` /*  * $Id: rawdeflate.js,v 0.5 2013/04/09 14:25:38 dankogai Exp dankogai $  *  * GNU General Public License, version 2 (GPL-2.0)  *   http://opensource.org/licenses/GPL-2.0  * Original:  *  http://www.onicos.com/staff/iz/amuse/javascript/expert/deflate.txt  */ ```  It looks used (at least it is `require`-d).  ``` firefox/profile.js:const AdmZip = require('adm-zip'), firefox/extension.js:const AdmZip = require('adm-zip'), remote/index.js:const AdmZip = require('adm-zip'); ``` which in turn requires `deflater.js` upon require.   See https://www.apache.org/licenses/GPL-compatibility.html: > This **licensing incompatibility applies only when some Apache project software becomes a derivative work of some GPLv3 software, because then the Apache software would have to be distributed under GPLv3**. This would be incompatible with ASF's requirement that all Apache software must be distributed under the Apache License 2.0. > We avoid GPLv3 software because **merely linking to it is considered by the GPLv3 authors to create a derivative work**. We want to honor their license. Unless GPLv3 licensors relax this interpretation of their own license regarding linking, our licensing philosophies are fundamentally incompatible. **This is an identical issue for both GPLv2 and GPLv3.**  Upstream issue is https://github.com/cthackers/adm-zip/issues/77, but the adm-zip project looks dead, so it's not likely to be resolved there.  Similar issues in other projects: https://github.com/Medium/phantomjs/issues/495, https://github.com/giggio/node-chromedriver/issues/102.

column3: Improved WebDriverExceptions: Subclasses
column4: This is a feature request. Currently, Selenium Python's `WebDriverException` encompasses exceptions from many different causes. For example:  * Message: Session [ea4e15ef-f60e-48a5-b520-9f360a100378] was terminated due to FORWARDING_TO_NODE_FAILED * Message: cannot forward the request 172.20.0.4:5555 failed to respond * Message: Session [e8457d7d-585c-47d3-a248-d249e21d4a8f] not available and is not among the last 1000 terminated sessions.  It would be great if these different causes were reflected by using subclasses of WebDriverException. For example, I'm using `webdriver.Remote`, and I like to handle exceptions differently if they were caused by the URL being loaded (ex, DNS lookup failed), or by a problem with the webdriver session itself (remote browser instance was killed).   My current workaround is to grep for error message strings in the WebDriverException, but that's certainly not ideal.

column3: support shadow DOM when reading element text
column4: This adds support to `getTextContent_` for reading text from shadow DOM nodes.  The following steps were added to the logic here:  * If the node has a shadow root, return early with the result of retrieving the text for the root rather than the element * If the node is a document fragment, treat it like an element with the existing logic (as a fragment has child nodes too) * If the node is a `` (v1 spec) or `` (v0 spec), iterate through the associated light DOM nodes and append their text content  Regarding the first point, we ignore the light DOM (the element's childnodes) and skip straight to the shadow root because any light children will only be rendered if there is a related slot/content (either a default or a named one). So any which do get slotted/distributed will be picked up further down when their insertion point is processed.  If I need to add this somewhere else or did my tests wrong, do let me know.  - [x] By placing an `X` in the preceding checkbox, I verify that I have signed the [Contributor License Agreement](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#step-6-sign-the-cla)

column3: add ctor for ElementNotInteractableError
column4: The WebDriver spec  defines the "element not interactable" error code, and geckodriver returns that code in response to a command on an element that isn't interactable, so selenium-webdriver should define a ctor for the error and display that ctor instead of the generic WebDriverError when printing errors to the console.  - [X] By placing an `X` in the preceding checkbox, I verify that I have signed the [Contributor License Agreement](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#step-6-sign-the-cla)

column3: Buck doesn't write junit4 XML test output
column4: The Selenium fork of Buck wrote *-junit4.xml files up until 2dce963c2118b9457b83d58a849ca610db904820 bumped the version. As far as I can tell, @shs96c had hacked support for JUnit4 output into his fork, and we were using that, but the new version doesn't include that change.  The JUnit XML outputs are used by Jenkins to present more fine-grained test results. Nobody noticed the missing XML files earlier, because Jenkins had already been broken by a different problem (#4173), and also because nobody ever looks at Jenkins.

column3: java client - Extract BrowserOptions interface.
column4: The intent is to standardize an approach to integrating the various options objects (`SafariOptions`, `ChromeOptions`, etc.) with a `DesiredCapabilities` object. column3: SendKeys in 3.5.2 sends incorrect keys when using grid and RemoteWebDriver
column4: The following example using 3.5.2 libraries shows different behaviour if using a local or a RemoteWebDriver. If using a local driver (in the example ChromeDriver.exe but the same behaviour is shown with IEDriverServer.exe) the SendKeys of Ctrl-a and backspace selects a text if present and deletes it, then sends the text "Cheese".  If using a grid configuration with selenium-server-standalone-3.5.2.jar the SendKeys of Ctrl-a and backspace results in the text "?a??" being sent.  If a grid configuration using selenium-server-standalone-3.4.0.jar is used instead then correct behaviour is shown by SendKeys.    package com.mytest.selenium;  import java.net.MalformedURLException; import java.net.URL;  import org.openqa.selenium.By; import org.openqa.selenium.Keys; import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver; import org.openqa.selenium.WebElement; import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeDriver; import org.openqa.selenium.remote.DesiredCapabilities; import org.openqa.selenium.remote.RemoteWebDriver;  public class SendKeyTest {  	private static final boolean USELOCAL = true; 	 	public static void main(String[] args) { 		 		WebDriver driver = null; 		 		if (USELOCAL) { 			driver = new ChromeDriver(DesiredCapabilities.chrome());  		} else { 			URL url = null; 			try { 				url = new URL("http://localhost:4444/wd/hub"); 			} catch (MalformedURLException e) { 				e.printStackTrace(); 			} 			driver = new RemoteWebDriver(url, DesiredCapabilities.chrome()); 		} 		                driver.get("http://www.google.com");                 WebElement element = driver.findElement(By.name("q"));                          element.sendKeys(Keys.chord(Keys.CONTROL, "a"));  // results in ?a? if using remote                element.sendKeys(Keys.BACK_SPACE);	// results in ? if using remote                 element.sendKeys("Cheese");                element.submit();          	       driver.quit(); 	       System.out.println("done"); 	} }

column3: Rb Polymorphism with Handshake
column4: The Appium code base is a literal mess, so I'm going to give examples based on the Sauce Client gem I'm writing.  What I want to do is take actions before & after driver initialization, add a `#sauce` method for interacting with our API and annotations, and take additional actions before the `#quit` method.  Let's start with what works before `selenium-webdriver-3.4.1.gem`:  [Subclassing the Bridge](https://github.com/titusfortner/saucer/blob/bridge_subclass/lib/saucer/driver.rb)  This no longer works because `Selenium::WebDriver::Remote::Bridge` can't be initialized with a `:desired_capabilities` parameter. (`ArgumentError: unknown option: {:desired_capabilities=> ...`)  I get that with the handshake this implementation probably doesn't work. It also has the disadvantage of requiring duplication of event listener handling if present.  So I tried [implementing this with composition](https://github.com/titusfortner/saucer/blob/master/lib/saucer/driver.rb). This mostly works except that I have to add the `#method_missing` and the `#respond_to?`, as well as needing to do `@driver.driver` to get the instance of the `Remote::Driver` instead of just `@driver`. Additionally, I can't do `Watir::Browser.new(@driver)`, because Watir is looking for `@driver` to be an instance of `Selenium::WebDriver::Driver`, and it isn't.  (The other sticking point here is that while the above code worked in `selenium-webdriver-3.4.2.gem` it is broken in `selenium-webdriver-3.4.3.gem`).  So this brings us to what I really want. A subclass of `Selenium::WebDriver::Driver`. This is the classic use case of inheritance. The Sauce driver *is a driver with a couple extra behaviors. Ideally, [this is what I think it should look like to the user](https://github.com/titusfortner/saucer/blob/inheritence/lib/saucer/driver.rb). `#super` in the right spots, with the extra method that doesn't require monkey patching, or duplicating code for handshake or listeners.  Hopefully this clarifies what I'm looking for. I have a couple ideas for what might work as far as an implementation, but I haven't had a chance to dig into it yet.

column3: New Errors added in selenium-webdriver 3.4 never get used due to naming error [rb]
column4: Selenium Version:   3.4.0 - ruby Browser:   Firefox  The new errors added in selenium-webdriver 3.4.0  (ElementNotInteractable and ElementClickIntercepted) never get returned due to `for_code` - https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/rb/lib/selenium/webdriver/common/error.rb#L218 - requiring eerror class names to end in 'Error'.  They should probably be renamed to ElementNotInteractableError and ElementClickInterceptedError

column3: W3C: Undefined behavior of WebElement.sendKeys() for checkbox
column4: Selenium Version:   3.4.0 Browser:   Firefox 54.0.1 geckodriver 0.18  I entered a bug for the geckodriver project because sendKeys(" ") of a space character for a checkbox element does nothing (silently fails). [https://github.com/mozilla/geckodriver/issues/777](https://github.com/mozilla/geckodriver/issues/777)  The bug was closed with a reference to the webdriver spec. https://w3c.github.io/webdriver/webdriver-spec.html#element-send-keys The solution would be to use the Actions API for this use case.  I have 2 questions: 1.) Isn't the behavior WebElement.sendKeys undefined for the checkbox (see referenced spec above)? Setting the value of the checkbox element makes no sense. If sendKeys() is not supported for a checkbox it should at least returning an error (in my opinion).  2.) This question here is kind of a meta question: How does Selenium avoid major incompatibilities like that in the time frame in which there still exist OSS webdrivers (like chromedriver). It seems that at least for this sendKeys() example and also the Actions API the semantics changed quite a bit.  Regards, Philip

column3: Wrong positions for all elements when display is not set to 100% in Windows
column4: Selenium 2.40.0 Windows 10 Firefox 27.0.1  When the "Scale and layout" in Windows 10 is set to a different value than 100%, Selenium won't take this setting into account and all coordinates of all elements are therefore off.  Right-click on desktop in Windows, pick Display Settings, under tab "Display" there is a field labeled "Change the size of text, apps and other items" (changing this requires log off and log on to apply). Set this to 175% for example and see any previously valid tests to fail due to the scale not being into account.

column3: After our mobile web upgrade to React 16.0.x, our automation input box sendkeys got failure on iOS simulator
column4: Protractor: 3.0.0  selenium-webdriver: 3.5.0  Test device: Saucelabs iPhone simulator iOS 10.0  Mobile web build by React 10.6.x  Our mobile web has input box which build React controlled input, after we upgrade the React from 10.5.x to 10.6.x  Our automation test got failure when we submit the input box value to our backend.  We used the saucelabs to execute our automatino testing. On the saucelabs recording video, we can see the input has value be presented.  We used webdriver sendkeys function to insert value to the input box element. Then click the submit button. We check our backend log, the input box value is empty.  I try to manual the simulator on saucelabs, use the soft keyboard to type the value and click submit. it works.  I also try use the Android emulator to run the same test, it works too. It seems the sendkeys function didn't trigger the React properly event. so the React component think the input value didn't be changed.  I saw the React changelog and noticed the upgrade include some input improvment.  https://facebook.github.io/react/blog/2017/06/13/react-v15.6.0.html  Does anyone face the same issue and know hope to fix or some workaround.  Thanks,  Charles

column3: ImplicitWait and PageLoad don't seem to be working for FireFox?
column4: OS: Windows 10 Pro, 64 bit OS, x64-based processor  Selenium Version: Selenium-Server-Standalone-3.4.0  GeckoDriver Version: v0.16.1  Browser: Mozilla Firefox  Browser Version: 52.0  Framework: Specflow v2.1.0  Expected Behavior - ImplicitWait and PageLoad should wait for the amount of time specified when searching for an element if it is not immediately present and wait for the amount of time the driver should wait for a page to load when setting the Url property for FF.    Actual Behavior - Steps fail due to code running ahead, indicating code isn't waiting for the timeouts.  Steps to reproduce -  Hi, I've read some of the other issues for the new ImplicitWait & PageLoad properties and can see that poeple were having issues but these seem to have been fixed recently. I think there are still issues with these two when running them with FireFox. I've kept to v52 as I could see there were still issues with v53. **Note: for Chrome, IE & Edge drivers I am still using the old ImplicitlyWait & SetPageLoadTimeout properties and have no issues when executing tests on these browsers. Obviously SetPageLoadTimeout thows an Exception when used with FF (gecko) driver.**  I am using a switch statement: `switch (browser)                 {                     case "FF":                         var waitfor = Driver.Browser.Manage().Timeouts().ImplicitWait;                         waitfor = TimeSpan.FromSeconds(Convert.ToDouble(impwait));                         var pageload = Driver.Browser.Manage().Timeouts().PageLoad;                         pageload = TimeSpan.FromSeconds((Convert.ToDouble(pagetimeout)));                         break;                     default:                         Driver.Browser.Manage().Timeouts().ImplicitlyWait(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(Convert.ToDouble(impwait)));                         Driver.Browser.Manage().Timeouts().SetPageLoadTimeout(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(Convert.ToDouble(pagetimeout))); //Causes an error with FF!                         break;                 }`  Incidentally Selenium throws an Exception if I change the line: ` var pageload = Driver.Browser.Manage().Timeouts().PageLoad;                         pageload = TimeSpan.FromSeconds((Convert.ToDouble(pagetimeout)));` to ` Driver.Browser.Manage().Timeouts().PageLoad = TimeSpan.FromSeconds((Convert.ToDouble(pagetimeout)));`  The Exception thrown is: WebDriver: (IndexOutOfBounds): at OpenQA.Selenium.Remote.RemoteWebDriver.UnpackAndThrowOnError(Response errorResponse) at OpenQA.Selenium.Remote.RemoteWebDriver.Execute(String driverCommandToExecute, Dictionary`2 parameters) at OpenQA.Selenium.Remote.RemoteTimeouts.ExecuteSetTimeout(String timeoutType, TimeSpan timeToWait) at OpenQA.Selenium.Remote.RemoteTimeouts.set_PageLoad(TimeSpan value) at PhoenixWebAutomation.Hooks1.BeforeTestRun() in C:\Users\XXXX\Documents\Visual Studio 2017\Projects\Automation Framework\src\02 Dev\XXXX\Hooks1.cs:line 71

column3: pageLoadTimeout not working with Selenium 3
column4: OS: Windows 10 Selenium Version: 3.4.0 (Java) Browser: Firefox Browser Version: 53.0 (32-bit)  When I use below line of code: driver.manage().timeouts().pageLoadTimeout(5, TimeUnit.SECONDS);  **Expected Behavior -** Then it would implement the maximum wait (5 seconds) for page load to complete  **Actual Behavior -** But the maximum time for page load to complete not implemented  **Steps to reproduce -**  1. Initialize the WebDriver: System.setProperty("webdriver.gecko.driver","geckodriver.exe"); WebDriver driver = new FirefoxDriver();  2. Set page load timeout 1 second: driver.manage().timeouts().pageLoadTimeout(1 , TimeUnit.SECONDS);  3. Launch application: driver.get("http://www.seleniumhq.org/");  Here, if application would take more than 1 second to load completely then the exception related to page load timeout should be occurred. But, it is not occurring.

column3: webDriver.get(url) doesn't do anything when ChromeDriver is initiated with user-data-dir
column4: OS:  Windows8 Selenium Version:  3.4 Browser:  Chrome  I've very peculiar usecase that requires me to run multiple webdriver instances at the same time. Unfortunately, IDP for the application that I'm trying to automate doesn't allow for multiple simultaneous logins.. as soon as the second login is done, first login session expires. While researching how to share sessions across WebDriver instances, I came across user-data-dir option.  This is how I implemented..  I'll create one webdriver instance and login into the application. I'll keep this webdriver instance running and will create more webdriver instances that actually do the automation work.Since I already logged into the application from first instance, I should be automatically logged into the second instance.   ``` public class TestClass {     private static WebDriver webDriver = null;     public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {          TestClass tc = new TestClass();          if(webDriver == null) {              webDriver = tc.getWebDriverInstance();              webDriver.get("https://example.com/loginpage");             //enter userid/password, click login button             //login is successful and redirected to next page - https://example.com/securepage          }           WebDriver newWebDriverOne = this.getWebDriverInstance();          newWebDriverOne.get("https://example.com/securepage"); // this doesn't work           WebDriver newWebDriverTwo = this.getWebDriverInstance();          newWebDriverTwo.get("https://example.com/securepage");// this doesn't work   }    WebDriver getWebDriverInstance(){          DesiredCapabilities dCaps = DesiredCapabilities.chrome();         ChromeOptions options = new ChromeOptions();         options.addArguments("user-data-dir=C:/user/me/selenium/chrome");         dCaps.setCapability(ChromeOptions.CAPABILITY, options);     return new ChromeDriver(dCaps);     }  } ```  Problem with this is, when I call get() on the newWebDriver instance which is created after the first one, nothing happens. Selenium opens the second window as since I created a new webdriver instance, but get() doesn't do anything. I tried manually entering the securepage url in the opened window and it worked. I was able to see the secure page without getting redirected to login page. That means that the automatic login into second instance is working since they share same profile. But the webDriver is useless as it doesn't do get() anymore.  It seems like it is impossible to have multiple webdriver instances if we specify user-data-dir. Is there any other option to share cookie data between sessions?

column3: support headless configuration for Firefox in selenium-webdriver package
column4: OS:  Windows, macOS, Linux Selenium Version:  3.5.0 Browser:  Firefox Browser Version:  56  Once Firefox supports headless mode on all three platforms (starting with Firefox 56, currently in beta and due to be released next month), the selenium-webdriver package should support configuring Firefox to run headlessly the same way it supports Chrome running headlessly, via a `headless()` method on the Firefox driver's _Options_ class, so that you can drive Firefox headlessly via:  ```js const { Builder } = require('selenium-webdriver'); const firefox = require('selenium-webdriver/firefox'); const driver = new Builder() .forBrowser('firefox') .setFirefoxOptions(new firefox.Options().headless()) .build(); ```  (It would additionally be useful to be able to set the headless window's size via the equivalent of Chrome's `windowSize({width, height})` method.)

column3: Selenium Server randomly infinity looping on elements.all(by.css(...))
column4: OS:  Windows 10 Selenium Version:  3.1.0 Browser:  All, as far as I can tell (tried Chrome 58.0.3029.96 (64-bit), Firefox 52.0.2 (32-bit) and Edge)  Hi all, So I'm trying to just get some elements using $$('selector'), which goes well most of the time, but seems to randomly hang. Looking at the Selenium Server logging I come across the following...  22:27:54.778 INFO - Executing: [find elements: By.cssSelector: .thumbnail]) 22:27:54.785 INFO - Done: [find elements: By.cssSelector: .thumbnail] 22:27:54.789 INFO - Executing: [is enabled: 10 [[ChromeDriver: chrome on XP (593f83c2b26434d5002c5d60c5fc6cac)] -> css selector: .thumbnail]]) 22:27:54.798 INFO - Done: [is enabled: 10 [[ChromeDriver: chrome on XP (593f83c2b26434d5002c5d60c5fc6cac)] -> css selector: .thumbnail]] 22:27:54.803 INFO - Executing: [find elements: By.cssSelector: .thumbnail]) 22:27:54.810 INFO - Done: [find elements: By.cssSelector: .thumbnail] 22:27:54.812 INFO - Executing: [is enabled: 10 [[ChromeDriver: chrome on XP (593f83c2b26434d5002c5d60c5fc6cac)] -> css selector: .thumbnail]]) 22:27:54.819 INFO - Done: [is enabled: 10 [[ChromeDriver: chrome on XP (593f83c2b26434d5002c5d60c5fc6cac)] -> css selector: .thumbnail]] 22:27:54.823 INFO - Executing: [find elements: By.cssSelector: .thumbnail]) 22:27:54.831 INFO - Done: [find elements: By.cssSelector: .thumbnail] 22:27:54.834 INFO - Executing: [is enabled: 10 [[ChromeDriver: chrome on XP (593f83c2b26434d5002c5d60c5fc6cac)] -> css selector: .thumbnail]]) 22:27:54.840 INFO - Done: [is enabled: 10 [[ChromeDriver: chrome on XP (593f83c2b26434d5002c5d60c5fc6cac)] -> css selector: .thumbnail]]  etc... For a minute before it times out.  So it seems there are some conditions that trigger an infinite loop?  This is my code, all in one method and I've changed some names. The website it runs against is not open for the public, so this'll have to do...  ``` browser.ignoreSynchronization = true; browser.get('mypage.html'); // redirect browser.wait(EC.presenceOf($('[ng-controller=myotherpagecontroller]'), 2000));  var username = $('input[ng-model=username]'); var password = $('input[type=password]');  username.sendKeys('something'); password.sendKeys('somethingelse');  var submit = $('input[type=submit]'); submit.click(); // another redirect browser.wait(EC.presenceOf($('[ng-controller=mypagecontroller]'), 2000));  browser.get('index.html'); browser.wait(EC.presenceOf($('.btn'), 2000));  var alert; var buttons = $$('.btn');  buttons.get(0).click(); browser.wait(EC.alertIsPresent(), 2000); alert = browser.switchTo().alert(); alert.accept();  buttons.get(1).click(); browser.wait(EC.alertIsPresent(), 2000); var alert = browser.switchTo().alert(); alert.accept();  browser.get('mypage.html'); browser.wait(EC.presenceOf($('[ng-controller=mypagecontroller]'), 2000));  browser.wait(EC.presenceOf($('.thumbnail'), 2000));  var items = $$('.thumbnail'); items.count().then(function (count) {     var first = items.get(0);     first.$('h3').getText().then(function (caption) {         first.$('button').click().then(function () {             browser.wait(EC.not(EC.presenceOf(first), 2000));             var newItems = $$('.thumbnail');             expect(newItems.count()).toBe(count - 1);             expect(newItems.get(0).$('h3').getText()).not.toBe(caption);                          // Refresh and check if the deleted item is still gone.             browser.refresh();             browser.wait(EC.presenceOf($('.thumbnail'), 2000));              // THE SERVER STARTS LOOPING ON THE FOLLOWING LINE...              var afterRefresh = $$('.thumbnail');             expect(afterRefresh.count()).toBe(count - 1);             done();         });     }); }); ```  That's really all I have, can't be more specific at this time as I'm not sure what the problem could be. Also not sure if this is my problem or your bug, so apologies if the problem is me. Thanks anyway.  [Edit] It seems Selenium runs fine the first few times, then starts failing, maybe runs successfully for another run and then keeps failing. I'm running Protractor by the way, so maybe the problem is with them? Hard to tell with all these tools and plugins... [/Edit]

column3: Is it possible to call the `executePhantomJS` method from a `RemoteWebDriver` instance?
column4: OS:  Windows Selenium Version:  3.0.1 Browser:  N/A (PhantomJS)  Is it possible to call the `executePhantomJS` method from a `RemoteWebDriver` instance?    The `PhantomJSDriver` object has the ability to call a PhantomJS specific script, but this method does not exist on `RemoteWebDriver`.    I'm using Selenium Grid to run my tests, but am not able to find a good way to run PhantomJS scripts on the `RemoteWebDriver`.  I've tried manually adding the 'executePhantomScript' command to the `CommandExecutor.CommandInfoRepository` in a `RemoteWebDriver` derivative, but that does not seem to allow the script to run successfully (even though the command appears to be added successfully).  The command I'm adding is `/session/{sessionId}/phantom/execute`.  Output when attempting to run a script after adding the command:  ``` System.NotImplementedException : POST /session/xxxx/phantom/execute Build info: version: '3.0.1', revision: '1969d75', time: '2016-10-18 09:48:19 -0700' System info: host: 'xxxx', ip: 'xxxx', os.name: 'Windows 10', os.arch: 'amd64', os.version: '10.0', java.version: '1.8.0_111' Driver info: driver.version: unknown ``` Scouring the Issues here and in the GhostDriver repo does not turn anything up.  Is this a hopeless scenario?  If so, it seems like full PhantomJSDriver functionality is limited to local usage.

column3: Remote session not sending capabilities to node using Selenium (Ruby) 3.4.3
column4: OS:  OSX 10.8 Selenium Version:  3.4.3 (Ruby bindings) Browser:  Chrome / Firefox / IE Selenium Server Version: 3.4.0 (on hub and nodes)  With 3.4.1 and 3.4.3, I attempted to utilize the new chromeOptions methods of add_argument and add_preference. Locally, these worked fine. When I attempt to run them against my grid, I receive "status error 500" from the hub.  Removing the role of "hub" from the hub VM allows the tests to run successfully on the same VM as a node. Either the grid is attempting to run the session on the hub and getting a 500, or the hub isn't sending the capabilities to the node. I do not see any log on the hub that indicates it's making a request to a node to start the session.  Reverting back to 3.4.0 and using the old style of args and prefs has fixed the issue.  Here's my setup method:  ``` def setup_chrome(params={})   setup = {:selenium_hub => params[:selenium_hub] || SELENIUM_HUB,                 :start_url => params[:start_url] || BASE_URL   }    options = Selenium::WebDriver::Chrome::Options.new   options.add_preference('credentials_enable_service', false)   options.add_preference('profile.password_manager_enabled', false)   options.add_argument('disable-infobars')   options.add_argument('use-fake-device-for-media-stream')   options.add_argument('use-fake-ui-for-media-stream')    caps = Selenium::WebDriver::Remote::Capabilities.chrome(:chromeOptions => options.as_json)   @driver = Selenium::WebDriver.for :remote, :url => setup[:selenium_hub], :desired_capabilities => caps    @driver.get setup[:start_url] end ```

I would expect to get {"status":0...} or {"state":"success"...} out of the /wd/hub/status route for selenium/hub.

column3: Selenium IDE - sendKeys fails on
column4: OS:  OSX Selenium Version:  Selenium IDE 2.9.1 Browser:  Firefox Browser Version:  53.0.3 (64-bit)  ## Expected Behavior - sendKeys should send keypresses to an input of type email.  ## Actual Behavior - sendKeys fails to send the keypresses to an input of type email. (It works fine with type="tel" or "password". And type works.)  ## Steps to reproduce - 1. Open https://jsfiddle.net and put `` in the html block and run it. 2. In Selenium IDE enter ```  	sendKeys 	id=query 	a@b.c   	type 	id=query 	z@y.x  ``` And run the two lines individually.  Note that `sendKeys` fails, but `type` works fine.

column3: Fails for integer parameters (Firefox)
column4: OS:  MacOS 10.12 Selenium Version: 3.5.0  Browser: Firefox 52.3 Geckodriver: 0.18.0 (downloaded latest today) Node.JS module selenium-webdirver: 3.5.0 (downloaded latest today)  I'm trying to set `browser.download.folderList` to `2`, but Selenium sends it as `2.0` to geckodriver, so that it crashes.  ## Steps to reproduce   Here's the code for Node.JS that requires only selenium-webdriver installed. That might not be selenium-webdriver problem though, maybe it's a Java code issue.  ```js const SeleniumServer = require('selenium-webdriver/remote').SeleniumServer; const webdriver = require('selenium-webdriver'); const firefox = require('selenium-webdriver/firefox');  const seleniumServer = new SeleniumServer('./vendor/selenium-server-standalone.jar', {   args: ['-debug'],   stdio: 'inherit' });  seleniumServer.start(); const profile = new firefox.Profile(); profile.setPreference("browser.download.folderList", 2);  const options = new firefox.Options().setProfile(profile);  const driver = new webdriver.Builder()   .usingServer(seleniumServer.address())   .withCapabilities({     browserName: 'firefox',     name:        require('os').hostname + ': ' + new Date().toLocaleString()   }).   setFirefoxOptions(options).   build(); ```  From the debug output: ``` 23:54:10.194 DEBUG - http-outgoing-0 >> "{"desiredCapabilities":{"browserName":"firefox","name":"function getHostname() { [native code] }: 2017-8-11 23:54:09","moz:firefoxOptions":{"prefs":{"browser.download.folderList":2.0}}}}" ```  You can see 2.0 here, so geckodriver dies.  It worked in older selenium, I upgraded it first time in half-year or like that, and got the regression.

column3: Re-render an HTML page with CSS and HTML working

However, the CSS and Javascript, and the links doesn't work anymore. Is there any way I can re-render the page with CSS, Javascript and the links working?       browser = webdriver.PhantomJS(service_log_path='/dev/null')     browser.get('http://www.mdpi.com/')     html_ph = open("phantomjs.html","w")     html_ph.write(browser.page_source.encode('utf-8'))     html_ph.close()

column3: ChromeOptions.setAcceptInsecureCerts(boolean) is missing
column4: OS:  ALL  Selenium Version:  3.6.0  Browser:  Chrome  Browser Version:  ANY  In Selenium 3.6.0 `ChromeDriver(Capabilities)` has been deprecated in favour of `ChromeDriver(ChromeOptions)`. However `ChromeOptions` class is missing `setAcceptInsecureCerts(boolean)` method. The only way to accomplish this functionality currently is to use the deprecated: ``` DesiredCapabilities capabilities = DesiredCapabilities.chrome(); capabilities.setAcceptInsecureCerts(true); ChromeDriver(capabilities); ```

column3: ActionBuilder: Click at offset does not work
column4: OS:   Windows 7 Selenium Version:   2.53.4 / 3.0.7 / 3.4.4 (Assumed to be global since 2 series) Browser:   Any Chrome / IE (Tested 2 chrome and 3 IE) *Likely to be a global bug*  ## Expected Behavior - Command should run (Notice the commented out command which *will* run) Test script passes and driver quits ## Actual Behavior - Command doesn't run, test script throws an error  ## Steps to reproduce - ``` require 'selenium-webdriver' @driver = Selenium::WebDriver.for :internet_explorer @driver.get('https://the-internet.herokuapp.com/horizontal_slider')  el = @driver.find_element(:css, 'input')  sleep 0.5 @driver.action.move_to(el, 10, 0).click.perform #won't work #sleep 0.5 #Uncomment this line to make script pass #@driver.action.move_to(el).move_by(10, 0).click.perform #will work #Uncomment this line to make script pass  ans = @driver.find_element(:css, '#range').text raise ArgumentError, 'Should not occur' if ans == '0' @driver.quit ```

column3: Unable to Update Maven Project with Selenium Java 3.4.0, facing NullPointerException in Maven Build and Update
column4: OS:   Windows 10 Pro 64-bit 14.393 Selenium Version:   Java 3.4.0 Browser:   N/A IDE: Eclipse Neon .3  Since the release of Selenium Java 3.4.0 client, I have been trying to pull the Maven Dependency for Selenium Java 3.4.0:  	    org.seleniumhq.selenium 	    selenium-java 	    3.4.0   While I was able to create a clean Maven package, every time I attempted to update the project, I have received a NullPointException:  ![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/23008759/25354851/9824cbf4-2902-11e7-8109-73a18a1763a2.png)  Since my IDE displays no other logs, I am unable to pinpoint the cause of this issue. I have tried deleting the metadata,, .settings, and .project folders/file and re imported the Maven project, but still faced the same issue.   There were times that I have received a NullPointerException even while the Maven build was successful, but I am unable to find a root cause since there were no stack traces:  ![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/23008759/25355116/8b88492e-2903-11e7-8e69-dbfefd53293b.png)  Please note that I have reverted to Selenium Java 3.3.1 and even 3.2.0, but I have not received this error when I tried to update the project.

column3: Leftover processes when aborting rspec
column4: OS:   Mac OS Selenium Version:   2.6.0 Browser:   Chrome  Using with `rspec` and `capybara`. When stopping specs with `Ctrl+C` the rspec shuts down gracefully but `chromedriver` process doesn't and we end up with leftover `chromedriver` and `Google Chrome` processes. We didn't have similar issues with `poltergeist` and `phantomjs` so I thought this might be something to do with `selenium`. Please let me know if I should report this to another team.

column3: Selenium Grid - Specified number of threads not getting fully occupied
column4: OS:   - Linux Suse11  Selenium Version:   - 2.53.1  Test environment:  - Selenium Grid v2.53.1 - Ruby, Cucumber, Remotewebdriver with http::persistent client - Browser Version:  Chrome v55+ (Current version 60.0.3112.90)  I have specified the number of threads as 20 for 300 test cases. When the test run starts it occupies all the 20 threads and completes over 270+ test cases, after that the thread occupancy is getting reduced to very few and by the end it is running with single thread.  This is the same case irrespective of number of threads, where the last 10% of the tests are occupied with minimum number of threads even though there are more test cases to run than the number_of_threads.  ## Expected Behavior - If the total number of tests are more than given number_of_threads, then it should occupy all the available threads to run.

column3: Selenium IDE is not compatible with Firefox 55
column4: Mozilla claimed (https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/Add-ons/Installing_extensions)  > From Firefox 57 onwards, WebExtensions will be the only supported extension type, and Firefox will not load other types. >  > Even before Firefox 57, changes coming up in the Firefox platform will break many legacy extensions. These changes include multiprocess Firefox (e10s), sandboxing, and multiple content processes. Legacy extensions that are affected by these changes should migrate to WebExtensions if they can.  Yes, this happened to Selenium IDE too, it does not work in Firefox 55+  This issue is created to mark all other Selenium IDE issues that are related to FF 55+ as duplicates of this one.  I'm going to keep it open until we can provide an alternative solution, a capture-n-replay tool implemented as a WebExtentsion compatible with newest Firefox versions.

column3: NPE in standalone-chrome when setting `implicitlyWait`
column4: Moving an issue created by @phtrivier in the docker-selenium repo on [Jun 15 2017 17:48 GMT+2](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/docker-selenium/issues/500)  ## Meta - Image(s):   * standalone-node Docker-Selenium Image Version(s):   * 3.4.0 OS:  * ubuntu 17.04   ## Expected Behavior -  * Start the image locally   ``` docker run -d -p 4444:4444 selenium/standalone-chrome:3.4.0-dysprosium ```  * Set env variable to test npm `selenium` package to use the image  ``` export SELENIUM_REMOTE_URL=http://localhost:4444/wd/hub ```  * Run a very basic script that just creates a driver  ``` var webdriver = require('selenium-webdriver'); var chromeCapabilities = webdriver.Capabilities.chrome(); var driver = new webdriver.Builder().withCapabilities(chromeCapabilities).build(); driver.manage().timeouts().implicitlyWait(2000); ```  * The last line (setting `implicitlyWait`) triggers an NPE in the image:   ``` 15:42:05.668 WARN - Exception thrown java.lang.NullPointerException 	at org.openqa.selenium.remote.server.handler.ConfigureTimeout.setJsonParameters(ConfigureTimeout.java:39) 	at org.openqa.selenium.remote.server.rest.ResultConfig.handle(ResultConfig.java:99) 	at org.openqa.selenium.remote.server.JsonHttpCommandHandler.handleRequest(JsonHttpCommandHandler.java:190) 	at org.openqa.selenium.remote.server.DriverServlet.handleRequest(DriverServlet.java:222) 	at org.openqa.selenium.remote.server.DriverServlet.doPost(DriverServlet.java:184) 	at javax.servlet.http.HttpServlet.service(HttpServlet.java:707) 	at org.openqa.selenium.remote.server.DriverServlet.service(DriverServlet.java:150) 	at javax.servlet.http.HttpServlet.service(HttpServlet.java:790) 	at org.seleniumhq.jetty9.servlet.ServletHolder.handle(ServletHolder.java:841) 	at org.seleniumhq.jetty9.servlet.ServletHandler.doHandle(ServletHandler.java:543) 	at org.seleniumhq.jetty9.server.handler.ScopedHandler.nextHandle(ScopedHandler.java:188) 	at org.seleniumhq.jetty9.server.handler.ContextHandler.doHandle(ContextHandler.java:1228) 	at org.seleniumhq.jetty9.server.handler.ScopedHandler.nextScope(ScopedHandler.java:168) 	at org.seleniumhq.jetty9.servlet.ServletHandler.doScope(ServletHandler.java:481) 	at org.seleniumhq.jetty9.server.handler.ScopedHandler.nextScope(ScopedHandler.java:166) 	at org.seleniumhq.jetty9.server.handler.ContextHandler.doScope(ContextHandler.java:1130) 	at org.seleniumhq.jetty9.server.handler.ScopedHandler.handle(ScopedHandler.java:141) 	at org.seleniumhq.jetty9.server.handler.HandlerWrapper.handle(HandlerWrapper.java:132) 	at org.seleniumhq.jetty9.server.Server.handle(Server.java:564) 	at org.seleniumhq.jetty9.server.HttpChannel.handle(HttpChannel.java:320) 	at org.seleniumhq.jetty9.server.HttpConnection.onFillable(HttpConnection.java:251) 	at org.seleniumhq.jetty9.io.AbstractConnection$ReadCallback.succeeded(AbstractConnection.java:279) 	at org.seleniumhq.jetty9.io.FillInterest.fillable(FillInterest.java:112) 	at org.seleniumhq.jetty9.io.ChannelEndPoint$2.run(ChannelEndPoint.java:124) 	at org.seleniumhq.jetty9.util.thread.QueuedThreadPool.runJob(QueuedThreadPool.java:672) 	at org.seleniumhq.jetty9.util.thread.QueuedThreadPool$2.run(QueuedThreadPool.java:590) 	at java.lang.Thread.run(Thread.java:748) ```  ## Actual Behavior -  It does not seem like the error prevents the test from working, but it pollutes log, and I suspect it means I'm doing something wrong.    ======= Additional debug info from @diemol  At the beginning I thought it was related to the [deprecation](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/selenium-3.4.0/javascript/node/selenium-webdriver/lib/webdriver.js#L1576) of `driver.manage().timeouts().implicitlyWait(2000);`, but the same behaviour is seen by using `driver.manage().setTimeouts({implicit: 2000});`.   This happens when I used the `selenium/standalone-chrome:3.4.0-dysprosium` and also when I start a Selenium standalone with `java -jar selenium-server-standalone-3.4.0.jar -role standalone`.  The JS code I used to reproduce this issue was:  ``` var webdriver = require('selenium-webdriver'),     By = webdriver.By,     until = webdriver.until; var chromeCapabilities = webdriver.Capabilities.chrome(); var driver = new webdriver.Builder().withCapabilities(chromeCapabilities).build(); driver.manage().setTimeouts({implicit: 2000}); driver.get('http://www.google.com/ncr'); driver.findElement(By.name('q')).sendKeys('webdriver'); driver.findElement(By.name('btnG')).click(); driver.wait(until.titleIs('webdriver - Google Search'), 1000); driver.quit(); ```  Dependencies: ```   "dependencies": {     "selenium-webdriver": "^3.4.0"   } ```  And I executed the code with this command:  ``` SELENIUM_REMOTE_URL="http://localhost:4444/wd/hub" node simple-test.js ```

column3: Take screenshot is taken immediately
column4: It seems like the method `.takeScreenshot` on `selenium-webdriver` on nodejs/npm is being executed immediately and is not waiting until other actions is being finished.  ```ts  this.driver.findElement(By.id(nameOrText)).sendKeys(text as any).then(() => {     console.log('sended keys'); }); this.driver.takeScreenshot()                 .then((pageScreenshot) => {                     console.log('taken screenshot')                     screenshotSource = pageScreenshot;                 }); ```  The string `taken screenshot` is sometimes printed before the string `sended keys`.  I use Selenium Grid for my tests using this Docker container https://github.com/elgalu/docker-selenium.

column3: Add temporary iOS platform to aid W3C migration
column4: In some cases we cannot consider platform and platformName to be equivalent. For example, SauceLabs uses platformName and not platform to run Appium tests. If we override platformName (iOS) with platform (Mac, because no iOS platform exists), we generate a set of invalid capabilities to actually run the browser test.  Fixes #4557  - [X] By placing an `X` in the preceding checkbox, I verify that I have signed the [Contributor License Agreement](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#step-6-sign-the-cla)

column3: Improvement: liveness and readiness endpoint
column4: In order to run selenium reliably in Kubernetes it needs a _liveness_ and _readiness_ endpoint.  The **/liveness** endpoint is used to see if the hub itself is healthy. If it doesn't respond with 200 OK the application gets killed and restarted. This should explicitly not take any dependencies - like the node health - into account.  The **/readiness** endpoint determines whether an application is ready to serve traffic. In this case it might make sense to take the health of the dependencies into account. Again it expects a 200 OK, in which case the application pod is added to a _service_ - effectively a load balancer - and removed from it as long as it returns another status code. However it doesn't lead to any application restarts.  For either endpoint it shouldn't tax the application too much, because it will be requested frequently.

column3: Suggestion: Add export to nightwatch function
column4: I'd like the seleniumide to be able to export the code to nightwatch also. Non-developers would be able to click together tests for all kinds of browers and setups after devs have setup nightwatch, magellan and sauce.  Of course if this is not a good Idea to include directly, one could start a separate project.  What do you guys think?

(Original issue: https://github.com/appium/appium/issues/8927)  ## Meta - OS:  iOS - Hybrid application Selenium Version:  3.5.1 Browser:  iOS Hybrid Web App - Safari? Browser Version:  iOS Version - 10.3.2  ## Expected Behavior - I should be able to SendKeys to an element with the **contenteditiable** attribute.  ## Actual Behavior -  When I use SendKeys to an element with the **contenteditable** attribute on iOS (using Appium) I get the following error:  ``` Message: System.Reflection.TargetInvocationException : Exception has been thrown by the target of an invocation.   ----> System.InvalidOperationException : An unknown server-side error occurred while processing the command. Original error: Error while executing atom: Cannot set the selection end (status: 13) ```  ## Steps to reproduce -  From what I've seen online, this is caused when trying to SendKeys to an element which has the 'contenteditable' attribute. I'm assuming this is an iOS issue, since the test works fine on Android. column3: Backward compatible error codes
column4: I haven't investigated to see if other bindings have this issue, so I'm marking it C-rb, but we should verify it is addressed on all bindings before closing it.  When running tests on Firefox through a remote server, the new w3c errors are getting translated in the server, but not properly handled in the bindings.  Essentially we need to implement all of the "new" error codes that have been added here: https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/java/client/src/org/openqa/selenium/remote/ErrorCodes.java  I'm also marking it as easy because this makes an excellent "fix a bug become a committer" item.

column3: Chrome tracing stops after first access to “.logs()”
column4: I have set up tracing on Selenium. I am able to access the trace the first time. However, in the middle of the test if I access the performance logs once, then all subsequent performance logs do not contain the trace information .   Accessing the logs via the following API: ``` driver.manage().logs().get(LogType.PERFORMANCE) ```  I followed the instructions [here](https://sites.google.com/a/chromium.org/chromedriver/logging/performance-log) which states, however it doesn't seem to be working as described:  > Collecting trace events can add overhead to a test, so ChromeDriver only collects trace events at appropriate points during a test. Currently, trace events are only collected on page navigation events and when any **ChromeDriver log (e.g. the performance log) is requested**. There is always a possibility that the buffer will still fill, so ChromeDriver monitors the buffer usage for supported Chrome versions (r263512 and later). If the buffer fills, ChromeDriver will log a warning and will add an entry to the performance log, as described below.   ## Meta OS:  OSX Selenium Version:  3.5.1 Browser:  Chrome Browser Version:  60  ## Behavior - enable tracing - visit page 1 - getLogs (the cpu profiler information is accessible here) - click a UI element - getLogs (no cpu profiler information, only network logs are seen)  ## Behavior with Code ```groovy def run() {    def driver = getDriverWithTracing();        driver.get("https://yahoo.com");    getTrace(); // has all the CPU traces    driver.clickButton(); // this click does not change the URL but runs some JavaScript code    getTrace(); // has no CPU traces < --- how can we fetch all the logs here?    driver.get("https://yahoo.com")    getTrace(); // has all the CPU traces }  def getTrace() {    JSONArray list = new JSONArray()      for (LogEntry entry : driver.manage().logs().get(LogType.PERFORMANCE)) {       JSONObject object = new JSONObject(entry.getMessage())       list.put(((JSONObject) object.get("message")).get("params"))     }         return list }  String TRACING_CATEGORIES = String.join(             ",",             "-*",             "devtools.timeline",             "v8.execute",             "disabled-by-default-devtools.timeline",             "disabled-by-default-devtools.timeline.frame",             "toplevel",             "blink.console",             "latencyInfo",             "disabled-by-default-devtools.timeline.stack"     )  def getDriverWithTracing() {    DesiredCapabilities capabilities = DesiredCapabilities.chrome();    ChromeOptions options = new ChromeOptions();    LoggingPreferences logs = new LoggingPreferences();     logs.enable(LogType.PERFORMANCE, Level.ALL);     Map perfLogPrefs = new HashMap();    perfLogPrefs.put("traceCategories", TRACING_CATEGORIES); // comma-separated trace categories     capabilities.setCapability(CapabilityType.LOGGING_PREFS, logs);    options.setExperimentalOption("perfLoggingPrefs", perfLogPrefs);      capabilities.setCapability(ChromeOptions.CAPABILITY, options);     return new ChromeDriver(capabilities); } ```  _NOTE: If I navigate away from the page via. `driver.get()`, then the trace information is populated and accessible._

column4: I am on MacOS and Node v6.9.5   ```js   let webdriver = require('selenium-webdriver');   let firefox = require('selenium-webdriver/firefox');   let profile = new firefox.Profile();   profile.setPreference('browser.download.dir', path.resolve(process.env.HOME + '/cdt_test_data_dir'));   profile.setPreference('browser.helperApps.neverAsk.openFile', MIME_TYPES.join(','));   profile.setPreference('browser.helperApps.neverAsk.saveToDisk', MIME_TYPES.join(','));   profile.setPreference('browser.download.manager.showWhenStarting', false);   profile.setPreference('pdfjs.disabled', true);    let opts = new firefox.Options().setProfile(profile);    let driver = new Builder()   .forBrowser('firefox')   .usingServer('http://localhost:4444/wd/hub')   .setFirefoxOptions(opts)   .build(); ```  for some reason Firefox is downloading the file to ~/Downloads, but it should be downloaded to ~/cdt_test_data_dir.  Any idea what might be wrong?

column3: [rb] Create crazy-fun task for ruby linter
column4: Hi, @p0deje.  I created new crazy-fun task for to execute rubocop. I updated .travis.yml so that it can be run on TravisCI. In https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/pull/4746, @p0deje taught me steps to execute rubocop with CI. I actually did it (the following steps).  > @RustyNail The short version of how you can add it: > 1. Add development dependency to rb/selenium-webdriver.gemspec. > 1. Add new crazy-fun mapping to rake-tasks/crazy_fun/mappings/ruby.rb (you can read more about crazy-fun build system on wiki). This mapping would add RubyLinter class that accepts the list of files and simply passes it to bundle exec rubocop. > 1. Use this new crazy-fun task in rb/build.desc. > 1. Verify it with ./go //rb:lint. > 1. Add //rb:lint to the list of tasks executed on Travis. > Let me know if something is not clear here. We can either discuss in this PR or hop on IRC and chat.  Some warning appears when looking at rubocop execution results. In this pull request, I considering changing only to execute rubocop with CI. When this pull request is merged, I intend to propose a response that makes the lint test succeed.   Ref:  https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/pull/4746#issuecomment-332097810  ----  - [x] By placing an `X` in the preceding checkbox, I verify that I have signed the [Contributor License Agreement](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#step-6-sign-the-cla)

column3: Firefox Timeout not configurable. (Firefox v46)
column4: Hi,  I am currently using Selenium 2.5.3 to automate test cases. The code has implicit and explicit timeouts set to be configurable after the driver is loaded. When i am using firefox however, it is not taking any of these timeouts into picture. The only timeout it is taking is the timeout that we hard code in the constructor when we load the driver: webDriver = new FirefoxDriver(new FirefoxBinary(), new FirefoxProfile(), new System.TimeSpan(0, 2, 0)); If we remove this hard coded value altogether so that the implicit and explicit timeout can be set later, it is not taking the other timeouts and is instead taking a default of 60 seconds as the timeout no matter what value we are setting later. Can someone please help me with this issue?

column3: Boolean returns exception instead of false using Any() on Safari Webdriver with Selenium Server 3.3.1 if object not present
column4: Hi,  When I try to run my Selenium tests (I am using Sauce Labs environment) on Safari pointing to seleniumVersion 3.3.1, booleans returns exception instead of "false" if I use "Any()" in C# when the object is not available. The desired capabilities are as follows: SetCapability("seleniumVersion", "3.3.1"); SetCapability("platform", "macOS 10.12");  For simplicity, I have created a simple google test as I can reproduce it with that as well, just copy paste in Visual Studio and run it (provided you have Selenium and webdriver/s from nuget): Please note that in my test I am using inheritance from "Helper Page" which has got my Sauce Labs config, You can try running this on local Safari webdriver setup if you have or on sauce labs. column3: Option for not resolving DNS (keeping hostname in URL) for remote connection ?
column4: Hi,  My company uses the PaaS Open Shift. So basically there are multiples DNS for the same IP address. The service distinguishes requests with the DNS in the message. I deployed a hub and a node with [SeleniumHQ/docker-selenium](SeleniumHQ/docker-selenium), on the PaaS (Open Shift).  On the other hand, I found that Selenium has chosen to get and use the IP address of the server, for performance purposes (this commit for instance : 2b10d56c).  So, when I try to access the hub server, through the python library, the server refuses my requests. For instance with openshift : ``` WebDriverException: Message: [...] Application is not available       The application is currently not serving requests at this endpoint. It may not have been started or is still starting. ```  Should an option be added somewhere, so that the hostname is kept ? Or did I missed it ?  I temporary (and in an ugly way) resolved the problem for my configuration, by changing the `self._url = remote_server_addr` of ` selenium/py/selenium/webdriver/remote/remote_connection.py` into : ```python #self._url = remote_server_addr self._url = "http://myaddr/wd/hub" ``` (yes it bypasses all the preceding processes)  I'm available to add any missing information, if needed.  ## Meta - OS:   Debian Selenium Version:   (python) `selenium==2.53.6` Browser: Selenium Hub  Selenium Hub Version:   Selenium build info: version: '3.4.0', revision: 'unknown'  ## Expected Behavior - Connect to the hub with the URL.  ## Actual Behavior - Connection fails, because direct messages to IP address are forbidden on the server.  ## Steps to reproduce - Install a hub on a server, behind a firewall/proxy where connections to the IP are refused. Connect to the remote hub with the python library.  *Edit* : The trouble as I understood it :  ```                                               +--OpenShift PaaS---------------------------+ +Local debian machine-+                       |                                           | |                     |                       |                       +----------------+  | | +-----------------+ | hostname:80  +-OpenShift Routes :---------+   |Selenium Hub    |  | | |Selenium modified+---------------->http://host:80 -> HubIP:4444+-->+Docker Container|  | | |python library   | |              +----------------------------+   +----------------+  | | +-----------------+ |                       |                               ^           | |                     |                       |                               v           | | +-----------------+ | IP_addr:80   \ /      |                       +----------------+  | | |Selenium default +---------------->X       |                       |Selenium Node   |  | | |python library   | |              / \      |                       |Docker Container|  | | +-----------------+ |                       |                       +----------------+  | +---------------------+                       +-------------------------------------------+ ```

column3: Documentation for selenium-webdriver ... shortcomings
column4: Hi Guys,   There is a fundamental difference on how  "selenium-webdriver" npm module works compared to other popular webdriver javascript implementations wd.js or webdriverIO. And although users are aware of advantages/ disadvantages of different api styles, there isn't much knowledge among users on what's the fundamental difference.  Eg. when you use "selenium-webdriver" you do not need to manage a standalone instance of selenium server (when every other webDriver implementation requires you to have it). This is something "selenium-webdriver" should take pride in, and expose in its documentation. Questions like these could be answered: * Does the node process communicate with browser driver directly?  * Whats thats the performance implication. * Whats the maintenance implication.  If there other fundamental differences, it'll be nice to document.  At the moment we get a very mixed/incomplete perception of "selenium-webdriver": [Stackoverflow - differences (and when to use) selenium-webdriver over webdriverjs?](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/21609040/what-are-the-differences-and-when-to-use-selenium-webdriver-over-webdriverjs).  Can we update documentation to clarify this?

column3: return overlapping element instead of unknown error
column4: Hello, there is a well known scrolling issue with sticky headers/footers or other elements overlapping the element we want to click. #1687 and #1740 explain the issue well.  At the moment selenium is returning a generic error that is not so helpful if one wants to automatically workaround such occurrences. It would be more useful if there is a special error type when this happens and the overlapping element to be extractable from the exception object. For example:  ``` begin   browser.find_element(...).click rescue WebDriver::Error::OverlappingElementError => e   el = e.overlapping_element   # some processing to scroll past `el` margins end ```  ## Meta - OS:  all Selenium Version:  selenium-webdriver-3.5.1 / ruby Browser:  Firefox Browser Version: 52ESR    ## Expected Behavior - ``` Selenium::WebDriver::Error::OverlappingElementError: ... error.overlapping_element -> # ``` ## Actual Behavior - ``` # ```  ## Steps to reproduce - see #1740

column3: Actions.keyDown doesn't work in IE driver, cannot make Ctrl+Click. RequireWindowFocus and Robot are not appropriate
column4: Hello, all.  Problem: Actions Chain 'Pressing a key -> clicking the element -> releasing the key' behaves as there is no pressing a key in Internet Explorer. ``` System.setProperty("webdriver.ie.driver", "C:\iedriverserver.exe"); WebDriver driver = new InternetExplorerDriver(); driver.get("http://seleniumhq.org/")  WebElement element = driver.find_element(By.LINK_TEXT,"Selenium WebDriver") new Actions(driver)     .keyDown(Keys.LEFT_CONTROL)     .click(element)     .keyUp(Keys.LEFT_CONTROL)     .build().perform(); ``` Expected result: Link is opened in a new tab. Actual result: Link is opened in the same tab (click was applied without Ctrl).  I know that there were many the same issue reports, i.e. https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium-google-code-issue-archive/issues/3734  I know possible **workarounds**: RequireWindowFocus capability and awt.Robot. I'd underline what it's not a fix, just workaround. Unfortunately, it doesn't appropriate for our project. We have many UI autotests (about 1500 TestNG methods), they run about 20 hours. We run our autotests with Jenkins and slave virtual machines. And these both workarounds doesn't work then **VM is disconnected** (usual situation, we cannot hold connection for long time). RequireWindowFocus on disconnected VM blocks all the clicks: **VM doesn't have GUI**, and IE driver cannot make any clicks. awt.Robot doesn't work **without GUI** too. Click is just processed without Ctrl (expected multiple elements selected, but clicks are applied to elements one by one, and in the end only the last element selected).  Please help to address this issue. Let me know if you need additional information.  Win 7/8/10 Java JDK 1.8.0_131 Selenium 2.53.1 IE driver 3.3.0.0 IE browser: 11.962.10586.0

column3: Introduce IE::Options class
column4: From now on all the customization of Internet Explorer driver (e.g. cli args, native events, element scroll behavior, etc.) should happen via this class. See documentation of this class for more information.  Please note that Options class is designed to work with IEDriverServer 3.5+ and is likely to behave incorrectly with older versions.  Kudos to @lmtierney who started the implementation in https://github.com/lmtierney/selenium/tree/ie-options, I mostly finalized it.

column3: ActionSequence seems to fail if control flow is off
column4: For the selenium-webdriver JavaScript bindings:  Creating an ActionSequence with multiple actions does not correctly perform the actions in order i the control flow is turned off. For example:  ```js webdriver.actions()     .mouseMove(foo)     .mouseUp()     .mouseDown()     .perform() ```  will occasionally perform the actions out of order.  I think this is due to `ActionSequence.perform()` relying on `Promise.all()` to manage its queue of `actions_`, instead of explicitly chaining them.   See https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/javascript/node/selenium-webdriver/lib/actions.js#L123

column3: made interfacesToBeProxied Lazy in order to become thread-safe
column4: Fixing concurrency issue in interfacesToBeProxied   Sometimes a `System.InvalidOperationException : Collection was modified` could be raised due to concurrency issues. The property InterfacesToBeProxied was made Lazy to overcome this issue. column3: Disconnect stdin from service process
column4: Fixes service eating characters from stdin - e.g. when a debugger is attached to stdin  This was affecting while using Python's `pdb` with the PhantomJS driver, with the the service running in the background.  Admittedly I have not tested this with other drivers, but it should not break anything - an open stdin descriptor is still presented to the process (c.f. closed descriptor).  - [X] By placing an `X` in the preceding checkbox, I verify that I have signed the [Contributor License Agreement](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#step-6-sign-the-cla)

column3: [js] fix driver.build() not returning thenable driver except for Chrome and Firefox
column4: fixes https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/issues/4268  [ChromeDriver.createSession](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/javascript/node/selenium-webdriver/chrome.js#L719) works, because it passes its reference to the super `createSession` and hence the reference to the `thenableWebDriverProxy` persists.  The issue seems to be that [WebDriver.createSession](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/javascript/node/selenium-webdriver/lib/webdriver.js#L765) does not pass itself and therefore the reference is lost and `WebDriver` is used instead of the thenable version. The returned driver does not have a `then` method and causes errors.  - [x] By placing an `X` in the preceding checkbox, I verify that I have signed the [Contributor License Agreement](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#step-6-sign-the-cla)
