column3: IEDriver giving intermittent jasmine spec timed out errors
column4: Firstly, sorry if this should be posted on stack overflow since it follows more the Q&A format, but I have already tried there a few times and not had any useful response, so I thought I would give here a go.  I am having a hard time trying to get tests that run fine on Chrome to run in a stable manner on IE.  I have followed the required configuration steps in your own documentation for IEDriver and I have the 32bit version of IEDriver also installed. I found the steps needed to setup the protected zones and add the registry key was all I needed to get IE to launch and for the tests to begin.  When running the tests I am often seeing intermittent time out related errors like so:  `A Jasmine spec timed out. Resetting the WebDriver Control Flow.`  I have not been able to get any test runs to perform without seeing these errors crop up. I have never see this with Chromedriver.  I have seen some talk of just increasing timeout settings in the protractor config but this just feels like a magic number approach to me.  I am unsure what else to try right now, so thought I'd ask here to see what others may have done to help them past such issues.  One thing I did come across in a post elsewhere was how Chrome is more 'forgiving' with promises and that to get them to behave with IE, chaining then() callbacks on promises helped. This doesnt make sense to me, since from what I have read about the webdriver control flow chaining like so shouldnt be required. Having said that I noticed on the BrowserStack documentation, they share a snippet of how a protractor test can look [here](https://www.browserstack.com/automate/protractor), where they nest the promises.  Can anyone from the Selenium team offer any advice on further things to try? Thanks  (I am currently using protractor version 5.1.1)

column3: Firefox doesn't return Browser Version
column4: FF: 53.0.2 Gecko: 16.1 Selenium 3.0 Platform: C#  I'm using: var capabilities = ((RemoteWebDriver) driver).Capabilities; _returnValue = capabilities.Version;  To get the version of the running browser. With Chrome and phantomjs it works perfectly fine. But with FF it returns an empty string.  Is there a different way to do this now with Gecko?  PS: I already checked with the Geckodriver Team and they say that the version is returned in the capabilities.  Thank you Dan

column3: Selenium Chrome remote webdriver not  support mobile emulation with touch actions
column4: Does the Selenium Chrome remote webdriver support mobile emulation with touch actions or gestures? I got the following exception when running touch actions on a Selenium grid.  System.InvalidOperationException:  Underlying driver does not implement advanced user interactions yet. Obviously the exception says no, but I want to know if this is not because of a implementation mistake I made.  I basically have the following code:  RemoteTouchScreen touch = new RemoteTouchScreen(WebDriver as RemoteWebDriver);  touch.Down(startX, startY); //exception thrown touch.Up(endX, startY); if the WebDriver is of type ChromeDriver, which runs locally it works perfectly. If I use the RemoteWebDriver class it fails with the mentioned exception.  Both the drivers have mobile emulation enabled which I can see working in both situations.  Used .Net Selenium Client & WebDriver Language Bindings Used Selenium server: selenium-server-standalone-2.53.1.jar

column3: Node JS selenium-testing before/after test hooks fail when provided with descriptions
column4: Descriptions on `before` / `after` method hooks exposed in the Node.js `selenium-testing` module result in test failure due to `before` / `after` method hooks only possessing a single argument for the callback function, rather than two as in the case of `describe` or `it` methods.  Lack of support for descriptions results in hook failure being difficult to debug.  Looking at the source, this appears to be a pretty simple fix -  Was there a reason for this change or would you consider a pull request to bring these hooks in line with the other mocha hooks?

column3: Propagate altered DC to Node
column4: Currently the grid logic is such that if a particular test’s capabilities are altered via an overloaded version of   * DefaultRemoteProxy#getNewSession * DefaultRemoteProxy#beforeSession  the expectation is that the altered capabilities are what gets forwarded to the actual node prior to an actual session creation on the node. But  this doesn’t happen because the altered desired  capabilities are not being considered. Fixed this.  - [X] By placing an `X` in the preceding checkbox, I verify that I have signed the [Contributor License Agreement](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#step-6-sign-the-cla)

column3: Warn if path provided by the user to screenshot-taking method has non-png extension
column4: Currently most of client libraries support taking screenshot only in PNG format. Only [.NET is able to convert a screenshot to some other format](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/1e221937594c8ac4895899024927575aa6015a60/dotnet/src/webdriver/Screenshot.cs).  ## Actual Behavior Screenshot methods defined in most client libraries do not warn if path provided by the user has non-PNG extension. There are multiple cases where users wrote code that actually does it (see "Steps to reproduce"). I think they expected a screenshot to be saved in the format specified by the path extension.  ## Expected Behavior It would be better if screenshot-taking methods outputted a warning if path provided by the user has an extension but this extension (after being downcased) is not ".png". A warning should tell that despite a path ends with e.g. ".jpg", image will be saved in PNG format.  ## Steps to reproduce https://stackoverflow.com/a/24445213/841064 https://github.com/watir/watir/issues/400 http://artoftesting.com/automationTesting/screenShotInSelenium.html http://www.softqe.com/capture-screenshot-using-selenium-webdriver/ http://www.ufthelp.com/2015/01/screenshot-using-selenium.html https://community.perfectomobile.com/posts/1055085-sample-script-screenshot-python  cc @titusfortner

column3: webdriver/remote/errorhandler.py doesn't match what the spec defines
column4: Comparing the error codes in https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/3de9df1630e574607aa703c22c2a4b8770a9523d/py/selenium/webdriver/remote/errorhandler.py and in https://w3c.github.io/webdriver/webdriver-spec.html#handling-errors (as of 6e6575c), the Python code is missing the following error codes:   * element click intercepted  * insecure certificate  * invalid argument  * invalid coordinates  * invalid session id  * no such cookie  * session not created  * unable to capture screen  * unknown method  The Python code also has the following that don't appear in the spec:   * element not visible  * ime engine activation failed  * ime not available  * invalid element coordinates

column3: Improper Handshake formatting in 3.5
column4: C# bindings appear to be sending non-backward compatible JSON in the recent 3.5 release (from NuGet).  I'm still trying to get more information about the code used to generate this, but the JSON I'm getting from the remote end looks like this:  ``` {       "capabilities": {         "alwaysMatch": {           "platform": "Windows 10",           "browserName": "firefox",           "version": "53",           "seleniumVersion": "3.5.0"         },         "firstMatch": []       },       "desiredCapabilities": {         "browserName": "firefox",         "firefox_profile": ,         "marionette": true       }     } ``` and ``` {       "capabilities": {         "alwaysMatch": {           "platform": "windows 10",           "browserName": "MicrosoftEdge",           "version": "14.14393",           "seleniumVersion": "3.5.0"         },         "firstMatch": []       },       "desiredCapabilities": {         "browserName": "MicrosoftEdge",         "proxy": {           "proxyAutoconfigUrl": ,           "proxyType": "PAC"         }       } ```  I would expect all of this information to be passed into desiredCapabilities not just capabilities through Selenium 4.0.  @jimevans please let me know what additional information you need from me on this to help troubleshoot. Learning the .NET bindings is on my to do list, but I don't have any experience with them still. :) Thanks!

column3: Missing Python bindings for Chrome network emulation
column4: Analogically to JS bindings prepared in #3624 and committed in d7bdd7cc, Python bindings are missing the Chrome debugging protocol functionality for getting and setting network emulation settings. This functionality was added to ChromeDriver in March of 2015 (https://chromium.googlesource.com/chromium/src.git/+/12a55ff7369b35adb29cd28f5e3dd4ef923e3e6c).

column3: Implementations of TakesScreenshot not complying with the contract defined in the interface
column4: `TakesScreenshot#getScreenshotAs` states that `@throws WebDriverException on failure`.  But:  - RemoteWebDriver and RemoteWebElement throw RuntimeException in case of Unexpected result from the CommandExecutor  ```     if (result instanceof String) {       String base64EncodedPng = (String) result;       return outputType.convertFromBase64Png(base64EncodedPng);     } else if (result instanceof byte[]) {       String base64EncodedPng = new String((byte[]) result);       return outputType.convertFromBase64Png(base64EncodedPng);     } else {       throw new RuntimeException(String.format("Unexpected result for %s command: %s",           DriverCommand.SCREENSHOT,           result == null ? "null" : result.getClass().getName() + " instance"));     } ```  - EventFiringWebDriver throws UnsupportedOperationException if the underlying driver is not a TakesScreenshot  ```     if (driver instanceof TakesScreenshot) {       return ((TakesScreenshot) driver).getScreenshotAs(target);     }      throw new UnsupportedOperationException(         "Underlying driver instance does not support taking screenshots"); ```  Shouldn't we throw WebDriverException even in those circumstances?  Thanks

column3: it does not work Selenium IDE in firefox 55.0.
column4: :( ## Meta - OS:    Windows 10? OSX Selenium Version:   2.52.0, IDE, etc Browser:   Firefox  Since Firefox version 48, Mozilla requires all add-ons to be signed. Until recently, Firefox support in Selenium was exclusively provided by an add-on. As this add-on is not currently signed, this solution does not work with the latest Firefox releases. As an alternative, Mozilla are working on a WebDriver specification compliant implementation named GeckoDriver. Please note that the specification is not complete, and that Selenium itself does not comply with the specification at this time. This means that features previously available through Selenium will not be available using GeckoDriver.  Any issue logged here for Firefox 48 or later will be closed as a duplicate of #2559. Our recommendation is to switch to GeckoDriver, or to continue testing on Firefox 45 until GeckoDriver is a viable option for you. If you are interested in helping us to sign the add-on to restore support for later Firefox versions, please see the following comment for what's needed: https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/issues/2942#issuecomment-259717567  If the issue is with Google Chrome consider logging an issue with chromedriver instead: https://sites.google.com/a/chromium.org/chromedriver/help  If the issue is with Microsoft Edge consider logging an issue with Microsoft instead: https://developer.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-edge/platform/issues/  If the issue is with Firefox GeckoDriver (aka Marionette) consider logging an issue with Mozilla: https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/buglist.cgi?product=Testing&component=Marionette  If the issue is with Safari, only Safari 10+ is supported. Please log any Safari issue with Apple: https://bugreport.apple.com/  If the issue is with PhantomJS consider logging an issue with Ghostdriver: https://github.com/detro/ghostdriver  -->  Browser Version:     ## Expected Behavior -  ## Actual Behavior -  ## Steps to reproduce -

column3: Add ability to interact with extension actions to C# bindings
column4: - [x] By placing an `X` in the preceding checkbox, I verify that I have signed the [Contributor License Agreement](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#step-6-sign-the-cla)  The following pull request adds the following commands to the Selenium C# language bindings:  - The ability to query for installed browser extensions - The ability to query for the extension actions that each installed browser extension exposes - The ability to invoke these aforementioned actions  It also makes the following infrastructure updates: - Edge-specific tests for the above capabilities - Adds dependency on NUnit3TestAdapter NuGET package  This aligns with new WebDriver commands (specifically `getBrowserExts()`, `getBrowserExtActions()` and `takeBrowserExtAction()` outlined in the [W3C Browser Extensions Community Group spec](https://browserext.github.io/browserext/index.html#wd). Microsoft Edge will support these as of the Creators Update, but I wanted to open this PR early so that feedback could be incorporated ahead of time.   **Note:** This PR must be tested on the Creators Update (build 15063.X)   --- This change is [](https://reviewable.io/reviews/seleniumhq/selenium/3818)

column3: fix file descriptor(/dev/null) leak in chrome webdriver
column4: - [X] By placing an `X` in the preceding checkbox, I verify that I have signed the [Contributor License Agreement](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#step-6-sign-the-cla)  The file descriptor has been leaked in `WebDriver::Chrome::Service` opened here line. https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/rb/lib/selenium/webdriver/chrome/service.rb#L43  This leak cause `Errno::EMFILE: Too many open files` exception in massive test. We have to close this file descriptor.  To error reproduce. (environment: ulimit -a => 1024) ```rb: 2000.times {|n|   d = Selenium::WebDriver.for :chrome  #=> Errno::EMFILE: Too many open files   d.quit } ```  Thank you.

column3: Support for DriverService "run as" username/password
column4: - [X] By placing an `X` in the preceding checkbox, I verify that I have signed the [Contributor License Agreement](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#step-6-sign-the-cla)  Motivation  When creating tests for Windows, there is occasionally a need to run the same test, while switching between different users (like, rung line 1-10 using windows user A, then run line 11-20 using user B, etc). This is useful for testing workflow applications for example, with **integrated** windows security.  To be able to properly test this, one needs to logon different users and re-launch the driver using those. This pull request adds support for launching driver under a specific user (the underlying OS support is already there, it just exposes those fields as optional properties).  We needed this functionality in our project.  Other examples where it may be needed (from stackoverflow):  https://stackoverflow.com/questions/16590207/how-to-impersonate-a-specific-user-with-selenium-webdriver https://stackoverflow.com/questions/28045870/how-can-i-run-internet-explorer-selenium-tests-as-a-specific-domain-user https://stackoverflow.com/questions/9951377/using-impersonation-to-launch-processes-indirectly-in-c-sharp https://sqa.stackexchange.com/questions/2277/using-selenium-webdriver-with-windows-authentication   Usage example:              var service = ChromeDriverService.CreateDefaultService();              service.StartupDomain = "contoso";              service.StartupUserName = "john.doe";              var pwd = new SecureString();             foreach (var c in "P@ssword")                 pwd.AppendChar(c);              service.StartupPassword = pwd;              service.Start();              var options = new ChromeOptions();             options.AddArgument("--no-sandbox");              var driver = new RemoteWebDriver(service.ServiceUrl, options); `

column3: IEDriver: Use a mutex to lock Win32 message handling
column4: - [X] By placing an `X` in the preceding checkbox, I verify that I have signed the [Contributor License Agreement](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#step-6-sign-the-cla)  I use Selenium at work and for our test bed we were having many problems with the IEDriverServer crashing due to a Memory Access Violation.  It got to the point where it was impeding our work, so I cloned the project and ran it in debug mode to see if I could identify the problem.  Our test bed was causing the driver to crash specifically on line 441 of IECommandExecutor.cpp, the inner message handling loop for Win32.  I believe the crash was occurring due to concurrent use of the Win32 APIs by multiple threads, which do not appear to be thread safe.  So I introduced a static mutex shared between threads and had each thread acquire a lock to this mutex before processing messages.  This has worked wonderfully for us, our tests are now much more stable.  I'd like to contribute this fix back to Selenium.  I believe this may have also been the cause for https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/issues/1973 and similar issues.

column3: simulate RETURN instead of button click on Google search page
column4: - [X] By placing an `X` in the preceding checkbox, I verify that I have signed the [Contributor License Agreement](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#step-6-sign-the-cla)  Here's a possible fix for #4491. Instead of finding and simulating a click on the "btnG" button on the Google search page, it simulates pressing the RETURN key in the input field after entering the search term. This works as expected in my testing with selenium-webdriver.  It's possible that there are examples elsewhere in the codebase that try to do the same thing and should also be updated. I can expand my search/replace to the rest of the repository, I only hesitated because selenium-webdriver is the only client I have configured currently.

column3: selenium.common.exceptions.ElementNotInteractableException: Message
column4: **OS:**  Windows 7  **Selenium Version:**  3.4.3  **Browser:**  Firefox ISR and Google Chrome   Hi Guys, I've been reading some issues here and StackOverflow topics but nothing helps yet. So, I'm testing some simple codes for Firefox and Google Chrome and they are a little bit unstable. When I said ''simple codes'' I'm refering about stuff like logon, searchs and open menu with dropdown. Sometimes, when I execute this codes in Firefox I receive this message: _"raise exception_class(message, screen, stacktrace) selenium.common.exceptions.ElementNotInteractableException: Message: "_ or _"selenium.common.exceptions.WebDriverException: Message: Failed to decode response from marionette"_  When I execute in Google Chrome I don't have any problem, but the problem is when I tried to execute again on Firefox, sometimes execute with errors and sometimes I have sucess. I've made some tests using the Selenium IDE, but seens they don't work well with the system what I'm testing here. I know, this errors sound "generic" but I don't understand why are so unstable for simple comands like .send_keys().  **This is an example of my tests:**  `driver = self.driver         driver.get(self.base_url + "mylink")         driver.find_element_by_css_selector("#menu_search").click()         driver.find_element_by_name("name").clear()         driver.find_element_by_name("name").send_keys("grazigs")         driver.find_element_by_name("password").clear()         driver.find_element_by_name("password").send_keys("***")         driver.find_element_by_css_selector("profile_type").click()         driver.find_element_by_css_selector("cyborg:profile_type").click()         driver.find_element_by_xpath("//button[@type='login']").click()         driver.find_element_by_link_text("consult_friends").click()         driver.find_element_by_xpath("(//input[@type='search_box'])[1]").clear()         driver.find_element_by_xpath("(//input[@type='search_box'])[1]").send_keys("my friend")         driver.find_element_by_css_selector("btnSearch").click()         driver.find_element_by_link_text("Best Friend Profile").click()`  Browser Version:  59.0.3071.115 (Google Chrome) and 52.2.1 (Firefox)

column3: IEdriver cannot switch to popup openend from a popup
column4: **OS:  Windows 7 Selenium Version:  3.4.0 Browser:  Internet Explorer (version 11.0.9600.18738 - 32bit)**   When i'm inside a popup and open another popup from that window, it will not be able to "see" this popup and the driver will freeze when trying to switch to it.  When using the following code to handle the switching it works fine on both chrome and firefox driver:  ``` 	public void getWindow() { 		Set handles = driver.getWindowHandles(); // get all window handles 		for(String test:handles){ 			System.out.println(test); 		} 		Iterator iterator = handles.iterator(); 		parentWindowHandler = iterator.next(); // The parent window is the top window 		while (iterator.hasNext()) { 			subWindowHandler = iterator.next(); 		} 	}  	@When("^switch to popup$") 	public void switch_to_popup() throws Throwable { 		getWindow(); 		System.out.println("switch to popup: " + subWindowHandler); 		driver.switchTo().window(subWindowHandler); 	}  	@When("^switch to mainwindow$") 	public void switch_to_mainwindow() throws Throwable { 		getWindow(); 		driver.switchTo().window(parentWindowHandler); 	} ```

column3: Regarding: HTML5 Drag and Drop with Selenium Webdriver #3604
column4: **NOTE:** This is not an issue, but rather a temporary alternative for developers (like myself) whom are looking for their tests to function while this issue remains open. I would have liked to comment on the existing issue, but it has been closed for comments (:-/).  ## Meta - OS:  Ubuntu 16.04 Selenium Version:  PHPUnit_Selenium 5.0.8 - 2015-10-23 Browser:  Chrome  Browser Version:  Version 58.0.3029.110 Built on Ubuntu , running on Ubuntu 16.04 (64-bit)  ## Expected Behavior - As already known, drag and drop events using draggable and droppable attributes/functionality does not function as expected when ran in Laravel's Dusk tests (among others). Running a $browser->drag('#from','#to') from testers should automate dragging the "from" element to the "to" element firing the "dragstart", "dragover", and "drop" events.   ## Actual Behavior - ``` /**      * Drag and drop from $source to $target.      *      * @param WebDriverElement $source      * @param WebDriverElement $target      * @return WebDriverActions      */     public function dragAndDrop(WebDriverElement $source, WebDriverElement $target)     {         $this->action->addAction(             new WebDriverClickAndHoldAction($this->mouse, $source)         );         $this->action->addAction(             new WebDriverMouseMoveAction($this->mouse, $target)         );         $this->action->addAction(             new WebDriverButtonReleaseAction($this->mouse, $target)         );          return $this;     } ```  This behavior, though in theory simulates a drag and drop, actually fires "mousedown" and "mouseup" events rather than the "dragstart", "dragover", and "drop" events.   ## Steps to reproduce - ``` $this->browse(function (Browser $browser) {     $browser->setUp()->visit($this->url)->drag('#element-a', '#element-b'); } ```  ## **Temporary solution** Create events for "mousedown" and "mouseup", on draggable and droppable elements (respectively), that trigger the dragstart and drop events (respectively).   -- Example: Included is a jsfiddle link that provides the code necessary for user driven drag-and-drop as well as the Dusk test drag and drop simulation (though of course the dusk test cannot be ran from it):  [Dusk "testable" Drag and Drop Fiddle](https://jsfiddle.net/grantdscs/nehjrbzo/)  A highlight of the functionality: ```     $("a[draggable='true']").on("mousedown", function(event) {         $(this).trigger("dragstart");     });      $("div[droppable='true']").on("mouseup", function(event) {         $(this).trigger("drop");     }); ```

column3: Selenium hub 3.5.3 ignoring Firefox profile set on DesiredCapabilities
column4: ## System * Version: v0.18.0 * Platform: Windows 7, 64 bit * Firefox: 55.0.3 * Selenium: 3.5.3   ## Testcase   **Test case 1 :**   Setting **network.proxy.type** on FirefoxProfile object to 0, so that the automation test's which run on FF skip's the proxy and doesnt ask for user authentication.  ``` FirefoxProfile fp = new FirefoxProfile(); fp.setPreference("network.proxy.type", 0); DesiredCapabilities capabilities = new DesiredCapabilities(); capabilities.setCapability(FirefoxDriver.PROFILE, fp);   ``` Create remote webdriver using the above capability object and continue with the test `new RemoteWebDriver(new URL(SELENIUM_REMOTE_URL), (capabilities));`   **Test case 2 :**  - Executing firefox.exe -p and create a new Firefox profile **AUTO_PRO** - On browser got to config(about:config) and set **network.proxy.type** to 0  - Set this profile onto the capabilities before creating Remote WebDriver  ``` ProfilesIni profileIni = new ProfilesIni(); FirefoxProfile fp = profileIni.getProfile("AUTO_PRO"); capabilities.setCapability(FirefoxDriver.PROFILE, fp); ```   ## Expected Behaviour: Opened Browser profile should have **network.proxy.type** set to **0** and should skip proxy and connect directly instead.  ## Actual behaviour: Firefox Profile object ignored by Remote node, the firefox browser opened by node creates its own default profile which has **network.proxy.type** set to **5** instead of **0**.   This scenario works fine if i run the test locally instead of running on a remote selenium hub.  Have also  tried with different versions, the last one which correctly picks up the set Firefox profile object is 3.4.0. All the selenium-server-standalone jar's from 3.5.0 ignore's the Firefox profile object's set on capabilities.  I have also tried setting "webdriver.firefox.profile" to the new profile name on the config json and pass the same on the node start up, but even then the profile is ignored.

column3: Selenium 3.5.3-Java-IEDriverServer 3.5.1 : 'platformName' attribute returns "XP" where as W3C Specs mentions either "linux", "mac" or "windows"
column4: ## Selenium 3.5.3-Java-IEDriverServer 3.5.1 : `platformName` attribute returns **`XP`** where as W3C Specs mentions either **`linux`**, **`mac`** or **`windows`**  [W3C Specs](https://w3c.github.io/webdriver/webdriver-spec.html#processing-capabilities) mentions the following:  In chapter [7. Capabilities](https://w3c.github.io/webdriver/webdriver-spec.html#processing-capabilities#x7.-capabilities), section [7.2 Processing Capabilities](https://w3c.github.io/webdriver/webdriver-spec.html#processing-capabilities#x7.2-processing-capabilities): > windows  where as IEDriverServer 3.5.1 returns **`XP`**  As per #4526 and this [comment](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/issues/4526#issuecomment-328199607) latest `IEDriverServer` is w3c compatible. But seems out of sync.  ## Meta - OS:  Windows 8 Pro, 64 bit Selenium Version:  3.5.3 Browser:  Internet Explorer Browser Version:  10.0 (64-bit)  ## Expected Behavior - `platformName` attribute should return either **`linux`**, **`mac`** or **`windows`**  ## Actual Behavior - `platformName` attribute returns **`XP`**  ## Steps to reproduce - Minimal Code Block :  ``` import java.util.Map;  import org.openqa.selenium.Capabilities; import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver; import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeDriver; import org.openqa.selenium.firefox.FirefoxDriver; import org.openqa.selenium.ie.InternetExplorerDriver; import org.openqa.selenium.remote.RemoteWebDriver;  public class WEBDRIVER_platformName { 	public static void main(String[] args)  	{ 		String attribute = "platformName"; 		System.setProperty("webdriver.ie.driver", "C:\\Utility\\BrowserDrivers\\IEDriverServer.exe"); 		WebDriver driver =  new InternetExplorerDriver();                 Capabilities cap = ((RemoteWebDriver) driver).getCapabilities();                 Map map = cap.asMap();                 Object value = map.get(attribute);                 System.out.println("Key : " + attribute + " Value :"+ value);                driver.quit();  	} }  ```  Console Output :  `Key : platformName Value :XP`

column3: Selenium Driver and OpenCV waitKey(0) Segfault
column4: ## Meta - Versions OS:  macOS Sierra 10.12.5  Selenium Version:  3.4.3  Browser:  Firefox, version 55.0 (64-bit)   Browser Version:  55.0 (64-bit)  OpenCV Version: 3.2.0   Python Version: 2.7.13  ## Expected Behavior - OpenCV Show Image I am running the following piece of code in OpenCV 3.2.0 to display an image.  ``` from selenium import webdriver from selenium.webdriver.common.keys import Keys import cv2  cv2.namedWindow('window') img = cv2.imread('my_image.png') cv2.imshow('window', img)  cv2.waitKey(0) ``` This works fine. However, when I add in driver open and close with Selenium, I get a segfault.  The following code produces a segfault.  ``` from selenium import webdriver from selenium.webdriver.common.keys import Keys import cv2  driver = webdriver.Firefox() driver.close()  cv2.namedWindow('window') img = cv2.imread('my_image.png') cv2.imshow('window', img)  cv2.waitKey(0) ```  ## Actual Behavior - Segfault  I get a segfault on `cv2.waitKey(0)`. In case I omit the `driver.close()` no segfault is thrown.  ## Steps to reproduce   Run this code in python  ``` from selenium import webdriver from selenium.webdriver.common.keys import Keys import cv2  driver = webdriver.Firefox() driver.close()  cv2.namedWindow('window') img = cv2.imread('my_image.png') cv2.imshow('window', img)  cv2.waitKey(0) ```

column3: Selenium 3.6.0 (Java client) is unable to navigate to the URL with existing Firefox profile
column4: ## Meta - Selenium 3.6.0 (Java client) is unable to navigate to the URL with existing Firefox profile  OS:  Windows 8 Pro Selenium Version:  3.6.0 Browser:  Mozilla Firefox Browser Version:  56.0 - 64 bit GeckoDriver: v0.19.0  ## Expected Behavior - Selenium 3.6.0 (Java client) should navigate to the URL with existing Firefox profile.  ## Actual Behavior - Selenium 3.6.0 (Java client) doesn't navigate to the URL with existing Firefox profile.  ## Steps to reproduce -  1. Created a Firefox profile through Profile Manager (Mozilla Firefox: 56.0 - 64 bit) as "debanjan" which gets created at "C:\Users\AtechM_03\AppData\Roaming\Mozilla\Firefox\Profiles\l85yv0bu.debanjan"  2. Referred to the [documentation](https://github.com/mozilla/geckodriver#firefox-capabilities) which clearly mentions:  `To have geckodriver pick up an existing profile on the filesystem, you may pass ["-profile", "/path/to/profile"].`  3. Changed my code as follows:  		package demo;  		import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver; 		import org.openqa.selenium.firefox.FirefoxDriver; 		import org.openqa.selenium.firefox.FirefoxOptions;  		public class FirefoxProfile {  			public static void main(String[] args) {  			System.setProperty("webdriver.gecko.driver", "C:\\Utility\\BrowserDrivers\\geckodriver.exe"); 			FirefoxOptions opt = new FirefoxOptions(); 			opt.addArguments("-profile", "C:\\Users\\AtechM_03\\AppData\\Roaming\\Mozilla\\Firefox\\Profiles\\l85yv0bu.debanjan"); 			WebDriver driver = new FirefoxDriver(opt); 			driver.get("https://google.com"); 			} 		}  4. On execution, Mozilla Firefox browser gets initialized but doesn't navigates to the url "https://google.com".  5. Trace Logs :   		1507042822078	geckodriver	INFO	geckodriver 0.19.0 		1507042822097	geckodriver	INFO	Listening on 127.0.0.1:6525 		1507042823284	mozrunner::runner	INFO	Running command: "C:\\Program Files\\Mozilla Firefox\\firefox.exe" "-marionette" "-profile" "C:\\Users\\AtechM_03\\AppData\\Roaming\\Mozilla\\Firefox\\Profiles\\l85yv0bu.debanjan" 		1507042829832	Marionette	INFO	Enabled via --marionette 		1507042850845	Marionette	INFO	Listening on port 2828

column3: Selenium 3.5.2-Java : Documentation mentions available levels for log object are trace, debug, config, info, warn, error, and fatal while Selenium 3.5.2 Java client intelligence provides the following options: All, CONFIG, FINE, FINER, FINEST, INFO, OFF, SEVERE and WARNING
column4: ## Meta - Selenium 3.5.2-Java : [Documentation](https://github.com/mozilla/geckodriver#log-object) mentions available levels for log object are `trace`, `debug`, `config`, `info`, `warn`, `error`, and `fatal` while Selenium 3.5.2 Java client intelligence provides the following options: `All`, `CONFIG`, `FINE`, `FINER`, `FINEST`, `INFO`, `OFF`, `SEVERE` and `WARNING`  ![selenium_java_logging](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/26503213/29995220-fd380fae-9001-11e7-9dd1-525965f17690.png)   OS: Windows 8 Pro, 64 bit  Selenium Version: 3.5.2  Selenium Binding: Java  GeckoDriver Version: 0.18.0  Browser: Mozilla Firefox  Browser Version: 55.0.3  ## Expected Behavior - Documentation of log levels and the client (Java) implementation of the log levels must be identical.  ## Actual Behavior - Documentation of log levels and the client (Java) implementation of the log levels are not identical.  ## Steps to reproduce - Minimum Code:  	package demo;  	import java.util.logging.Level;  	import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver; 	import org.openqa.selenium.firefox.FirefoxDriver; 	import org.openqa.selenium.firefox.FirefoxOptions;  	public class Gecko_TRACE_LOGS  	{ 		public static void main(String[] args)  		{ 			System.setProperty("webdriver.gecko.driver", "C:\\Utility\\BrowserDrivers\\geckodriver.exe"); 			FirefoxOptions options = new FirefoxOptions(); 			options.setLogLevel(Level.OFF); 			WebDriver driver =  new FirefoxDriver(options); 			driver.get("https://stackoverflow.com"); 			System.out.println("Application opened"); 			System.out.println("Page Title is : "+driver.getTitle()); 			driver.quit(); 		} 	}

column3: Selenium 3.5.0: Java and Python client sending different number of capabilities to Marionette
column4: ## Meta - Selenium 3.5.0: Java and Python client sending different number of capabilities to Marionette  When `capabilities` are retrieved through **Java** Client **14** capabilities are retrieved from the **`Map.Entry`** object  through **`Capabilities`** class object by default.  When `capabilities` are retrieved through **Python 3.6.1** Client **12** capabilities are retrieved from the **`Dictionary`** object by default.  --------------------------------------------------  OS: Windows 8 Pro, 64 bit  Selenium Version: 3.5.2  Selenium Binding: Java & Python 3.6.1  GeckoDriver Version: 0.18.0  Browser: Mozilla Firefox  Browser Version: 55.0.2  ## Expected Behavior - Java & Python 3.6.1 Client should send/receive equal number of capabilities to/from Marionette.  ## Actual Behavior - Java & Python 3.6.1 Client send/receive different number of capabilities to/from Marionette.  ## Steps to reproduce -  Minimal Java Code:  ``` package demo;  import java.util.Map; import java.util.logging.Level;  import org.openqa.selenium.Capabilities; import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver; import org.openqa.selenium.firefox.FirefoxDriver; import org.openqa.selenium.firefox.FirefoxOptions; import org.openqa.selenium.remote.RemoteWebDriver;  public class WEBDRIVER_CAPABILITIES_MAP { 	public static void main(String[] args)  	{ 		System.setProperty("webdriver.gecko.driver", "C:\\Utility\\BrowserDrivers\\geckodriver.exe"); 		FirefoxOptions options = new FirefoxOptions(); 		options.setLogLevel(Level.FINEST); 		WebDriver driver =  new FirefoxDriver(options);         Capabilities cap = ((RemoteWebDriver) driver).getCapabilities();         Map map = cap.asMap();         for ( Map.Entry entry : map.entrySet())          {             System.out.println(entry.getKey() + " value is " + entry.getValue());         }         driver.quit();  	} }  ```  Console Output:  ``` moz:profile value is C:\Users\ATECHM~1\AppData\Local\Temp\rust_mozprofile.CrLgYK3noEc9 rotatable value is false timeouts value is {implicit=0, pageLoad=300000, script=30000} pageLoadStrategy value is normal platform value is ANY specificationLevel value is 0 moz:accessibilityChecks value is false acceptInsecureCerts value is false browserVersion value is 55.0.2 platformVersion value is 6.2 moz:processID value is 3604 browserName value is firefox javascriptEnabled value is true platformName value is windows_nt ```  Minimal Python Code:  ``` from selenium import webdriver from selenium.webdriver.firefox.options import Options  binary = r'C:\Program Files\Mozilla Firefox\firefox.exe'  options = Options() options.binary = binary driver = webdriver.Firefox(log_path='./Logs/WEBDRIVER_capabilities.log', firefox_options=options, executable_path="C:\\Utility\\BrowserDrivers\\geckodriver.exe") my_dict = driver.capabilities for key,val in my_dict.items():     print (key, "=>", val) driver.quit(); ```  Console Output:  ``` acceptInsecureCerts => True browserName => firefox browserVersion => 55.0.2 moz:accessibilityChecks => False moz:processID => 3468 moz:profile => C:\Users\ATECHM~1\AppData\Local\Temp\rust_mozprofile.87dcBfBxqQdP pageLoadStrategy => normal platformName => windows_nt platformVersion => 6.2 rotatable => False specificationLevel => 0 timeouts => {'implicit': 0, 'pageLoad': 300000, 'script': 30000} ```  **Python 3.6.1 Client clearly misses `platform` and `javascriptEnabled` capability.**

column3: IEDriverServer.exe (3.5.0.0) with Selenium (3.5.0) doesn't produce any logs when "webdriver.Ie()" contains "log_file='./Logs/IEDriverServer.log'" through Python PyDev (Eclipse)
column4: ## Meta - IEDriverServer.exe (3.5.0.0) with Selenium (3.5.0) doesn't produce any logs when "webdriver.Ie()" contains "log_file='./Logs/IEDriverServer.log'" through Python PyDev (Eclipse)  OS: Windows 8 Pro, 64 bit  Selenium Version: 3.5.0 (Python 3.6.1)  Selenium Binding: Python 3.6.1  IEDriverServer Version: 3.5.0.0  Browser: INTERNETEXPLORER  Browser Version: INTERNETEXPLORER 10.0  ## Expected Behavior -   The documentation for [`"webdriver.Ie()"`](https://seleniumhq.github.io/selenium/docs/api/py/webdriver_ie/selenium.webdriver.ie.webdriver.html#module-selenium.webdriver.ie.webdriver) clearly mentions as follows:      class selenium.webdriver.ie.webdriver.WebDriver(executable_path='IEDriverServer.exe', capabilities=None, port=0, timeout=30, host=None, log_level=None, log_file=value)  So, IEDriverServer.exe (3.5.0.0) with Selenium (3.5.0) should produce expected logs when "webdriver.Ie()" contains "log_file='./Logs/IEDriverServer.log'" through Python PyDev (Eclipse).  ## Actual Behavior - Though the file `IEDriverServer.log` is created during runtime but IEDriverServer.exe (3.5.0.0) with Selenium (3.5.0) doesn't produce any logs when "webdriver.Ie()" contains "log_file='./Logs/IEDriverServer.log'" through Python PyDev (Eclipse)  ## Steps to reproduce - Minimal Code block:  	from selenium import webdriver 	from selenium.webdriver.common.desired_capabilities import DesiredCapabilities  	cap = DesiredCapabilities().INTERNETEXPLORER 	cap['platform'] = "Win8" 	cap['version'] = "10" 	cap['browserName'] = "internet explorer" 	cap['ignoreProtectedModeSettings'] = True 	cap['IntroduceInstabilityByIgnoringProtectedModeSettings'] = True 	cap['nativeEvents'] = True 	cap['ignoreZoomSetting'] = True 	cap['requireWindowFocus'] = True 	cap['INTRODUCE_FLAKINESS_BY_IGNORING_SECURITY_DOMAINS'] = True 	browser = webdriver.Ie(capabilities=cap, executable_path="C:\\Utility\\BrowserDrivers\\IEDriverServer.exe", log_file='./Logs/IEDriverServer.log') 	browser.get('http://google.com/') 	browser.quit()

column3: Selenium 3.5.2-Python 3.6.1 : driver.capabilities['version'] returns KeyError: 'version'
column4: ## Meta - driver.capabilities['version'] returns KeyError: 'version'  OS: Windows 8 Pro, 64 bit  Selenium Version: 3.5.2   Selenium Binding: Python 3.6.1  GeckoDriver Version: 0.18.0  Browser: Mozilla Firefox  Browser Version: 55.0.2  ## Expected Behavior - As per the documentation at [**`JsonWireProtocol`**](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/wiki/JsonWireProtocol)  `version` is a **Capabilities JSON Object** hence `driver.capabilities['version']` must be resolved and return a value.  ## Actual Behavior - driver.capabilities['version'] doesn't gets resolved and return an error as `KeyError: 'version'`.  ## Steps to reproduce - Minimal Code Block:  ``` from selenium import webdriver from selenium.webdriver.firefox.options import Options from selenium.webdriver.common.desired_capabilities import DesiredCapabilities  binary = r'C:\Program Files\Mozilla Firefox\firefox.exe'  options = Options() options.binary = binary cap = DesiredCapabilities().FIREFOX cap["marionette"] = True driver = webdriver.Firefox(log_path='./Logs/WEBDRIVER_capabilities.log', firefox_options=options, capabilities=cap, executable_path="C:\\Utility\\BrowserDrivers\\geckodriver.exe") driver.get('http://google.com/') print('"WebDriver Attributes"') print('-------------------------') print('Usecase 1 : Wrapper methods : ') print(driver.capabilities['browserName']) driver.capabilities['version'] driver.quit();  ```  Console Output:  ``` "WebDriver Attributes" ------------------------- Usecase 1 : Wrapper methods :  firefox Traceback (most recent call last):   File "C:\Users\AtechM_03\LearnAutmation\PythonProject\MyPythonPackage\WEBDRIVER_capabilities.py", line 17, in      driver.capabilities['version'] KeyError: 'version' ```

column3: Selenium 3.5.2-Java : getPlatform() method and map.get("platform") method returns different results for capability Platform through geckodriver
column4: ## Meta - `getPlatform()` method and `map.get("platform")` method returns different results for capability `Platform` through geckodriver.  **`cap.getPlatform().toString()`** returns `Platform` as **`XP`** while **`map.get("platform")`** returns `Platform` as **`ANY`**  Through [**`895`**](https://github.com/mozilla/geckodriver/issues/895) @andreastt confirmed it's a Java Client issue.  OS: Windows 8 Pro, 64 bit  Selenium Version: 3.5.2 (Java)  Selenium Binding: Java  GeckoDriver Version: 0.18.0  Browser: Mozilla Firefox  Browser Version: 55.0.2  ## Expected Behavior - `getPlatform()` method and `map.get("platform")` method should return same result for capability `Platform` through geckodriver.  ## Actual Behavior - `getPlatform()` method and `map.get("platform")` method returns different results for capability `Platform` through geckodriver.  ## Steps to reproduce - Minimal Code Block:  	package demo;  	import java.util.Map;  	import org.openqa.selenium.Capabilities; 	import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver; 	import org.openqa.selenium.firefox.FirefoxDriver; 	import org.openqa.selenium.remote.RemoteWebDriver;  	public class WEBDRIVER_Platform 	{ 		public static void main(String[] args)  		{ 			String attribute = "platform"; 			System.setProperty("webdriver.gecko.driver", "C:\\Utility\\BrowserDrivers\\geckodriver.exe"); 			WebDriver driver = new FirefoxDriver(); 			Capabilities cap = ((RemoteWebDriver) driver).getCapabilities(); 			System.out.println("Platform is : "+cap.getPlatform().toString()); 			Map map = cap.asMap(); 			Object value = map.get(attribute); 			System.out.println("Key : " + attribute + " Value : "+ value); 		} 	}  Console Output:  ``` Platform is : XP Key : platform Value : ANY ```

column3: Selenium api docs refers WebDriver Interface as a Class
column4: ## Meta - [Selenium api docs](https://seleniumhq.github.io/selenium/docs/api/java/org/openqa/selenium/WebDriver.html) refers **`WebDriver` Interface** as a **Class** which is completely misleading.  > Currently, you will need to instantiate implementations of this class directly. It is hoped that you write your tests against this interface so that you may "swap in" a more fully featured browser when there is a requirement for one.  OS:  All  Selenium Version:  3.4.0  Browser:  All   Browser Version:  All   ## Expected Behavior - **`WebDriver` Interface** should be referred as  **Interface** only  ## Actual Behavior - **`WebDriver` Interface** is referred as  **Class** in the [API Docs](https://seleniumhq.github.io/selenium/docs/api/java/org/openqa/selenium/WebDriver.html).  ## Steps to reproduce -  Steps: 1. Browse to "https://seleniumhq.github.io/selenium/docs/api/java/org/openqa/selenium/WebDriver.html" 2. Observe the text:  > Currently, you will need to instantiate implementations of this class directly. It is hoped that you write your tests against this interface so that you may "swap in" a more fully featured browser when there is a requirement for one.

column3: Selenium 3.5.2-Java :  Need methods to retrieve the new capabilities with a "moz:" prefix through Java Client.
column4: ## Meta -  Need methods to retrieve the new capabilities with a "moz:" prefix through Java Client. As of now we are unable to retrieve the capabilities like `"moz:experimental-webdriver"` through Java Client.  As per WebDriver [**`W3C Candidate Recommendation 24 August 2017`**](https://w3c.github.io/webdriver/webdriver-spec.html#capabilities) Mozilla could elect to hide new features behind capabilities with a "moz:" prefix.    In chapter [7. Capabilities](https://w3c.github.io/webdriver/webdriver-spec.html#capabilities#x7.-capabilities): > Mozilla could elect to hide new features behind capabilities with a "moz:" prefix:  Example: ``` { 	"browserName": "firefox", 	"browserVersion": "1234", 	"moz:experimental-webdriver": true } ``` As of now Java client have the implementation for `browserName`, `browserVersion` and `platform`. Java client needs to implement methods to retrieve the new capabilities with a "moz:" prefix like `"moz:experimental-webdriver"`  ----------------------------------  OS: Windows 8 Pro, 64 bit  Selenium Version: 3.5.2 (Java)  Selenium Binding: Java  GeckoDriver Version: 0.18.0  Browser: Mozilla Firefox  Browser Version: 55.0.2  ## Expected Behavior - Java Client must implement methods to retrieve the new capabilities with a "moz:" prefix  ## Actual Behavior -  Java Client havn't implemented methods to retrieve the new capabilities with a "moz:" prefix  ## Steps to reproduce - Minimal Code Block:  	package demo;  	import java.util.Map;  	import org.openqa.selenium.Capabilities; 	import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver; 	import org.openqa.selenium.firefox.FirefoxDriver; 	import org.openqa.selenium.remote.RemoteWebDriver;  	public class WEBDRIVER_Experimental 	{ 		public static void main(String[] args)  		{ 			String attribute = "moz:experimental-webdriver"; 			System.setProperty("webdriver.gecko.driver", "C:\\Utility\\BrowserDrivers\\geckodriver.exe"); 			WebDriver driver = new FirefoxDriver(); 			Capabilities cap = ((RemoteWebDriver) driver).getCapabilities(); 			System.out.println("Browser Name is : "+cap.getBrowserName().toLowerCase()); 			System.out.println("Platform is : "+cap.getPlatform().toString()); 			System.out.println("Browser version is : "+cap.getVersion().toString()); 			//Need a get() method for "moz:experimental-webdriver" 			Map map = cap.asMap(); 			Object value = map.get(attribute); 			System.out.println("Key : " + attribute + " Value : "+ value); 		} 	}   Console Output:  ``` Browser Name is : firefox Platform is : XP Browser version is : 55.0.2 Key : moz:experimental-webdriver Value : null ```

column3: Passthrough server responds in wrong dialect if the "upstream" driver only understands OSS
column4: ## Meta - Selenium Version: synced to HEAD (currently 58ac131382942a543f692ed6319f87dd8a7f3552)  cc @shs96c  ## Steps to reproduce -  Run the standalone server: ``` $ java -Dwebdriver.chrome.driver=chrome/chromedriver-2.29 -jar selenium-server-standalone-3.4.0.jar -enablePassThrough ```  Send a dual-dialect new session request: ``` $ curl -d'{"capabilities": {"alwaysMatch": {"browserName": "chrome"}}, "desiredCapabilities": {"browserName": "chrome"}}' http://localhost:4444/wd/hub/session ```  The request gets forwarded to Chromedriver, which responds with an OSS response. Because OSS is spoken by both sides, the server enters passthrough mode. However, it replies with a W3C response, e.g., ``` {     "value": {         "capabilities": {             "acceptSslCerts": true,             ...         },         "sessionId": "01fdc7b0a9045152c8b15797a93567aa"     } } ```  Downstream clients doing the protocol handshake will take this to mean that they should use W3C, which is incorrect.  It seems like the problem is that [the BeginSession handler decides](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/b9f03491f807e034baa245fa764ff9d566113490/java/server/src/org/openqa/selenium/remote/server/BeginSession.java#L134) whether to send an OSS or W3C response based on the downstream request, rather than based on the upstream response, and it doesn't have any way of determining from the ActiveSession which dialect is being spoken.  Not sure how to fix this. Maybe the ActiveSession should be responsible for creating the new session response?

column3: Actions class is not consistently inheritable
column4: ## Meta - Selenium Version:  3.4/.NET Bindings  ## Expected Behavior -  When adding an action to an `Actions` subclass via `protected void AddAction(IAction actionToAdd)` the action should be executed when calling `Perform`.  ## Actual Behavior -  Depending on the driver used, the action will be executed or ignored.  ## Steps to reproduce -  1. Subclass `Actions` 2. Add method that calls `AddAction` 3. Call method in test case     - ChromeDriver (executable v2.29): Executes     - FirefoxDriver (executable: v0.16.1): Ignores  ## Underlying reason  `Actions` has two lists of actions and `AddAction`, the only method that allows generic access to those lists, adds to the `CompositeAction` list.      this.action.AddAction(actionToAdd);  `Perform` only executes one of the two based on driver capabilities:      IActionExecutor actionExecutor = this.driver as IActionExecutor;     if (actionExecutor.IsActionExecutor)     {         actionExecutor.PerformActions(this.actionBuilder.ToActionSequenceList());     }     else     {         this.action.Perform();     }

column3: selenium-webdriver 3.4.1 breaks passing in a hash for desired_capabilities [rb]
column4: ## Meta - Selenium Version:     3.4.1  ## Expected Behavior - Able to pass a hash for desired_capabilities as 3.4.0 supported  ## Actual Behavior - NoMethodError:        undefined method `capabilities' for {:unexpectedAlertBehaviour=>"ignore", "moz:firefoxOptions"=>{}}:Hash  selenium-webdriver 3.4.0 supported passing a Hash for the `:desired_capabilities` option when creating a new marionette driver, 3.4.1  has broken that since it now unconditionally calls `#capabilities` on the object passed in  - https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/rb/lib/selenium/webdriver/remote/w3c/capabilities.rb#L149  There was no deprecation notification before this behavior, and having it break in a point release is completely unexpected.

column3: Wrong Actions for CONTROL-Click
column4: ## Meta - OS: Windows 10 Creators Update Selenium Version:  3.5.2 Browser Version:  FF 55.0.2  ## Expected Behavior -  ```java new Actions(driver)       .keyDown(Keys.CONTROL)       .click()       .keyUp(Keys.CONTROL)       .perform(); ``` This code which uses the Actions API should send the following action sequences to the browser:  tick| pointer (Mouse) | key (Keyboard) --|------------ | ------------- 0 | pause 0 | keyDown Keys.CONTROL 1 | pointerDown | pause 0 2 | pointerUp | pause 0 3 | pause 0 | keyUp Keys.CONTROL  ## Actual Behavior -  Actually the `Actions` class sends the following action sequences:  tick| pointer (Mouse) | key (Keyboard) --|------------ | ------------- 0 | pause 0 | keyDown Keys.CONTROL 1 | pointerDown | keyUp Keys.CONTROL 2 | pointerUp |   Therefore in FF 55 (which implements the W3C actions API) the click event does not carry the ctrlKey flag and the web application does not recognize the Ctrl-Click.  ## Steps to reproduce -  For reproducing it with a browser see this geckodriver issue: https://github.com/mozilla/geckodriver/issues/888  I also created a unit test to show the exact problem. I added a comment to mark the failing assert.  ```java import static org.junit.Assert.assertEquals; import static org.junit.Assert.assertNotNull;  import java.util.Collection; import java.util.HashMap; import java.util.List; import java.util.Set;  import org.junit.Test; import org.openqa.selenium.By; import org.openqa.selenium.Keys; import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver; import org.openqa.selenium.WebElement; import org.openqa.selenium.interactions.Actions; import org.openqa.selenium.interactions.Interactive; import org.openqa.selenium.interactions.Sequence;   public class SeleniumActionsUnitTests {      private Collection performActions;      private class DummyWebDriver implements Interactive, WebDriver {          @Override     public void get(String url) {       // nothing     }      @Override     public String getCurrentUrl() {       return null;     }      @Override     public String getTitle() {       return null;     }      @Override     public List findElements(By by) {       return null;     }      @Override     public WebElement findElement(By by) {       return null;     }      @Override     public String getPageSource() {       return null;     }      @Override     public void close() {       // nothing     }      @Override     public void quit() {       // nothing     }      @Override     public Set getWindowHandles() {       return null;     }      @Override     public String getWindowHandle() {       return null;     }      @Override     public TargetLocator switchTo() {       return null;     }      @Override     public Navigation navigate() {       return null;     }      @Override     public Options manage() {       return null;     }      @Override     public void perform(Collection actions) {       performActions = actions;     }      @Override     public void resetInputState() {       // nothing     }        }    @Test   public void testCtrlClick() {     performActions = null;          new Actions(new DummyWebDriver())       .keyDown(Keys.CONTROL)       .click()       .keyUp(Keys.CONTROL)       .perform();          assertNotNull(performActions);     assertEquals(2, performActions.size());          // get mouse and keyboard sequences     HashMap[] sequencesJson = performActions.stream().map(s -> s.toJson()).toArray(HashMap[]::new);     HashMap mouseSequence = sequencesJson[0];     HashMap keyboardSequence;     if (!mouseSequence.get("type").equals("pointer")) {       mouseSequence = sequencesJson[1];       keyboardSequence = sequencesJson[0];     }     else {       keyboardSequence = sequencesJson[1];     }          assertEquals("pointer", mouseSequence.get("type"));     List mouseActions = (List) mouseSequence.get("actions");          HashMap pauseAction = mouseActions.get(0);     assertEquals("pause", pauseAction.get("type"));     assertEquals(0l, pauseAction.get("duration"));          HashMap pointerDownAction = mouseActions.get(1);     assertEquals("pointerDown", pointerDownAction.get("type"));     assertEquals(0, pointerDownAction.get("button"));          HashMap pointerUpAction = mouseActions.get(2);     assertEquals("pointerUp", pointerUpAction.get("type"));     assertEquals(0, pointerUpAction.get("button"));      assertEquals(3, mouseActions.size());        assertEquals("key", keyboardSequence.get("type"));     List keyboardActions = (List) keyboardSequence.get("actions");          HashMap keyDownAction = keyboardActions.get(0);     assertEquals("keyDown", keyDownAction.get("type"));     assertEquals(Keys.CONTROL.toString(), keyDownAction.get("value"));          // pause for pointerDown     pauseAction = keyboardActions.get(1);     assertEquals("pause", pauseAction.get("type")); // FAILS! Actually 'keyUp' is here which is not expected.     assertEquals(0l, pauseAction.get("duration"));      // pause for pointerUp     pauseAction = keyboardActions.get(2);     assertEquals("pause", pauseAction.get("type"));     assertEquals(0l, pauseAction.get("duration"));      HashMap keyUpAction = keyboardActions.get(3);     assertEquals("keyUp", keyUpAction.get("type"));     assertEquals(Keys.CONTROL.toString(), keyUpAction.get("value"));   }  } ```

column3: Using Firefox profile is not working with other device but not in my working device, in C#

column3: IE Driver Window Handle loss
column4: ## Meta - OS: Windows 10 Selenium Version:  2.52.0 Browser: Internet Explorer 11  Java 1.8    My test group has a test set consisting of 1800 test cases written for internet explorer. We have recently migrated to Windows 10, from Windows 7. The migration has broken our test bed. Without going further into the problem, we are able to execute the tests with the same IE settings (protected mode, registry, capabilities) on a Windows 10 laptop that is an HP but not one that is a Dell.   I understand the configurations are obviously different but am confounded by why it would cause a failure assuming all other settings held constant.  I am trying to debug this in part by using the IE Driver Server log file. I see window handle losses (connection to window lost) in the log file but they don't always correlate to the failures. I've searched for an 'interpreter' of that log file but haven't found one. Can anyone tell me if the log file reporting a window handle being lost indicates a failure by the driver? Is it possible for the window handle being lost to later be 'found' again?  Thanks for your help.

column3: Flaky InvalidSelectorException caused by Error: Permission denied
column4:
## Meta - OS: Window 7 Selenium Version: 2.53.0 Browser: Internet Explorer 11 Драйвер: IEDriverServer_Win32_3.4.0, 64 бит. драйвер не использую из-за медленной работы Browser Version:   Версия: 11.0.9600.18738 (64-bit) Версия обновления: 11.0.44  ## Expected Behavior - Отсутствие плавающей ошибки InvalidSelectorException. Правильная интерпретация ошибки,  InvalidSelectorException не должна быть плавающей, если поломанный xpath, либо он возвращает не WebElement трудно ожидать, что он станет рабочим, в данном случае ошибка плавающая и возникает на разных элементах в разное время.  Если  элемент не найден должна выбрасываться NoSuchElementException, если устарел StaleElementReferenceException, но не как не  InvalidSelectorException, которая пропадает при sleep(3000).   ## Actual Behavior - возникает плавающая ошибка InvalidSelectorException на разных элемента, в разный момент времени. Частный случай: org.openqa.selenium.InvalidSelectorException: Unable to locate an element with the xpath expression .//input[@value='Очистить'] because of the following error: Error: Разрешение отклонено (WARNING: The server did not provide any stacktrace information) Command duration or timeout: 62 milliseconds For documentation on this error, please visit: http://seleniumhq.or..._exception.html Build info: version: '2.53.0', revision: '35ae25b1534ae328c771e0856c93e187490ca824', time: '2016-03-15 10:43:46' System info: host: 'DF3-131016-NE03', ip: '10.80.16.134', os.name: 'Windows 7', os.arch: 'amd64', os.version: '6.1', java.version: '1.8.0_102' Driver info: org.openqa.selenium.ie.InternetExplorerDriver  ## Steps to reproduce - В примере видно, что локатор корректный  .//input[@value='Очистить'].   Элемент на странице существует, более того driver().getPageSource() возвращает во время ошибки:   `...     ...` При явном ожидании элемента, периодически получаю InvalidSelectorException, NoSuchElementException в зависимости от ожидания   Попробовал реализовать самостоятельное ожидание  `public WebElement findElementTo(By xpath, int timout){                 long deadLine = DateManager.getCurrentTimestamp() + (timout*1000);                 while(deadLine > DateManager.getCurrentTimestamp()){                         try{                                WebElement WebElement= find(xpath);                                return WebElement;                         }catch(Exception e){                                LOG.info("Ошибкак при получении элемента
"+Init.getWebDriver().getPageSource()+"
"+e);                         }         }                        WebElement WebElement= find(xpath);                 return WebElement;                      }          private WebElement find(By xpath) throws InvalidSelectorException{                      WebElement WebElement = Init.getWebDriver().findElement(xpath);                     if(WebElement.isDisplayed()){                 return WebElement;             }             throw new org.openqa.selenium.ElementNotVisibleException("Элемент не виден.          Xpath="+xpath+"


");         } ` Соответственно постоянно идет обращение к получению элемента и в течении 10 мин я могу получать ошибку InvalidSelectorException. Замечу это не регулярная ошибка, она периодически возникает на разных элементах.  На странице используются AJAX запросы.  Как решение проблемы, делаю такие грабли: `public void waitForJQueryLoad(long timeout) {                   WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(Init.getWebDriver(), timeout);                 wait.until(new ExpectedCondition(){                           @Override                         public Boolean apply(WebDriver driver){                                Boolean active = false;                                JavascriptExecutor js = null;                                try{                                        js = ((JavascriptExecutor)driver);                                        active = (Boolean)js.executeScript("return $j.active == 0");                                }catch(WebDriverException e){                                        LOG.info("Ошибка драйвера:
"+e);                                }                                LOG.info("$.active="+active);                                return active;                          }                 });                  try {                         //Таймаут необходим, для отрисовки элементов DOM, после JQuery запросов.                         Thread.sleep(250);                 } catch (InterruptedException e) {                         // TODO Автоматически созданный блок catch                         e.printStackTrace();                 }` То есть дожидаюсь что бы все AJAX запросы были выполнены и жду построения ДОМ в течении 0,25 сек   Я не в курсе как отрабатывает дальше цепочка, селениум - драйвер IE - браузер IE. Но из опыта прихожу к выводам: 1) Не правильно интерпретируется ошибка InvalidSelectorException - она же означает, что xpath не валидный, либо возвращается не WebElement, а текст к примеру в нашем случае тут явно WebElement. К тому же ошибка плавающая, это говорит, что локатор валидный. Более того обычный sleep решает проблему. 2) Второе странное поведение, если  предположить, что ДОМ не успел до строиться, например странно (value=Очистить - почему то без кавычек), но тогда почему при последующих запросах, получения того же элемента WebElement WebElement= find(xpath);, ДОМ не перестраивается для драйвера? То есть если в текущем тесте получили  InvalidSelectorException, то она так и появляется, пока таймаут не закончится. (Приложение отрабатывает корректно и совершенно точно элементы подгружается до окончания таймаута) 3) Думаю проблема заключается в драйвере IE, возможно из-за того, что используется драйвер 32 битный, но пока не будет исправлена длительная работа 64 битного драйвера, нет возможности переходить на него. Хотелось бы понять чем характеризуется такое странно поведение в тестах.

column3: Selenium does not wait after calling WebElement.submit()
column4: ## Meta - OS: OS X 10.11.6 (15G1611) Selenium Version:  3.4.0 Browser:  Firefox 55.0.2  Originally opened at https://github.com/mozilla/geckodriver/issues/878, but then I was referred to here.  ## Expected Behavior -  With Firefox 47 (without marionette), calling submit() on a WebElement caused Selenium to wait until the page load starts (just as it also works in current Chrome).  ## Actual Behavior -  This is not the case with current Firefox that uses WebDriver. Is that intended behaviour? Our test suite relies on that implicit wait currently.  ## Steps to reproduce -  If a submit() is triggered on a form, the following test code runs in the context of the old page.  ## Possible issue -  Information by @andreastt in the geckodriver issue:  > Do note that there is no submit command in the WebDriver specification, so my suspicion is that the shim Selenium uses to map it to a valid WebDriver primitive is wrong. If Selenium were to map WebElement#submit() to Element Click, which we have confirmed waits for the document to finish loading, it should work just fine provided you are using the normal page loading strategy.  Any help will be most appreciated. Sorry, I'm not familiar with the technical details of Selenium's internals.

column3: Unable to set `moz:firefoxOptions` property in `Builder#withCapabilities`
column4: ## Meta - OS: Mac OSX 10.12.5 Selenium Version: 3.4.0 (of `selenium-webdriver` Node.js package) Browser: Firefox/Geckodriver  Browser Version: 53.0.3 (64-bit)  ## Description  I primarily use the `new Builder().withCapabilities([object literal]).build()` API for creating driver instances because it lets me easily store a set of configurations in a JSON file. However, it looks like the Node.js version of selenium-webdriver throws out the `moz:firefoxOptions` field: https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/javascript/node/selenium-webdriver/firefox/index.js#L486-L488  ## Expected Behavior  For example, I needed to configure a browser with geolocation support turned off. I expected the following to work:  ```js const driver = new webdriver.Builder()   .withCapabilities({     'browserName': 'firefox',     'moz:firefoxOptions': {       prefs: {         'geo.enabled': false       }     }   })   .build(); ```  ## Actual Behavior  However, the browser that is opened as a result still has geolocation support turned on.  For comparison, this works fine with Chromedriver:  ```js const driver = new webdriver.Builder()   .withCapabilities({     'browserName': 'chrome',     'chromeOptions': {       prefs: {         'profile.default_content_settings.geolocation': 2       }     }   })   .build(); ```  It looks like the problem is because the `createGeckoDriver()` function in the firefox module simply overwrites whatever was in `moz:firefoxOptions`.  I know I can work around this by doing:  ```js const profile = new firefox.Profile(); profile.setPreference('geo.enabled', false); const options = new firefox.Options().setProfile(profile); const driver = new webdriver.Builder()   .forBrowser('firefox')   .setFirefoxOptions(options)   .build(); ```  …but making that work with a set of serialized capabilities stored on disk is a lot of extra work :\

column4: ## Meta - OS: GNURoot on Andoid  Selenium Version:  3.5.0  Browser:  Chromium   Browser Version:     ## Expected Behavior - To load driver ## Actual Behavior - Error. Chromium executable not found in path. ## Steps to reproduce -  Selenium installed using pip, on GNURoot on Android.  Trying to run this code :      import selenium      from selenium import webdriver      #driver = webdriver.Chrome()      driver = webdriver.Chrome(executable_path='/usr/bin/chromedriver')      time.sleep(5)      driver.quit()    What I get:  >  python 5formscrape-selenium.py >  >  Traceback (most recent call last): >  > File "5formscrape-selenium.py", line 5, in   driver = > webdriver.Chrome(executable_path='/usr/bin/chromedriver') >  > File > "/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/selenium/webdriver/chrome/webdriver.py", > line 62, in __init__  self.service.start() >  > File > "/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/selenium/webdriver/common/service.py", > line 81, in start  os.path.basename(self.path), > self.start_error_message) > selenium.common.exceptions.WebDriverException: Message: 'chromedriver' > executable needs to be in PATH. column3: W3C IEDriver ignores "unhandledPromptBehavior" capability
column4: ## Meta - OS: any Windows Selenium Version: n/a Browser: Internet Explorer Browser Version: any  IEDriver 3.3.99.4 (cc @jimevans)  ## Expected Behavior - The `unhandledPromptBehavior` capability should be respected.  ## Actual Behavior - The capability is always set to `"dismiss"` in a newly-created session.  ## Steps to reproduce - `c:\bin\wget.exe http://localhost:4444/session --post-data="{\"capabilities\": {\"alwaysMatch\": {\"unhandledPromptBehavior\": \"accept\"}}}"`  The capabilities in the response contain `"unhandledPromptBehavior":"dismiss"`, and the driver does appear to dismiss unhandled prompts without raising an error.  If I set an illegal value (`"unhandledPromptBehavior": "cheese"`), then a `session not created` error is raised, as expected.  I think that, by default, the capability should be absent, because the "missing value default state" [is a distinct case](https://w3c.github.io/webdriver/webdriver-spec.html#dfn-handle-any-user-prompts) from either of the defined states "accept" and "dismiss". Though perhaps this is a spec question of whether it should really be defined that way, or if there should be a third value, such as "error".

column3: Add "Windows XP" as a platform to align with SauceLabs Platform Configurator

column3: WebDriver doesn't work properly with C# LINQ
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 8.1 x64 Selenium Version: 3.0.1, C# nuget package   Browser:  Chrome Browser Version:  56.0.2924.87  ## Steps to reproduce - 1. Open web-page with element located by some XPath which contains Text 2. Run one of the following functions for waiting For Example: Waiter(driver, 2000, "//button[@id='test_button']", "BUTTON");   1.  ``` public static void Waiter(IWebDriver driver, int millisec, string xpath, string text) { try { (new WebDriverWait(driver, TimeSpan.FromMilliseconds(millisec))).Until(     d => d.FindElements(By.XPath(xpath)).Any(         element => element.Displayed && element.Enabled && element.Text.Equals(text))); } catch (WebDriverTimeoutException ex) { // do smth } } ```  2.   ``` public static void Waiter(IWebDriver driver, int millisec, string xpath, string text) { try { (new WebDriverWait(driver, TimeSpan.FromMilliseconds(millisec))).Until(             d =>     {         var elements = d.FindElements(By.XPath(xpath));         return elements.Any(element => element.Displayed && element.Enabled && element.Text.Equals(text));     }); catch (WebDriverTimeoutException ex) { // do smth } } ```  3.  ``` public static void Waiter(IWebDriver driver, int millisec, string xpath, string text) { try { (new WebDriverWait(driver, TimeSpan.FromMilliseconds(millisec))).Until(     d =>     {         var elements = d.FindElements(By.XPath(xpath));         foreach (var element in elements)         {             if (element.Displayed && element.Enabled && element.Text.Equals(text))             {                 return true;             }         }              return false;     }); catch (WebDriverTimeoutException ex) { // do smth } } ```  ## Expected Behavior - all examples should work identically  ## Actual Behavior - 1st example causes StaleElementReferenceException 2nd and 3rd works properly without errors/exceptions
