column3: [Selenium 3.4.0-Java]-beforeFindBy and afterFindBy methods of WebDriverEventListner interface throwing java.lang.NullPointerException
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 8 Pro-64 bit OS, x64-based processor  Selenium Version:  selenium-server-standalone-3.4.0  Browser:  Mozilla Firefox   WebDriver:  geckodriver-v0.16.0-win64 (geckodriver.exe)  Browser Version:  53.0 (64-bit)   ## Expected Behavior -`beforeFindBy` and `afterFindBy` methods of `WebDriverEventListner` interface when implemented through Java bindings must not throw `java.lang.NullPointerException`  ## Actual Behavior - `beforeFindBy` and `afterFindBy` methods of `WebDriverEventListner` interface when implemented through Java bindings throws `java.lang.NullPointerException`  ## Steps to reproduce -  1. Written "EventHandler" class which implements "WebDriverEventListener" as follows:          package WebDriver_Event_Listener;          import org.openqa.selenium.By;         import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver;         import org.openqa.selenium.WebElement;         import org.openqa.selenium.support.events.WebDriverEventListener;          public class EventHandler implements WebDriverEventListener{  	        @Override 	        public void afterAlertAccept(WebDriver arg0) { 		        // TODO Auto-generated method stub 		 	        }  	        @Override 	        public void afterAlertDismiss(WebDriver arg0) { 		        // TODO Auto-generated method stub 		 	        }  	        @Override 	        public void afterChangeValueOf(WebElement arg0, WebDriver arg1, CharSequence[] arg2) { 		        // TODO Auto-generated method stub 		        System.out.println("inside method afterChangeValueOf on " + arg0.toString()); 	        }  	        @Override 	        public void afterClickOn(WebElement arg0, WebDriver arg1) { 		        // TODO Auto-generated method stub 		        System.out.println("inside method afterClickOn on " + arg0.toString()); 		 	        }  	        @Override 	        public void afterFindBy(By arg0, WebElement arg1, WebDriver arg2) { 		        // TODO Auto-generated method stub 		        System.out.println("Find happened on " + arg1.toString() + " Using method " + arg0.toString()); 		 	        }  	        @Override 	        public void afterNavigateBack(WebDriver arg0) { 		        // TODO Auto-generated method stub 		        System.out.println("Inside the after navigateback to " + arg0.getCurrentUrl()); 		 	        }  	        @Override 	        public void afterNavigateForward(WebDriver arg0) { 		        // TODO Auto-generated method stub 		        System.out.println("Inside the afterNavigateForward to " + arg0.getCurrentUrl()); 		 	        }  	        @Override 	        public void afterNavigateRefresh(WebDriver arg0) { 		        // TODO Auto-generated method stub 		 	        }  	        @Override 	        public void afterNavigateTo(String arg0, WebDriver arg1) { 		        // TODO Auto-generated method stub 		        System.out.println("Inside the afterNavigateTo to " + arg0); 		 	        }  	        @Override 	        public void afterScript(String arg0, WebDriver arg1) { 		        // TODO Auto-generated method stub 		        System.out.println("Inside the afterScript to, Script is " + arg0); 		 	        }  	        @Override 	        public void beforeAlertAccept(WebDriver arg0) { 		        // TODO Auto-generated method stub 		 	        }  	        @Override 	        public void beforeAlertDismiss(WebDriver arg0) { 		        // TODO Auto-generated method stub 		 	        }  	        @Override 	        public void beforeChangeValueOf(WebElement arg0, WebDriver arg1, CharSequence[] arg2) { 		        // TODO Auto-generated method stub 		        System.out.println("Inside the beforeChangeValueOf method"); 		 	        }  	        @Override 	        public void beforeClickOn(WebElement arg0, WebDriver arg1) { 		        // TODO Auto-generated method stub 		        System.out.println("About to click on the " + arg0.toString()); 		 	        }  	        @Override 	        public void beforeFindBy(By arg0, WebElement arg1, WebDriver arg2) { 		        // TODO Auto-generated method stub 		        System.out.println("Just before finding element " + arg1.toString()); 		 	        }  	        @Override 	        public void beforeNavigateBack(WebDriver arg0) { 		        // TODO Auto-generated method stub 		        System.out.println("Just before beforeNavigateBack " + arg0.getCurrentUrl()); 		 	        }  	        @Override 	        public void beforeNavigateForward(WebDriver arg0) { 		        // TODO Auto-generated method stub 		        System.out.println("Just before beforeNavigateForward " + arg0.getCurrentUrl()); 		 	        }  	        @Override 	        public void beforeNavigateRefresh(WebDriver arg0) { 		        // TODO Auto-generated method stub 		 	        }  	        @Override 	        public void beforeNavigateTo(String arg0, WebDriver arg1) { 		        // TODO Auto-generated method stub 		        System.out.println("Just before beforeNavigateTo " + arg0); 		 	        }  	        @Override 	        public void beforeScript(String arg0, WebDriver arg1) { 		        // TODO Auto-generated method stub 		        System.out.println("Just before beforeScript " + arg0); 		 	        }  	        @Override 	        public void onException(Throwable arg0, WebDriver arg1) { 		        // TODO Auto-generated method stub 		        System.out.println("Exception occured at " + arg0.getMessage()); 		 	        }  	         }  2. Written "programMain" class which calls the "EventHandler" class as follows:          package WebDriver_Event_Listener;           import org.openqa.selenium.By;         import org.openqa.selenium.WebElement;         import org.openqa.selenium.firefox.FirefoxDriver;         import org.openqa.selenium.support.events.EventFiringWebDriver;          public class programMain {  	        public static void main(String[] args) { 		        // TODO Auto-generated method stub 		        System.setProperty("webdriver.gecko.driver", "C:\\Utility\\BrowserDrivers\\geckodriver.exe");                     FirefoxDriver driver = new FirefoxDriver();                     EventFiringWebDriver eventDriver = new EventFiringWebDriver(driver);  		        EventHandler handler = new EventHandler(); 		        eventDriver.register(handler); 		        eventDriver.get("https://google.com"); 		        WebElement element = eventDriver.findElement(By.linkText("Gmail")); 		        element.click();  	        }          }  3. Executed the "programMain" class as a "Java Application"  4. `java.lang.NullPointerException` is observed for **WebDriver_Event_Listener.EventHandler.beforeFindBy(EventHandler.java:105)**  5. Console stack trace is as follows:  ``` May 30, 2017 9:59:47 PM org.openqa.selenium.remote.ProtocolHandshake createSession INFO: Detected dialect: W3C Just before beforeNavigateTo https://google.com Inside the afterNavigateTo to https://google.com Exception in thread "main" java.lang.NullPointerException 	at WebDriver_Event_Listener.EventHandler.beforeFindBy(EventHandler.java:105) 	at sun.reflect.NativeMethodAccessorImpl.invoke0(Native Method) 	at sun.reflect.NativeMethodAccessorImpl.invoke(NativeMethodAccessorImpl.java:62) 	at sun.reflect.DelegatingMethodAccessorImpl.invoke(DelegatingMethodAccessorImpl.java:43) 	at java.lang.reflect.Method.invoke(Method.java:498) 	at org.openqa.selenium.support.events.EventFiringWebDriver$1.invoke(EventFiringWebDriver.java:81) 	at com.sun.proxy.$Proxy0.beforeFindBy(Unknown Source) 	at org.openqa.selenium.support.events.EventFiringWebDriver.findElement(EventFiringWebDriver.java:187) 	at WebDriver_Event_Listener.programMain.main(programMain.java:20) ```  6. Commented out `System.out.println("Just before finding element " + arg1.toString());` from `public void beforeFindBy(By arg0, WebElement arg1, WebDriver arg2)` method:  ``` 	@Override 	public void beforeFindBy(By arg0, WebElement arg1, WebDriver arg2) { 		// TODO Auto-generated method stub 		//System.out.println("Just before finding element " + arg1.toString()); 		 	} ```  7.Executed the "programMain" class as a "Java Application" again.  8. `java.lang.NullPointerException` is observed for **WebDriver_Event_Listener.EventHandler.afterFindBy(EventHandler.java:38)**  9. Console stack trace is as follows:  ``` May 30, 2017 10:06:45 PM org.openqa.selenium.remote.ProtocolHandshake createSession INFO: Detected dialect: W3C Just before beforeNavigateTo https://google.com Inside the afterNavigateTo to https://google.com Exception in thread "main" java.lang.NullPointerException 	at WebDriver_Event_Listener.EventHandler.afterFindBy(EventHandler.java:38) 	at sun.reflect.NativeMethodAccessorImpl.invoke0(Native Method) 	at sun.reflect.NativeMethodAccessorImpl.invoke(NativeMethodAccessorImpl.java:62) 	at sun.reflect.DelegatingMethodAccessorImpl.invoke(DelegatingMethodAccessorImpl.java:43) 	at java.lang.reflect.Method.invoke(Method.java:498) 	at org.openqa.selenium.support.events.EventFiringWebDriver$1.invoke(EventFiringWebDriver.java:81) 	at com.sun.proxy.$Proxy0.afterFindBy(Unknown Source) 	at org.openqa.selenium.support.events.EventFiringWebDriver.findElement(EventFiringWebDriver.java:189) 	at WebDriver_Event_Listener.programMain.main(programMain.java:20) ```

column3: IE Browser | invalid selector exception if xpaths are used
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 7, Windows 8 and Windows 10 Selenium Version:  2.53.1 & 3.3.1 Browser:  IE-10 and IE-11  org.openqa.selenium.InvalidSelectorException: Unable to locate an element with the xpath expression //*[contains(text(),'Country')]/ancestor::li[@class='clearfix listItemTrackPosition']//i[contains(@class,'remove-row')] because of the following error: TypeError: Object doesn't support property or method 'toLowerCase' (WARNING: The server did not provide any stacktrace information) Command duration or timeout: 109 milliseconds  The xpath //*[contains(text(),'Country')]/ancestor::li[@class='listItemTrack']//i[contains(@class,'remove-row')] is valid and works perfectly fine on Chrome & Firefox browsers. However, it fails with the above error in IE-10/IE-11.  Similarly following xpath expression is failing on IE-10 & IE-11:  org.openqa.selenium.InvalidSelectorException: Unable to locate an element with the xpath expression //li[contains(@class, 'listItemTrackPosition')][1]//div[contains(@id, 'ruleConditionsFormattedText')] because of the following error: TypeError: Object doesn't support property or method 'toLowerCase' (WARNING: The server did not provide any stacktrace information) Command duration or timeout: 78 milliseconds For documentation on this error, please visit: http://seleniumhq.org/exceptions/invalid_selector_exception.html Build info: version: '2.53.1', revision: 'a36b8b1', time: '2016-06-30 17:37:03' System info: host: 'win7-01', ip: '192.168.2.21', os.name: 'Windows 7', os.arch: 'amd64', os.version: '6.1', java.version: '1.8.0_92' Driver info: org.openqa.selenium.ie.InternetExplorerDriver Capabilities [{browserAttachTimeout=0, ie.enableFullPageScreenshot=true, enablePersistentHover=false, ie.forceCreateProcessApi=false, ie.forceShellWindowsApi=false, pageLoadStrategy=normal, ignoreZoomSetting=true, ie.fileUploadDialogTimeout=3000, version=11, platform=WINDOWS, nativeEvents=false, ie.ensureCleanSession=true, elementScrollBehavior=0, ie.browserCommandLineSwitches=, requireWindowFocus=false, browserName=internet explorer, initialBrowserUrl=http://localhost:32396/, javascriptEnabled=true, ignoreProtectedModeSettings=false, enableElementCacheCleanup=true, unexpectedAlertBehaviour=dismiss}] Session ID: 194f63fd-7a14-4b2b-9c5e-38aa5ab57726 *** Element info: {Using=xpath, value=//li[contains(@class, 'listItemTrackPosition')][1]//div[contains(@id, 'ruleConditionsFormattedText')]} Command duration or timeout: 584 milliseconds  Anyone noticed similar issues with IE? what is the solution if so? column3: Not able to set DesiredCapabilities for firefox 53.0 with selenium 3.4.0 and geckdriver 0.16.0
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 7 x64  Selenium Version:  3.4.0  Browser:  Firefox   Browser Version:  53.0 (64-bit)   ## Expected Behavior - setting driver binary path with firefoxOptions  ## Actual Behavior - org.openqa.selenium.SessionNotCreatedException: Unable to find a matching set of capabilities  ## Steps to reproduce -  ``` FirefoxProfile firefoxProfile = new FirefoxProfile(); firefoxProfile.setPreference("enableNativeEvents", true);  FirefoxOptions options = new FirefoxOptions(); options.setBinary(browserBinary); options.toCapabilities();  DesiredCapabilities desired = DesiredCapabilities.firefox(); desired.setCapability("browserName", "firefox"); desired.setCapability("browserVersion", "53.0"); desired.setCapability("platformName", "Windows");            desired.setCapability(CapabilityType.ForSeleniumServer.ENSURING_CLEAN_SESSION, true); System.setProperty("webdriver.gecko.driver", driverBinary); ```  this returns org.openqa.selenium.SessionNotCreatedException: Unable to find a matching set of capabilities  Tried a variety of ways to set-up browser binary and all without positive outcome. This: ``` FirefoxOptions options = new FirefoxOptions(); ... desired.setCapability(FirefoxOptions.FIREFOX_OPTIONS, options.setBinary(driverBinary)); ``` returns the same exception.

column3: "storedVars is not defined" error when run HTML test suite in Selenium HTML Runner
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 7 SP1 x64 Selenium Version:  selenium-server-standalone-3.4.0, selenium-html-runner-3.4.0, Selenium IDE 2.9.1.1 Browser:  Firefox Browser Version:  51.0.1 (32-bit)  ## Expected Behavior - Selenium HTML Runner must support storedVars object in storeEval and runScript commands.  ## Actual Behavior - Any HTML test which accesses storedVars object fails  with the following error when run through Selenium HTML Runner: com.thoughtworks.selenium.SeleniumException: ReferenceError: storedVars is not defined  ## Steps to reproduce - 1. Run Suite_storedVars2.html test suite in Firefox Selenium IDE plugin - no errors, test is successful.  2. Run selenium standalone: java -jar selenium-server-standalone-3.4.0.jar  3. Run Suite_storedVars2.html test suite in selenium html runner: java -jar selenium-html-runner-3.4.0.jar -timeout 1000 -htmlSuite "*firefox" "https://www.ibm.com/us-en/" "D:\SeleniumIDE\Suite_storedVars2.html" log1  4. Observe log1\firefox.results.html result file, which contains an error message: com.thoughtworks.selenium.SeleniumException: ReferenceError: storedVars is not defined  Please find test suite Suite_storedVars2.txt (rename to .html) and test case Test_storedVars2.txt (rename to .html) files attached, [Suite_storedVars2.txt](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/files/1029228/Suite_storedVars2.txt) [Test_storedVars2.txt](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/files/1029231/Test_storedVars2.txt)

column3: Selenium (Python) stuck after download of files
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 7 Professional  Selenium Version:  3.4.3  Browser:  Firefox    Browser Version:  52.3.0 (32 bit)   ## Expected Behavior -  We expect Selenium to download two files from the world bank webpage and open google.com after that.   ## Actual Behavior -  Firefox does download the two files. However Selenium does not return the command back to python and will not execute the next line (which would open google.com).  The driver.get(URL_to_file) keeps running although the file download is finished by Firefox.   ## Steps to reproduce -  import selenium from selenium import webdriver from selenium.webdriver.common.keys import Keys from selenium.webdriver.common.by import By from selenium.webdriver.support.ui import WebDriverWait from selenium.webdriver.support import expected_conditions as EC  fp = webdriver.FirefoxProfile() fp.set_preference("browser.helperApps.neverAsk.saveToDisk","text/csv") fp.set_preference("browser.download.folderList",1) fp.set_preference("browser.download.manager.showWhenStarting",False) fp.set_preference("http.response.timeout", 5) fp.set_preference("dom.max_script_run_time", 5) fp.set_preference('browser.helperApps.neverAsk.saveToDisk', "text/plain, application/vnd.ms-excel, text/csv, text/comma-separated-values, application/octet-stream") driver = webdriver.Firefox(fp)   driver.get('http://databank.worldbank.org/data/download/site-content/CLASS.xls') driver.get("http://databank.worldbank.org/data/download/site-content/OGHIST.xls") driver.get("http://google.com")

column3: IE Driver Server does not use the right protected mode settings
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 7 Selenium Version:  Webdriver 3.4 (C#) and IEDriverServer 3.4 Browser:  Internet Explorer Browser Version:  11.0.9600.18638  Related to https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/issues/919   ## Expected Behavior - IEDriverServer should determine the used Protected Mode settings in the same way that IE itself does it, which is examining (in order of searching):  - HKLM\Software\Policies\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Internet Settings\Zones - HKCU\Software\Policies\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Internet Settings\Zones - HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Internet Settings\Zones - HKLM\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Internet Settings\Zones  If IE finds the setting at a certain location, it doesn't look further. This is e.g. to allow policies to override local settings, which happens a lot in corporate environments.   ## Actual Behavior - IEDriverServer only examines HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Internet Settings\Zones  ## Steps to reproduce - Add DWORDS 1\2500, 2\2500, 3\2500 and 4\2500 under  HKCU\Software\Policies\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Internet Settings\Zones and give them all value 3.  Make the same entries under HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Internet Settings\Zones a combination of values 3 and 0.  Now IE uses the same protected mode settings for all zones, as it uses the values under the Policies tree, but the constructor for InternetExplorerDriver throws an OpenQA.Selenium.WebDriverException: 'Unexpected error launching Internet Explorer. Protected Mode settings are not the same for all zones. Enable Protected Mode must be set to the same value (enabled or disabled) for all zones.'

column3: delete_all_cookies doesn't work with web-driver 3.4.0
column4: ## Meta - OS:  windows 7 Selenium Version:  selenium-webdriver 3.4.0  Browser:   Chrome IE Firefox Browser Version:   Firefox 53 Chrome 57.0.2987.98 IE11 Browser Driver Version Chrome: ChromeDriver 2.28 Firefox:GeckoDriver 0.16 ## Expected Behavior - browser.manage.delete_all_cookies can work ## Actual Behavior - delete_all_cookies doesn't work   ## Steps to reproduce -  we are using ruby22 + cucumber + capybara as our automation framework, we have a script need to delete all cookies and reset browser,After go through the code, I found delete_all_cookies doesn't work,  Here is the code: ``` def reset!     # Use instance variable directly so we avoid starting the browser just to reset the session     if @browser       navigated = false       start_time = Capybara::Helpers.monotonic_time       begin         if !navigated           # Only trigger a navigation if we haven't done it already, otherwise it           # can trigger an endless series of unload modals           begin             @browser.manage.delete_all_cookies             puts "delete_all_cookies"             if options[:clear_session_storage]               if @browser.respond_to? :session_storage                 @browser.session_storage.clear               else                 warn "sessionStorage clear requested but is not available for this driver"               end             end             if options[:clear_local_storage]               if @browser.respond_to? :local_storage                 puts ":clear_local_storage"                 @browser.local_storage.clear               else                 warn "localStorage clear requested but is not available for this driver"               end             end           rescue Selenium::WebDriver::Error::UnhandledError             # delete_all_cookies fails when we've previously gone             # to about:blank, so we rescue this error and do nothing             # instead.           end           @browser.navigate.to("about:blank")                   end         navigated = true          #Ensure the page is empty and trigger an UnhandledAlertError for any modals that appear during unload         until find_xpath("/html/body/*").empty? do           raise Capybara::ExpectationNotMet.new('Timed out waiting for Selenium session reset') if (Capybara::Helpers.monotonic_time - start_time) >= 10           sleep 0.05         end       rescue Selenium::WebDriver::Error::UnhandledAlertError         # This error is thrown if an unhandled alert is on the page         # Firefox appears to automatically dismiss this alert, chrome does not         # We'll try to accept it         begin           @browser.switch_to.alert.accept           sleep 0.25 # allow time for the modal to be handled         rescue Selenium::WebDriver::Error::NoAlertPresentError           # The alert is now gone - nothing to do         end         # try cleaning up the browser again         retry       end     end   end ```  But it worked with the old version:ruby193+ webdriver 3.3.0 + chromedriver 2.24   Could you please take a look?thx

column3: py[3.5.0]: __package__ may be None in selenium.webdriver.remote.webelement
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 7 Selenium Version:  selenium-py 3.5.0, on python 3.6.2 Browser:  N/A  ## Expected Behavior - `selenium.webdriver.remote.webelement` can be imported without issue  ## Actual Behavior - In some situations (I encountered that when launching a test suite from PyCharm), importing `selenium.webdriver.remote.webelement` (indirectly via `selenium.webdriver`) raises an `AttributeError` coming from the fact that `__package__` is `None` when calling `pkgutil.get_data(__package__, ...)` [here](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/py/selenium/webdriver/remote/webelement.py#L41).  ```   File "d:\dev\.env\buildout\eggs\selenium-3.5.0-py3.6.egg\selenium\webdriver\remote\webelement.py", line 45, in      getAttribute_js = pkgutil.get_data(__package__, 'getAttribute.js').decode('utf8')   File "C:\Python\3.6\Lib\pkgutil.py", line 616, in get_data     spec = importlib.util.find_spec(package)   File "D:\dev\.env\venv\buildout\lib\importlib\util.py", line 83, in find_spec     fullname = resolve_name(name, package) if name.startswith('.') else name AttributeError: 'NoneType' object has no attribute 'startswith' ```  Looking for a way to resolve that, I discovered that `__package__` is not set consistently by python within modules (see [here](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/4437394/package-is-none-when-importing-a-python-module), while it's hard to understand why it's not set in that situation), and that it may be better to rely on `__name__` instead. Hence I'd think of replacing:  ``` getAttribute_js = pkgutil.get_data(__package__, 'getAttribute.js').decode('utf8') isDisplayed_js = pkgutil.get_data(__package__, 'isDisplayed.js').decode('utf8') ```  by:  ``` _pkg = '.'.join(__name__.split('.')[:-1]) getAttribute_js = pkgutil.get_data(_pkg, 'getAttribute.js').decode('utf8') isDisplayed_js = pkgutil.get_data(_pkg, 'isDisplayed.js').decode('utf8') ```  ## Steps to reproduce - Not sure if it can be reproduced on any machine, but for me it's simply 'launch a script importing `selenium.webdriver` at some point from PyCharm'. Launching the same script in the console works, for some reason.

column3: IEDriverServer doesn't handle concurrent requests correctly
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 7 Selenium Version:  IEDriver 3.3.0.0 is what I happened to be using (I didn't any changes that would have fixed this in a more recent build, but I can double-check with a newer release later) Browser:  IE11, but it shouldn't matter  cc @jimevans   ## Steps to reproduce - Send two commands to the IEDriverServer concurrently (i.e., with the second request arriving before the first response is sent).  This script reproduces the problem pretty reliably for me:  ```py import multiprocessing import sys  from selenium import webdriver from selenium.common import exceptions  driver = webdriver.Remote(     command_executor=sys.argv[1],     desired_capabilities={})  def Execute(id):   print 'starting thread', id   for n in xrange(3):     try:       want = 'thread %s, request %s' % (id, n)       script = 'return "%s";' % want       got = driver.execute_script(script)       if got != want:         print 'ERROR: (%s) returned %s' % (script, got)     except exceptions.WebDriverException as e:       print 'ERROR: (%s) exception %s' % (script, e)  p1 = multiprocessing.Process(target=Execute, args=(1,)) p2 = multiprocessing.Process(target=Execute, args=(2,)) p1.start() p2.start() p1.join() p2.join() ```  Start IEDriver (WLOG let's say it's on port 4444), then run `python example.py http://localhost:4444`. Some sample output, which will of course differ a little every time: ``` starting thread 1 starting thread 2 ERROR: (return "thread 2, request 0";) returned thread 1, request 0 ERROR: (return "thread 1, request 0";) exception Message: Error 404: Not Found Not Found  ERROR: (return "thread 1, request 1";) returned thread 2, request 0 ERROR: (return "thread 1, request 2";) returned thread 2, request 1 ERROR: (return "thread 2, request 1";) returned thread 1, request 2 ERROR: (return "thread 2, request 2";) returned thread 1, request 2 ```  Full trace log from IEDriver here: https://gist.github.com/anonymous/f25108e2679431caaef5dc4a2d4cbfac

column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 7 Selenium Version:   2.53.1 Browser:   IE 11 (IE Update version - 11.0.42 KB4018271) IEDriverServer version: 2.53.0/2.53.1  We are using a custom Selenium framework (xFramium version 1.0.6) which internally uses selenium 2.53.1 version and the RemoteWebDriver.  We have around 3000 automation scripts which we have executed on Chrome using Selenium grid setup without much issues. But now when we are trying to execute the same set of test cases in IE, the first issue that we faced was with the objects not getting identified because of invalid xpaths which we had to update to CSS selectors for majority of the objects.  After fixing the object identification issues when we started executing the test cases on the Selenium grid with multiple instances the same set of test cases which passed locally are failing and it does not consistently fail on the same screen or the same object. We tried reducing the number of instances per selenium node to 1 the pass rate is better but not significant.  We have done the standard setup required for IEDrvierServer in registry (Protected mode, BFCache etc.) even the noFrameMerging to allow IE to have a completely new session every time a new IE window is opened but still no luck in achieving higher pass percentage.  We tried updating the IEDriverServer version and Selenium-standalone server version to 3.4 but no improvement.  Below are the registry settings: REG ADD "HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Internet Settings\Zones\0" /v 2500 /t REG_DWORD /d 00000000 /f REG ADD "HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Internet Settings\Zones\1" /v 2500 /t REG_DWORD /d 00000000 /f REG ADD "HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Internet Settings\Zones\2" /v 2500 /t REG_DWORD /d 00000000 /f REG ADD "HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Internet Settings\Zones\3" /v 2500 /t REG_DWORD /d 00000000 /f REG ADD "HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Internet Settings\Zones\4" /v 2500 /t REG_DWORD /d 00000000 /f REG ADD "HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Internet Settings\Zones\0" /v 2500 /t REG_DWORD /d 00000000 /f REG ADD "HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Internet Settings\Zones\1" /v 2500 /t REG_DWORD /d 00000000 /f REG ADD "HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Internet Settings\Zones\2" /v 2500 /t REG_DWORD /d 00000000 /f REG ADD "HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Internet Settings\Zones\3" /v 2500 /t REG_DWORD /d 00000000 /f REG ADD "HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Internet Settings\Zones\4" /v 2500 /t REG_DWORD /d 00000000 /f REG ADD "HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Policies\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Internet Settings\Zones\2" /v 2101 /t REG_DWORD /d 00000000 /f REG ADD "HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Internet Explorer\Zoom" /v ZoomFactor /t REG_DWORD /d 000186a0 /f REG ADD "HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Internet Explorer\Main" /v FrameMerging /t REG_DWORD /d 00000000 /f  IE Capabilities setting ie.browserCommandLineSwitches = -private ie.ensureCleanSession = true      Appreciate any pointers to help resolve the issue.

column3: IE driver is not recognized
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 7  Selenium-Java Version:  3.4.0  Browser:  IE   Browser Version: IE11   ## Expected Behavior - Newly opened tab should be focused by IEServer driver (32bit).  ## Actual Behavior - New IE opened tab is not comes under a new window when we use getWindowHandles. it is returning 1 as size but 2 windows are opened.  ##Description - IE driver is not controlled by WebDriver when it opens in a new tab, even though 2 windows are opened. It shows 1 window is present.   ## Steps to reproduce - 1. Open a IE browser using IEServer32.exe driver. 2.Using a 'Robot' class, opene a new tab by pressing "CTRL+T" 3.Get the count of windows after a new tab opened. Expected : 2 windows Actual : 1 window.  ##Selenium Code to reproduce:                 System.setProperty("webdriver.ie.driver","Path to driver");                 WebDriver driver = new InternetExplorerDriver(); 		driver.get(""); 		Thread.sleep(2500); 		 	Robot robot = new Robot();         robot.delay(3000);         robot.keyPress(KeyEvent.VK_CONTROL);         robot.keyPress(KeyEvent.VK_T);         robot.delay(3000);         robot.keyRelease(KeyEvent.VK_T);         robot.keyRelease(KeyEvent.VK_CONTROL); 		Thread.sleep(2500); 		Set parentHandle = driver.getWindowHandles();  		System.out.println(parentHandle.size()); 		for (String winHandle : driver.getWindowHandles()) { 		    driver.switchTo().window(winHandle);  		} 		driver.navigate().to("");

/favicon.ico on the IEDriverServer that can interleave with the command processing.  Is it possible that one of those requests is toggling the is_waiting_ boolean to true, causing the session creation command to hang?  I'm not set up to compile IEDriver, but I'm happy to reproduce the issue with an instrumented binary, if that would make it easier to track down the bug.  Thanks!

column3: Selenium IDE does not work with Firefox version 55
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 7  Selenium Version:  IDE  Browser:  Firefox   Browser Version:  55.0   ## Expected Behavior - All options should be usable and work  ## Actual Behavior - With Firefox version 55.0 Selenium IDE becomes unusable.  Unexpected Exception JavaScript errors pop up whenever trying to use anything, including using options such as "logs", "reference", and UI-Element" in the lower half of the screen.  The options in "File" become unusable, and trying to create a new test case by right-clicking in the "Test Cases" frame does nothing.  ## Steps to reproduce - I was only able to reproduce this in FireFox version 55.0, which was released on August 8th.  Downgrading to v54.0.1 fixed the issue.

column3: UnsupportedCommandException: mouseMoveTo Driver3.5.3 FF 55.0.3
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 7  Selenium Version:  3.5.3  Browser:  Firefox    Browser Version:  55.0.3   ## Expected Behavior - Perform Hover ## Actual Behavior - org.openqa.selenium.UnsupportedCommandException: mouseMoveTo Build info: version: '3.5.3', revision: 'a88d25fe6b', time: '2017-08-29T12:54:15.039Z' ## Steps to reproduce -  --EDIT: Added an extract of a Test case and a min class implementation--  As soon as startTest is called it invokes act.moveToElement which fails with the above mentioned exception.   ``` public class BewertungExport extends TestCase {      @Before     public void setupTest() {         Assume.assumeTrue("may not run test due to a previous error", mayRunTest());     }      @Test     public void gesamtBewertung() throws Exception{          try         {             StartPage startPage = new StartPage(driver);             startPage.login(user.getUsername(), user.getPassword());              startPage.startTest(4, "Dashboard"); 	    startPage.clickElement(By.xpath(("//*[@id=\"abh\"]/div[3]/div/div[2]/div[2]/div[2]/div[3]/div/div/a"));              ReviewsPage reviewsPage = new ReviewsPage(driver);             reviewsPage.clickExport();         }         catch (Exception e)         {             System.err.println("Error while exporting: " + e.getMessage());             errors.append(e.getMessage());         }     } }   public class StartPage extends BasePage {     public StartPage(WebDriver driver)     {         super(driver);     }          public StartPage login(String userName, String password) throws Exception     {         fillInput(By.id("passwordinput-rf"), password, "Insert Password");         fillInput(By.id("user-rf"), userName, "Insert username");         clickElement(By.id("login-button-rf"), "click login button"); 		         return this;     }      public void startTest(int menuIndex, String linkText) throws Exception {         HomeScreenData hD = TestSuite.getHomeScreenData(); 		Actions act = new Actions(driver); 		act.moveToElement(findElement(By.linkText(hD.menuLogin[menuIndex]))).click().build().perform(); 		clickElement(By.linkText(linkText));     }       } ```

column3: System.InvalidOperationException : Collection was modified; enumeration operation may not execute.
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 7  Selenium Version:  3.4.0.0  Browser:  Chrome  Sometimes I'm getting this exception that is thrown from selenium: --InvalidOperationException    at System.ThrowHelper.ThrowInvalidOperationException(ExceptionResource resource)    at System.Collections.Generic.List`1.Enumerator.MoveNextRare()    at System.Collections.Generic.List`1.Enumerator.MoveNext()    at OpenQA.Selenium.Support.PageObjects.DefaultPageObjectMemberDecorator.CreateTypeForASingleElement()    at OpenQA.Selenium.Support.PageObjects.DefaultPageObjectMemberDecorator.get_InterfaceProxyType()    at OpenQA.Selenium.Support.PageObjects.DefaultPageObjectMemberDecorator.CreateProxyObject(Type memberType, IElementLocator locator, IEnumerable`1 bys, Boolean cache)    at OpenQA.Selenium.Support.PageObjects.DefaultPageObjectMemberDecorator.Decorate(MemberInfo member, IElementLocator locator)    at OpenQA.Selenium.Support.PageObjects.PageFactory.InitElements(Object page, IElementLocator locator, IPageObjectMemberDecorator decorator)    at OpenQA.Selenium.Support.PageObjects.PageFactory.InitElements(ISearchContext driver, Object page)    at CommonLogic.PageObject.PageObjectBase..ctor(MyWebDriver driver) in C:\Git\auto-tests\Shared\CommonLogic\CommonLogic\PageObject\PageObjectBase.cs:line 35    at BEPortalPageObject.LoginPage..ctor(MyWebDriver driver) in C:\Git\auto-tests\Tests\BEPortal\BEPortalPageObject\LoginPage.cs:line 25 Result Message:	 System.Reflection.TargetInvocationException : Exception has been thrown by the target of an invocation.   ----> System.InvalidOperationException : Collection was modified; enumeration operation may not execute. ## Expected Behavior - I'm using PageFactory in my page object and it's happens sometimes ```cs   public class LoginPage     {        [FindsBy(How = How.CssSelector, Using = @"a[href='/register?redirect=/']")]         private IWebElement _newUserButton;          [FindsBy(How = How.Name, Using = "password")]         private IWebElement _passwordTextField;     } ``` ## Actual Behavior - No exception should be thrown, or more meaningful exception should be thrown with help how to avoid it.  ## Steps to reproduce - Happens sometimes for unknown reason.

column3: File upload in Selenium grid fails with JSON parse error
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 7  Selenium Version:  3.4.0 (grid/node + python bindings)  Browser:  Google Chrome (but probably all browsers/platforms)  Browser Version:  58.0.3029.110 (64-bit)   ## Expected Behavior - Local file is uploaded to the Selenium node that is part of a grid.  ## Actual Behavior - There is a JSON parse error: selenium.common.exceptions.WebDriverException: Message: Failed parsing JSON source: JsonReader at line 1 column 20712896 path $.file to Json.  The line/column offset in the error is always the same.  ## Steps to reproduce - 1) Create a 20 MiB random file (e.g. dd if=/dev/urandom of=20MiB.file bs=1M count=20). It should be a file that will be >20MiB when compressed with Python's zipfile module and then base64 encoded. I don't see this problem with smaller files (files of a few megabytes). 2) Upload this file to a browser in a Selenium grid: ``` from selenium import webdriver from selenium.webdriver.common.desired_capabilities import DesiredCapabilities grid = "http://:4444/wd/hub" d = webdriver.Remote(command_executor=grid,\                      desired_capabilities=DesiredCapabilities.CHROME) d.get("https://fiddle.jshell.net/2f15yz1a/show/") d.switch_to.frame(0) e = d.find_element_by_id("f") e.send_keys(r"C:\20MiB.file") ``` I then get this exception:  ``` Traceback (most recent call last):   File "", line 1, in    File "C:\Python27\lib\site-packages\selenium\webdriver\remote\webelement.py", line 345, in send_keys     value = self._upload(local_file)   File "C:\Python27\lib\site-packages\selenium\webdriver\remote\webelement.py", line 550, in _upload     raise e selenium.common.exceptions.WebDriverException: Message: Failed parsing JSON source: JsonReader at line 1 column 20712896 path $.file to Json ```

column3: Issues with Guava 23.0rc1 in URLChecker.java class
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 7  Selenium Version:  3.4.0  Browser:  Chrome  Browser Version:  59.0.3071.86  ## Expected Behavior - https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/d37a5cc4e853b35283ae4ebf1daca2d0b1e95a37/java/client/src/org/openqa/selenium/net/UrlChecker.java#L67  This URLChecker class should on construction create an instance of itself using a new SimpleTimeLimiter.  SimpleTimeLimiter comes from the guava project. This should run and return correctly.  ## Actual Behavior - As of Guava 23.0r1, the SimpleTimeLimiter constructor being used is private, and this will cause an IllegalAccessError when creating a new instance of the UrlChecker class.  You can see the new code for 23.0r1 that does this line 51 at:  https://github.com/google/guava/blob/master/guava/src/com/google/common/util/concurrent/SimpleTimeLimiter.java#L51  However, you can see on line 67: https://github.com/google/guava/blob/master/guava/src/com/google/common/util/concurrent/SimpleTimeLimiter.java#L67  that the developers have added in a create method.  It could be fixed as simply by changing: `public UrlChecker() {     this(new SimpleTimeLimiter(THREAD_POOL));   }` to `public UrlChecker() {     this(SimpleTimeLimiter.create(THREAD_POOL));   }`  However, it seems that older version of guava may not have included this create method, so this may not work unless a full transition to 23.0 is made in the future when it is actually released.  ## Steps to reproduce - Create a new instance of the chromedriver or attempt to call the default constructor on the UrlChecker class while having guava 23.0rc1 as your current version of guava.  This is a minor issue as you can prevent this error from occurring by downgrading your guava version, however, it is something that may need to be considered going forward.

column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 7  Selenium Version:  2.9.1 Browser:   Firefox?  Since Firefox version 48, Mozilla requires all add-ons to be signed. Until recently, Firefox support in Selenium was exclusively provided by an add-on. As this add-on is not currently signed, this solution does not work with the latest Firefox releases. As an alternative, Mozilla are working on a WebDriver specification compliant implementation named GeckoDriver. Please note that the specification is not complete, and that Selenium itself does not comply with the specification at this time. This means that features previously available through Selenium will not be available using GeckoDriver.  Any issue logged here for Firefox 48 or later will be closed as a duplicate of #2559. Our recommendation is to switch to GeckoDriver, or to continue testing on Firefox 45 until GeckoDriver is a viable option for you. column3: IEDriver dismisses unhandled prompt by default
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 7  Selenium Version:   3.5.3, IEDriverServer 3.5.1  Browser:   Internet Explorer  Browser Version:   11.0.9600.18762  ## Expected Behavior I get an allert and it not closes  ## Actual Behavior - IE dismisses my alert so that my test fails when I actually try to check that my alert is preset and check it's text;  It was ok on selenium 2.53.1  ## Steps to reproduce - 1. Create IE web driver like this:  ```java DesiredCapabilities capabilities = new DesiredCapabilities(); capabilities.setBrowserName("internet explorer"); capabilities.setCapability("disable-popup-blocking", true); capabilities.setCapability(CapabilityType.VERSION, "EDGE"); capabilities.setCapability(CapabilityType.PLATFORM, "WINDOWS"); capabilities.setCapability(CapabilityType.ACCEPT_SSL_CERTS, true); capabilities.setCapability(InternetExplorerDriver.IGNORE_ZOOM_SETTING, true); capabilities.setCapability(InternetExplorerDriver.INTRODUCE_FLAKINESS_BY_IGNORING_SECURITY_DOMAINS, true); capabilities.setCapability(InternetExplorerDriver.NATIVE_EVENTS, Methods.getCheckBoxState(IE_NATIVE_EVENTS) != 0); capabilities.setCapability(InternetExplorerDriver.IE_ENSURE_CLEAN_SESSION, true); capabilities.setCapability(InternetExplorerDriver.REQUIRE_WINDOW_FOCUS, Methods.getCheckBoxState(IE_REQUIRE_FOCUS) != 0); capabilities.setCapability(CapabilityType.UNEXPECTED_ALERT_BEHAVIOUR, UnexpectedAlertBehaviour.IGNORE); WebDriver driver = new InternetExplorerDriver(capabilities); ```  2. I have a page (which I cant provide here), so when I don't fill a field and press a button I get an Alert (default ie modal window). So I do click that button without filling a field to check alert text.

column3: Encoding problem. Non latin characters are not supported by Grid
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 10, Server 2016 Selenium Version:  3.5.+ Browser:  IE, Chrome, FF with latest versions and latest drivers Platform: .Net, Java  ## Expected Behavior - - Text with non latin characters e.g. "Über", "вебдрайвер" is typed (during send keys) as "Über", "вебдрайвер" - Locators with non latin characters processed in the same way e.g. ```//*[text()='Über']``` is received by hub/node as ```//*[text()='Über']```  ## Actual Behavior - - Text with non latin characters e.g. "Über", "вебдрайвер" is typed (during send keys) as "�ber", "??????????" - Locators with non latin characters processed in the same way e.g. ```//*[text()='Über']``` is received by hub/node as ```//*[text()='�ber']``` - In some cases even latin symbols sends with ? e.g. from string "some text" webdriver types "?s?o?m?e? ?t?e?x?t?"  ## Steps to reproduce - for .Net 1. Setup Selenium Grid Hub and Node with default configs. 2. By any way create app that will use WebDriver 3.  Initialize RemoteWebDriver e.g. ```IWebDriver driver = new RemoteWebDriver(gridUri, new FirefoxOptions())``` or ChromeOptions, or IE... 4. Try to do following:  ```                 driver.Navigate().GoToUrl("https://google.com");                 driver.Manage().Window.Maximize();                 var el = driver.FindElement(By.XPath("//*[@name='q']"));                 el.SendKeys("Über"); // CHECK typed symbols                 el.Clear(); // PAUSE HERE                 el.SendKeys("вебдрайвер"); // CHECK typed symbols ``` Without grid (using "local" web driver) all work fine. On selenium grid 3.3.* all work fine.

column3: Couldn't create RemoteWebDriver with v 3.4.0. Null pointer exception in Grid server
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 10 | 8.1 | Server 2016  Selenium Version:  3.4.0  Browser:  IE, Chrome, FF  Browser Version:  latest  Selenium target platform: .Net ## Actual Behavior -  [This commit](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/commit/1afc18be518f6e8eb9d574e0e141fce7a045dffb) causes null pointer exception in Grid server that prevents any tries to create RemoteWebDriver.  Some details: E.g. json sent as payload for command to Grid server to create Chrome instance (stat new session) is following: ``` {  "desiredCapabilities":  {    "browserName":"chrome","version":"","platform":"ANY","javascriptEnabled":true,"chromeOptions":{"args":["disable-infobars"],"prefs":{"download.prompt_for_download":true,"download.default_directory":"NULL"}}  },  "capabilities":  {   "firstMatch":[{"browserName":"chrome","javascriptEnabled":true,"chromeOptions":{"args":["disable-infobars"],"prefs":{"download.prompt_for_download":true,"download.default_directory":"NULL"}}}]  } ``` }  According to logic (of mentioned commit) if there is "capabilities" element in json, "desiredCapabilities" element should be found in "capabilities" and parsed as Map ``` if (map.has("capabilities")) { return new JsonToBeanConverter().convert(Map.class, map.getAsJsonObject("capabilities").getAsJsonObject("desiredCapabilities"));  } ``` But there is no inner element "desiredCapabilities" in "capabilities" (there is just element "firstMatch"). Verified with creating RemoteWebDriver for FF, Chrome and IE. So this peace of code return null in all cases of sending request to create new session during creating remote webdriver. And that cause null pointer exception in Grid.  Actually I could debug just .Net sources and possible I've missed some logic in java code. But if I remove whole "capabilities" element from request payload all works fine.  Some stacktrace exception info extracted from response in format "{classname} > {method} > {line}": ``` "java.util.HashMap > putMapEntries > -1" "java.util.HashMap > putAll > -1" column3: PageFactory.InitElements Does not work in Net Core as uses a deprecated dll from Net Framework
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 10 Pro Selenium Version:  3.4.0 Browser:  All  ## Expected Behavior -   PageFactory Init Elements   ## Actual Behavior - Warning is raised:  `System.TypeLoadException : Could not load type 'System.Runtime.Remoting.Proxies.RealProxy' from assembly 'mscorlib, Version=4.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=b77a5c561934e089'.    at OpenQA.Selenium.Support.PageObjects.DefaultPageObjectMemberDecorator.CreateProxyObject(Type memberType, IElementLocator locator, IEnumerable1 bys, Boolean cache)    at OpenQA.Selenium.Support.PageObjects.DefaultPageObjectMemberDecorator.Decorate(MemberInfo member, IElementLocator locator)    at OpenQA.Selenium.Support.PageObjects.PageFactory.InitElements(Object page, IElementLocator locator, IPageObjectMemberDecorator decorator)` Error is raised ` OneTimeSetUp: System.TypeLoadException : Could not load type 'System.Runtime.Remoting.Proxies.RealProxy' from assembly 'mscorlib, Version=4.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=b77a5c5 61934e089'.`  ## Steps to reproduce -  - Have latests Net Core 2 preview  - Create a test to search on google with PageFactory (Created this repo to reproduce https://github.com/Saetabis1/pageFactoryNetCoreIssue)  - run tests with dotnet test  ## Possible solution   - Switch from RealProxy to DispatchProxy in Net Core as here is told  https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/issues/4091 https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/tree/master/src/System.Reflection.DispatchProxy .   Kind Regards, Saetabis.

column3: DefaultWait Throws NoSuchElementException Before Timeout Elapsed Even When Added To IgnoreExceptionTypes
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 10 Enterprise  Selenium Version:  3.5.1  Browser:  Chrome   Browser Version:  Chrome Version 60.0.3112.113 (Official Build) (64-bit)   ## Expected Behavior - DefaultWait should not throw NoSuchElementException before DefaultWait.Timeout has elapsed if is added to DefaultWait.IgnoreExceptionTypes. ## Actual Behavior - Throws NoSuchElementException straight away. ## Steps to reproduce - `public static void Test2() { 	var curdir = Directory.GetCurrentDirectory(); 	string chromeDriverPath = Path.Combine(curdir, @"bin\Debug\netcoreapp2.0"); 	IWebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver(chromeDriverPath); 	try 	{ 		driver.Navigate().GoToUrl("http://google.com"); 		IWebElement body = driver.FindElement(By.TagName("body"));  		DefaultWait wait = new DefaultWait(body); 		wait.Timeout = TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10); 		wait.PollingInterval = TimeSpan.FromSeconds(1); 		wait.IgnoreExceptionTypes(typeof(NoSuchElementException)); 		wait.Message = "Couldnt find within 10 seconds";  		Func waitSearchbox = new Func((IWebElement webElement) => 		{ 			return webElement.FindElement(By.Id("non-existent-id")); 		});  		Console.WriteLine(DateTime.Now); 		IWebElement searchBox = wait.Until(waitSearchbox); 		Console.WriteLine(DateTime.Now); 	} 	finally 	{ 		driver.Close(); 		driver.Quit(); 	} }`

column3: Selenium Chromedriver driver.get nor find_element works on background
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 10 64-bit  Selenium Version:  3.3.3 Celery Version:  3.1.23  Browser:  Chrome   Browser Version:  ChromeDriver 2.29 and Chrome 57.0.2987.133   ## Expected Behavior -  The automated task does not complete when kicked off by celery using the following command: ``` from tasks import myworker1 myworker1.apply_async((inputArgs[1],     inputArgs[2],     inputArgs[3],     inputArgs[4]),    expires=90); ``` ## Actual Behavior - The task goes to an url logs in and then I need to redirect to another url after that. The problem occurs when after logged in I need to click or redirect to a different url within the same web page. Found out that driver.get("http://myurl.com") does not load. Thus I tried to click on the elements that in exchange will be like just going to the url directly. However, 'driver.find_element_by_css_selector("button.goTo").click()' does not work either. It never finds it. Options for chromedriver:  ``` chrome_options = webdriver.ChromeOptions() chrome_options.add_argument('--start-maximized'); chrome_options.add_argument('--disable-extensions') chrome_options.add_argument("--incognito") chrome_options.add_argument("--disable-plugins-discovery") self.driver = webdriver.Chrome(executable_path='C:/Chrome/chromedriver.exe',chrome_options=chrome_options) ``` Does running chrome in the background affects the driver.get or finding elements in a web page? Because if I run the same task without celery by calling it directly (the browser opens) it just works: ``` from tasks import myworker1 myworker1(arg1,arg2,arg3,arg4) ```  ## Steps to reproduce - Push a task to the queue via celery using the command '.apply_async' like explained above. driver.get or find_element will stop working after initial web page changed because of being redirected after log in to a website.

column3: Grid: Node not registering successfully to the hub in v3.4 (Node running on VirtualBox)
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 10 (Running on virtualbox on Ubuntu 16.04)  Selenium Version:  3.4  Browser:     Browser Version:     ## Expected Behavior - Node Should stay Registered to the Hub  ## Actual Behavior - The node never seems to be successfully registered at all. According to the logs, it is registered and then unregistered after just a few seconds.    ## Steps to reproduce - I am getting this issue with Selenium 3.4. Here is the complete scenario -  1)  Hub is running on my ubuntu machine 2) Ran node on the same machine as well as another machine and they both are working fine 3) Started one Win10 VM on the Ubuntu machine (running hub) using Oracle VirtualBox. Disabled Windows Firewall 4) Using the same selenium version (3.4), trying to start a node on this VM - **Node logs say** - Node is registered to the hub and ready to  use  **Command used** : java -Dwebdriver.edge.driver="driver_path" -jar selenium-server-standalone-3.4.0.jar -role node -hub http://[IP]:4444/grid/register  **Hub Logs** - ``` 19:30:14.787 INFO - Unregistering the node http://10.0.2.15:5555 because it's been down for 60030 milliseconds 19:30:14.787 WARN - Cleaning up stale test sessions on the unregistered node http://10.0.2.15:5555 19:30:15.278 INFO - Registered a node http://10.0.2.15:5555 19:30:35.290 INFO - Marking the node http://10.0.2.15:5555 as down: cannot reach the node for 2 tries ``` Issue Same as https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/issues/3631

column3: moveToElement() not working with dynamic popups (dotnet)
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 10 Selenium Version:  Webdriver v3.5.1, Firefox.Webdriver v0.18.0 Browser:  Firefox Nightly Browser Version:  57.0a1 (2017-08-24) (64-Bit)  ## Expected Behavior - Performing a ContectClick action on a DataTable appends a contextmenu with elements to the clicked tr. MoveToElement() should move to the specified element that was appended before  ## Actual Behavior - MoveToElement fails with a StaleElementReference Exception (see SeleniumLog_MoveToElement), whereas FindElements() returns the elements successfully. Also MoveByOffset() and then clicking on the offset is working as expected (see SeleniumLog_MoveByOffset)  ## Steps to reproduce - Rightclick on a DataTable element (or most likely also anything else), that triggers a custom popup (not the standard Firefox contextmenu). Call actions.MoveToElement(elementThatGotAppendedByPopup).  A snippet of the actual HTML looks like this: ```                                             Ausschneiden                 Drehen                 Auftrag entfernen                             ```  And the actual test code excerpt that's failing looks like this: ``` action.ContextClick(Browser.Driver.FindElement(By.XPath(Tours.TableElementConstructor + "/tr[2]/td[5]"))).Build().Perform(); // this is finding the correct elements var popup = Browser.Driver.FindElements(By.CssSelector("div.ti_popup_item")); // not working version /*action.MoveToElement(popup[1]).Click().Build().Perform();*/ // working version action.MoveByOffset(10, 40).Click().Build().Perform(); ``` TableElementConstructor being a const string of: "//table[@Id='DataTables_Table_0']/tbody"  Trace logs are attached below. Please tell me if you need any more information.  [Logs.zip](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/files/1251714/Logs.zip)

column3: PlatformNotSupportedException when using RemoteWebDriver in C# and .NET Core 2.0
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 10 Selenium Version:  Selenium.WebDriver 3.6.0 C#, .NET Core 2.0 Browser:  RemoteWebDriver -->  Browser Version:  na  ## Expected Behavior - Connects to RemoteWebDriver VM.  ## Actual Behavior - Throws this error: System.PlatformNotSupportedException : Operation is not supported on this platform.    at System.Net.SystemWebProxy.GetProxy(Uri destination)    at System.Net.ServicePointManager.ProxyAddressIfNecessary(Uri& address, IWebProxy proxy)    at System.Net.ServicePointManager.FindServicePoint(Uri address, IWebProxy proxy)    at System.Net.HttpWebRequest.get_ServicePoint()    at OpenQA.Selenium.Remote.HttpCommandExecutor.MakeHttpRequest(HttpRequestInfo requestInfo)    at OpenQA.Selenium.Remote.HttpCommandExecutor.Execute(Command commandToExecute)    at OpenQA.Selenium.Remote.RemoteWebDriver.Execute(String driverCommandToExecute, Dictionary`2 parameters)    at OpenQA.Selenium.Remote.RemoteWebDriver.StartSession(ICapabilities desiredCapabilities)    at OpenQA.Selenium.Remote.RemoteWebDriver..ctor(ICommandExecutor commandExecutor, ICapabilities desiredCapabilities)    at MicroEdge.DonorCentral.Automation.Common.WebDriver.RemoteWebDriverConfiguration.CreateRemoteWebDriver() in C:\Users\Windows 10  Seems related to this error: https://github.com/Azure/azure-iot-sdk-csharp/issues/140  ## Steps to reproduce - This is generic test that can reproduce this issue. Will require SL credentials to execute.  public class UnitTest1 {  [Fact] public void Test1() { Uri bsuri = new Uri("http://ondemand.saucelabs.com:80/wd/hub"); IWebDriver driver; DesiredCapabilities caps = new DesiredCapabilities(); caps.SetCapability(CapabilityType.BrowserName, "chrome"); caps.SetCapability(CapabilityType.Version, "49"); caps.SetCapability(CapabilityType.Platform, "Windows 7"); caps.SetCapability("username", ""); caps.SetCapability("accessKey", ""); caps.SetCapability("name", "testing"); driver = new RemoteWebDriver(bsuri, caps);  driver.Navigate().GoToUrl("http://www.google.com"); Console.WriteLine(driver.Title); IWebElement query = driver.FindElement(By.Name("q")); query.SendKeys("SauceLabs"); query.Submit(); Console.WriteLine(driver.Title);  driver.Quit();  } }

column3: How to use 1 Driver(Appium) instead of 2 Different Drivers(Appium and Web) for Android and Windows Automation ??
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 10 Selenium Version:  Selenium 3.4 Browser:  Multiple  I am working on a framework based on selenium. We are creating and executing script of  **Web , Android Web and Hybrid App** using selenium Grid  For Web , we are using the **RemoteWebDriver** to initialise the **webDriver** for all the browsers(Firefox,Chrome,IE) For which the code is  : -  **WebDriver driver = new RemoteWebDriver(sURL, cap);**  For Android Web and Hybrid App we are using **AndroidDirver** to initialise the **AppiumDriver**  **AppiumDriver driver = new AndroidDriver(sURL, oCap);**  Now to perform different validations for Windows Web , we are using WebDriver and to perform validations on Andorid web and Hybrid , We are using Appium Driver.  Now ,typecasting Android Driver to WebDriver is working fine. But when trying to typecast RemoteWebDriver to AppiumDriver it is throwing error :  **org.openqa.selenium.remote.RemoteWebDriver cannot be cast to io.appium.java_client.AppiumDriver**  I want to now use only **one Driver preferably Appium driver** to run the scripts on both Platforms(Windows and Android).  **Is there a way of how I can Use only one driver for all type of my Testcases as AppumDriver will give more and better options for automating the hybrid apps on Android ???**

column3: openWindow with selenium-html-runner-3.5.0 fails if target is a variable containing a URL
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 10 Selenium Version:  Html Runner-3.5.0 Browser:  Firefox Browser Version:  55.0.2 (64-bit) ## Expected Behavior - New tab or window opened with target URL ## Actual Behavior - HTML Runner prepends the base URL to the target URL resulting in a URL like http://localhost:8082/http://localhost:8082/somplace ## Steps to reproduce - Store a URL in a variable, and use the variable as the openWindow target e.g.     	storeAttribute 	css=#118 > a@href 	targetURL   	openWindow 	${targetURL} 	targetWinId    This works fine except when run from HTML Runner, i.e. works when run from SeleniumIDE and as a JUnit test.  Just a brief look at org.openqa.selenium.server.htmlrunner.CoreTestCase suggested that the case where value maybe a variable is not handled.  This is the command line I am using: ``` java -Dwebdriver.gecko.driver=../geckodriver-v0.18.0-win64/geckodriver.exe -jar selenium-html-runner-3.5.0.jar -htmlSuite "*firefox" "http://localhost:8082" OpenWindowTestSuite.html logs ```

column3: Actions broken when used after each other
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 10 Selenium Version:  3.5.2 Browser:  Firefox  Browser Version:  56.0b12 (64-Bit)  ## Expected Behavior -  Upon calling an action using the Actions API and calling another action after properly executing the first one, the second action gets executed. In this case, either moving up after clicking on a leaflet map, or moving down after having moved up.  ## Actual Behavior -  The same action happens twice.  ## Steps to reproduce - ``` Driver.Navigate().GoToUrl("https://leafletjs.com"); Actions action = new Actions(Browser.Driver); action.Click(Browser.Driver.FindElement(By.Id("map"))).Build().Perform(); // get rid of the popup var mapLocationBefore = Browser.Driver.FindElement(By.CssSelector("div.leaflet-map-pane")).GetAttribute("style"); // get translate-3d value action.SendKeys(Keys.ArrowUp).Build().Perform(); // should scroll up, but clicks popup again var mapLocationAfter = Browser.Driver.FindElement(By.CssSelector("div.leaflet-map-pane")).GetAttribute("style");  Assert.AreNotEqual(mapLocationAfter, mapLocationBefore); action.SendKeys(Keys.ArrowDown).Build().Perform(); // this moves up instead of down mapLocationAfter = Browser.Driver.FindElement(By.CssSelector("div.leaflet-map-pane")).GetAttribute("style");	// same location as the inital one, so before and after should match Assert.AreEqual(mapLocationAfter, mapLocationBefore); ```

column3: Selenium node does not pass the command line arguments to geckodriver
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 10 Selenium Version:  3.5.*, 3.4.0 Browser:  Firefox Browser Version:  55.0.3 (64-bit)  On versions 3.5.0 and higher, Selenium node does not pass the command line arguments to geckodriver.   ## Expected Behavior - If the node receives `moz:firefoxOptions` with `args`, all args should be passed to geckodriver so that Firefox can be started with the correct command line params.  ## Actual Behavior - Args are not being passed to geckodriver. Tested with `-profile`.  ## Steps to reproduce - 1. Have selenium grid set up and running 2. Create your browser with the following Firefox options: ``` FirefoxOptions options = new FirefoxOptions();  options.addArguments("-profile", "./firefoxprofile"); ``` 3. Observe the Selenium node log (args are not passed to geckodriver) ``` 12:32:14.961 INFO - Capabilities {androidServerPort=7100, appInstall=true, marionette=true, browserName=firefox, serverPort=5769, moz:firefoxOptions={args=[-profile, ./firefoxprofile], prefs={}, }, platformName=ANY, version=, uuid=09af7ada-5a10-4840-a58b-358..., platform=ANY, } matched class org.openqa.selenium.remote.server.ServicedSession$Factory (provider: org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeDriverService) 1505935934992   geckodriver     INFO    geckodriver 0.19.0 1505935935008   geckodriver     INFO    Listening on 127.0.0.1:5137 1505935935586   mozrunner::runner       INFO    Running command: "C:\\Program Files (x86)\\Mozilla Firefox\\firefox.exe" "-marionette" "-profile" "C:\\Users\\Selenium\\AppData\\Local\\Temp\\rust_mozprofile.Fb9H6o79oRbe" ```  ## Variations - - Reproducible using Selenium v3.5.0, v3.5.1, v3.5.2, v.3.5.3 using geckodriver v0.16, v0.17, v0.18, v0.19 - Using Selenium v3.4.0 and geckodriver v0.19, the browser is started with the correct args, but Selenium hangs (the browser itself remains functional)

column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 10 Selenium Version:  2.9.1, IDE Browser:  Firefox  Since Firefox version 48, Mozilla requires all add-ons to be signed. Until recently, Firefox support in Selenium was exclusively provided by an add-on. As this add-on is not currently signed, this solution does not work with the latest Firefox releases. As an alternative, Mozilla are working on a WebDriver specification compliant implementation named GeckoDriver. Please note that the specification is not complete, and that Selenium itself does not comply with the specification at this time. This means that features previously available through Selenium will not be available using GeckoDriver.  Any issue logged here for Firefox 48 or later will be closed as a duplicate of #2559. Our recommendation is to switch to GeckoDriver, or to continue testing on Firefox 45 until GeckoDriver is a viable option for you. column3: Selenium Click is not working with IE11 in Windows 10
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 10 Selenium Version:   3.4.0 Browser:    Internet Explorer 11  Hi Team, I have the below scripts which was working perfectly fine in my laptop with Windows 7 and IE11.  I had to change my laptop with Windows 10 following which the same scripts is not performing Click action on Login.  It neither gives error. It simply moves on to the next line and fails. I have added the FEATURE_BFCACHE as per the config mentioned but still its not fixing the issue.   I tried with other application urls too but still its not performing the click action. Can you please check and help me address this issue.   Script: System.setProperty("webdriver.ie.driver", file.getCanonicalPath()); DesiredCapabilities caps = DesiredCapabilities.internetExplorer(); caps.setCapability(InternetExplorerDriver.REQUIRE_WINDOW_FOCUS, false); webDriver = new InternetExplorerDriver(caps); webDriver.findElement(By.id("Login")).click();  Test Case is to open the application url and enter username,password and click on Login. Its an intranet

column3: Selenium is hanging when go to the site that have Basic Authentication
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 10   Selenium Version:  3.5.3   Browser:  Microsoft Edge   Browser Version:  Microsoft Edge 40.15063.0.0 (64-bit)  ## Expected Behavior - The selenium will run next step or throw an exception.  ## Actual Behavior - The selenium is hanging  ## Steps to reproduce - Can you please use the java code below to reproduce this issue: ``` public class TestSeleniumEdge extends KeepToFileText {  	public static void main(String[] args) { 		try { 			// set edge driver path 			System.setProperty("webdriver.edge.driver", "path\\MicrosoftWebDriver.exe"); 			// create new EdgeDriver instance 			WebDriver webDriverEdge = new EdgeDriver(); 			// go to site that have Basic authentication 			webDriverEdge.get("https://www.engprod-charter.net/"); 			// selenium is hanging here 			// expected: the selenium run next step or throw an exception 			// TODO 		} catch (Exception e) { 			e.printStackTrace(); 		} 		System.out.println("Done!"); 	} ```  **Please help to investigate and let me know if any questions.** Thanks.

column3: Element is not clickable at point - C# - Chrome Driver
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 10  Selenium Version:  3.6.0, Visual Studio, C#  Browser:  Google Chrome   Browser Version:  2.31.488763 (32-bit)   ## Expected Behavior -  Click on found element  ## Actual Behavior -  I have an automation project using Selenium WebDriver in version 3.6 and the Chrome Driver. The software was working fine until it started to display the error  > Unhandled exception has occurred in your application. If you click Continue, the application will ignore this error and attempt to continue. If you click Quit, the application will close immediately. >  > unknown error: Element is not clickable at point (25, -9) (Session info: chrome=61.0.3163.100) (Driver info: chromedriver=2.31.488763 (092de99f48a300323ecf8c2a4e2e7cab51de5ba8),platform=Windows NT 6.1.7601 SP1 x86_64).    I'm using the .click () method to click on the element, and this always worked, I've never had any problems with the software running for months >   Searching the internet I found methods that even worked like using .SendKey () and IJavaScriptExecutor to give a scroll to the element. But the point is I never had to do this ..  Could it be some bug in this version of Selenium? Maybe Chrome Driver?  ## Steps to reproduce -

column3: location_once_scrolled_into_view change the element
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 10  Selenium Version:  3.4.3  Browser:  Firefox   Browser Version:  54.0.2   ## Expected Behavior - The correct link (the one to expand the experience section) should be clicked with or without calling location_once_scrolled_into_view on the button element before the clicking  ## Actual Behavior - If you call `btn.location_once_scrolled_into_view` before calling `btn.click()`, it does NOT work. The search text box on the navbar is clicked instead. This element was never selected in our code. If you comment the `btn.location_once_scrolled_into_view` line, it works correctly.  This line should not change the element , and thus should not change which element is clicked. See also the comment on the attached SSCCE   ## Steps to reproduce -   You need a LinkedIn account, and substitute the `username` and `password` variable with the username and password of your LinkedIn account  ``` from selenium import webdriver from selenium.webdriver.common.keys import Keys import time  url = "https://www.linkedin.com/in/orarbel/" username = "YOUR_USERNAME" password = "YOUR_PASSWORD"  def sessionKeyLogin(driver):     login_email_element = driver.find_element_by_id("session_key-login")     login_password_element = driver.find_element_by_id("session_password-login")     login_email_element.clear()     login_password_element.clear()     login_email_element.send_keys(username)     login_password_element.send_keys(password)     login_password_element.submit()     time.sleep(5)          driver = webdriver.Firefox() driver.get(url) time.sleep(5)  signin_link = driver.find_element_by_class_name("sign-in-link") signin_link.click() time.sleep(5) sessionKeyLogin(driver)  driver.get(url) time.sleep(5)  btn = driver.find_element_by_class_name("experience-section").find_element_by_css_selector(".pv-profile-section__see-more-inline.link") #If you comment the following line, it works, and the link to expand the experience section is clicked #If you un-comment the following lines, the search textbox on the navbar is clicked instead btn.location_once_scrolled_into_view time.sleep(5) btn.click() ```

column3: Firefox click on the wrong link even if the correct one is clickable
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 10  Selenium Version:  3.4.3  Browser:  Firefox   Browser Version:  54.0.2   ## Expected Behavior -  ## Actual Behavior - You call `.click()` on a link. Firefox scrolls the correct link into view. The link is now at the bottom of the viewport, and it is "clickable", that is, nothing hides it and it can be identified by its screen coordinates, as the following image shows  ![image](https://image.ibb.co/eEBZ4k/selenium_ff_link.png "Firefox link into view at the bottom of the viewport")  Since the link is clickable, this bug is not related to #4280  But then, the link below the correct one is clicked (this is the wrong link to click). In the following screenshot, taken in a new window (since in the Selenium window the correct link is at the bottom of the viewport), the correct link is in red, while the incorrect one that is clicked is in blue. ![image](https://preview.ibb.co/eC72qQ/selenium_ff_not_correct_link.png "")  Chrome works correctly  ## Steps to reproduce -    ``` from selenium import webdriver from selenium.webdriver.common.keys import Keys import time  username = "YOUR_USERNAME" password = "YOUR_PASSWORD"  css_selector = ".pv-profile-section__see-more-inline.link" url = "https://www.linkedin.com/in/sachindsharma/" section_name = "experience-section"  # Set this to False and it will work ff = True  def login(browser):     login_email_element = browser.find_element_by_id("login-email")     login_password_element = browser.find_element_by_id("login-password")     login_email_element.clear()     login_password_element.click()  # focus on the field     login_password_element.clear()     time.sleep(2)     login_email_element.send_keys(username)     login_password_element.send_keys(password)     login_password_element.submit()     time.sleep(2)              #MAIN if ff:     driver = webdriver.Firefox() else:     driver = webdriver.Chrome() driver.get("https://linkedin.com") time.sleep(5)  #Log in login(driver) time.sleep(2) driver.get(url) time.sleep(2)  #Click on links while True:     link_list = driver.find_element_by_class_name(section_name).find_elements_by_css_selector(css_selector)     count = len(link_list)     print("Found "+str(count)+" links")     if count==0:         break     for link in link_list:         print("Clicking on the link tag='"+link.tag_name+"' text='"+link.text+"'")         link.click()         time.sleep(5)  #driver.quit() print("Ended!!!") ```

column3: click() fails to bring clickability to an element which is not clickable
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 10  Selenium Version:  3.4.3  Browser:  Firefox   Browser Version:  54.0.1   ## Summary - This bug is related to #4280 but regards the `click()` function In #4280, the `location_once_scrolled_into_view()` function brought a link behind a navbar, rendering it not clickable, and the WebDriver failed to issue an exception In this report, the link is already behind a navbar, and the `click()` function fails to render the element _clickable_. (using the terminology I learnt in that report)  ## Expected Behavior - `click()` would render the element _clickable_ (uniquely selectable by its coordinates) and then click on it  ## Actual Behavior - The link is not clicked  ## Steps to reproduce -  Substitute username and password with the one of your LinkedIn account. Since the link is not clicked, you will enter an infinite loop. If you go in the browser windows and manually scroll up a bit (to have the link not only in the viewport but clickable), the link gets clicked, the loop finishes and the program concludes  ``` from selenium import webdriver from selenium.webdriver.common.keys import Keys import time  username = "caloman@email.com" password = "MarcoPolo32" css_selector = ".pv-profile-section__see-more-inline.link" url = "https://www.linkedin.com/in/enriqueaguilera/"  def sessionKeyLogin(driver):     print("Logging in")     signin_link = driver.find_element_by_class_name("sign-in-link")     signin_link.click()     time.sleep(5)     login_email_element = driver.find_element_by_id("session_key-login")     login_password_element = driver.find_element_by_id("session_password-login")     login_email_element.clear()     login_password_element.clear()     login_email_element.send_keys(username)     login_password_element.send_keys(password)     login_password_element.submit()     time.sleep(5)      #MAIN driver = webdriver.Firefox() driver.get(url) time.sleep(5)  #Log in sessionKeyLogin(driver)  #Without scrolling, the experience-section is not in the DOM and thus it is not found for i in range(7):     print("Scrolling")     driver.execute_script("window.scrollBy(0,500)")     time.sleep(2)  #Click on links exp_section = driver.find_element_by_class_name("experience-section")  #This will generate an infinite loop because the link is never clicked #If you go in the browser windows and manually scroll up a bit, the link gets clicked, the loop finishes and the program concludes while True:     link_list = exp_section.find_elements_by_css_selector(css_selector)     count = len(link_list)     print("Found "+str(count)+" links")     if count==0:         break     for link in link_list:         #if you uncomment this line, it works column3: .click() scrolls the element to the _top_ of the viewport instead of to the _bottom_
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 10  Selenium Version:  3.4.3  Browser:  Chrome    Browser Version:  59.0.3071.115 (Official Build) (64-bit)   ## Expected Behavior - What is written in #4280 "When you call .click, [...] WebDriver spec tells to scroll to to the **very bottom of viewport**, so the button is not overlapped by other elements and click successfully happens."  ## Actual Behavior - The element is scrolled to the **top** of the viewport instead of to the bottom of it. Since in the top there is a navbar, the element becomes hidden under the navbar, and an exception is throw saying that another element would receive the click If the element would be scrolled to the **bottom** of the viewport, as WebDriver specs say, it would be clicked correctly  ## Steps to reproduce -  ``` from selenium import webdriver from selenium.webdriver.common.keys import Keys import time  username = "YOUR_USERNAME" password = "YOUR_PASSWORD"  css_selector = ".pv-profile-section__see-more-inline.link" url = "https://www.linkedin.com/in/sachindsharma/" section_name = "experience-section"  def login(browser):     print("Login check 2")     try:         login_email_element = browser.find_element_by_id("login-email")     except NoSuchElementException:         print("NoSuchElementException caught")         return False     else:         # Execute if no exception occurred         print("LOGIN CHECK 2 TRIGGERED")         login_password_element = browser.find_element_by_id("login-password")         login_email_element.clear()         login_password_element.click()  # focus on the field         login_password_element.clear()         time.sleep(2)         login_email_element.send_keys(username)         login_password_element.send_keys(password)         login_password_element.submit()         time.sleep(2)         return True              def scroll(driver):     old_source  = driver.page_source     while True:         print("Scrolling")         driver.execute_script("window.scrollBy(0,500)")         time.sleep(2)         new_source = driver.page_source         if new_source == old_source:             break         else:             old_source = new_source      #MAIN #driver = webdriver.Firefox() driver = webdriver.Chrome() driver.get("https://linkedin.com") time.sleep(5)  #Log in login(driver) time.sleep(2) driver.get(url) time.sleep(2)  #Without scrolling, the experience-section is not in the DOM and thus it is not found scroll(driver)  #Click on links exp_section = driver.find_element_by_class_name(section_name)  while True:     link_list = exp_section.find_elements_by_css_selector(css_selector)     count = len(link_list)     print("Found "+str(count)+" links")     if count==0:         break     for link in link_list:         print("Clicking on the link tag='"+link.tag_name+"' text='"+link.text+"'")         link.click()         time.sleep(5)  #driver.quit() print("Ended!!!") ```

column3: RemoteWebDriver doesn't return platform version
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Win 7/Win10  Selenium Version:  3+  Browser:  Any  ``` @BeforeTest(alwaysRun = true)     public void setVariables() {         env = new Properties();         HasCapabilities remote = (HasCapabilities) getWebDriver();         env.setProperty("Url", Configuration.baseUrl);         env.setProperty("Browser", remote.getCapabilities().getBrowserName());         env.setProperty("Browser Version", remote.getCapabilities().getVersion());         env.setProperty("Platform", remote.getCapabilities().getPlatform().name());         env.setProperty("Platform version", **remote.getCapabilities().getPlatform().getMajorVersion()** + "." +                 **remote.getCapabilities().getPlatform().getMinorVersion()** );         LOGGER.setLevel(Level.CONFIG);     } ```  Starting from version 3.1.0 of seleniumhq both remote.getCapabilities().getPlatform().getMajorVersion() and remote.getCapabilities().getPlatform().getMinorVersion() return "0" values.  For version 3.0.1 and below it works like a charm.  Zip file with diff between versions 3.0.1 and 3.3.1 is attached.  [3.3.1-3.0.1.zip](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/files/946659/3.3.1-3.0.1.zip)
