column3: firefox downloading(updating) addons when running tests
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Win 7 x64  Selenium Version:  3.4.0  Browser:  Firefox   Browser Version:  53.0 64-bit   ## Expected Behavior - disabled auto update for addons  ## Actual Behavior - When running my tests firefox driver stops executing commands because it starts downloading some things. Sometimes it resumes after download, sometimes fails because of timeout for page load. Still, even if it resumes, the delay for download is big, like a few minutes sometimes.  Here's the log: ``` 1493190654998   addons.productaddons    INFO    sending request to: https://aus5.mozilla.org/update/3/GMP/53.0/20170413192749/WINNT_x86_64-msvc-x64/en-US/release/Windows_NT%206.1.1.0 %20(x64)/default/default/update.xml 1493190656309   addons.productaddons    INFO    Completed downloading document 1493190656675   addons.productaddons    INFO    downloadXHR File download. status=200 1493190656684   addons.productaddons    INFO    Downloaded file will be saved to C:\Users\L094540\AppData\Local\Temp\tmpaddon-c40aec 1493190658529   addons.productaddons    INFO    downloadXHR File download. status=200 1493190658536   addons.productaddons    INFO    Downloaded file will be saved to C:\Users\L094540\AppData\Local\Temp\tmpaddon-2e96c4 ```  I have added the following preferences to the profile that I'm creating in test setup method ``` ffprofile.setPreference("app.update.enabled", false); ffprofile.setPreference("app.update.service.enabled", false); ffprofile.setPreference("app.update.auto", false); ffprofile.setPreference("app.update.staging", false); ffprofile.setPreference("app.update.silent", false); ``` however the result is the same. column3: Actions Drag&Drop doesn't work
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Win 7  Selenium Version:  2.43.1  Browser:  Chrome    Browser Version: Chrome 57.0.2987.133 / Chrome driver 2.29.461591   ## Expected Behavior - I'm testing Drag&Drop features in GWT application. Test consist of dragging random rows in DataGrid to random positions in it.  ## Actual Behavior - Selenium succesfully selects rows, but Drag&Drop feature doesn't work correctly. It seems like _clickAndHold()_ method stops holding _WebElement_ when _moveToElement()_ is in process. Is it a Selenium 2.43.1 bug? Or Selenium can't correctly work with GWT events?  ## Steps to reproduce - I tried something like this:     _new Actions(driver).dragAndDropBy(draggableRow, x, y).perform();_ and i also tried to make an action chain by myself like this:     _new Actions(driver)       .clickAndHold(draggableRow)       .moveToElement(targetRow, x, y)       .release()       .build()       .perform();_

column3: Linux Selenium Grid hub server reporting as a node with IE on Windows Capabilities
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Ubuntu 16.04.2 LTS  Selenium Version:  3.4  Browser:  Internet Explorer  Browser Version:  Any   java -version openjdk version "1.8.0_131" OpenJDK Runtime Environment (build 1.8.0_131-8u131-b11-0ubuntu1.16.04.2-b11) OpenJDK 64-Bit Server VM (build 25.131-b11, mixed mode)  ## Expected Behavior - Message: System.InvalidOperationException : Error forwarding the new session cannot find : Capabilities [{browserName=internet explorer, javascriptEnabled=true, version=, platform=WINDOWS}] TearDown : System.NullReferenceException : Object reference not set to an instance of an object.  ## Actual Behavior - Message: System.InvalidOperationException : The best matching driver provider org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeDriver can't create a new driver instance for Capabilities [{browserName=internet explorer, version=, platform=WINDOWS}] Build info: version: '3.0.1', revision: '1969d75', time: '2016-10-18 09:48:19 -0700' System info: host: 'asburyselenium-virtual-machine', ip: '127.0.1.1', os.name: 'Linux', os.arch: 'amd64', os.version: '4.4.0-31-generic', java.version: '1.8.0_121' Driver info: driver.version: unknown TearDown : System.NullReferenceException : Object reference not set to an instance of an object.  ## Steps to reproduce -  We are running selenium-server-standalone-3.4.0.jar in hub mode, with the jar just downloaded fresh. To demonstrate this bug, I'm not running any nodes at all, but it happens if I have one or more nodes running. But the error will only occur when it round-robins to the Linux server to try to run the IE on Windows test.  `java -jar selenium-server-standalone-3.4.0.jar -role hub`  This shows: > DefaultRemoteProxy (version : 3.0.1) > id : http://10.64.1.58:5555, OS : mixed OS > BrowsersConfiguration > browserTimeout: 0 > debug: false > help: false > port: 5555 > role: node > timeout: 1800 > cleanUpCycle: 5000 > host: 10.64.1.58 > maxSession: 1 > capabilities: Capabilities [{seleniumProtocol=WebDriver, browserName=firefox, maxInstances=5, platform=LINUX}] > capabilities: Capabilities [{seleniumProtocol=WebDriver, browserName=chrome, maxInstances=5, platform=LINUX}] > capabilities: Capabilities [{seleniumProtocol=WebDriver, browserName=internet explorer, maxInstances=1, platform=WINDOWS}] > downPollingLimit: 2 > hub: http://192.168.25.80:4444/grid/register > id: http://10.64.1.58:5555 > hubHost: 192.168.25.80 > hubPort: 4444 > nodePolling: 5000 > nodeStatusCheckTimeout: 5000 > proxy: org.openqa.grid.selenium.proxy.DefaultRemoteProxy > register: true > registerCycle: 5000 > remoteHost: http://10.64.1.58:5555 > unregisterIfStillDownAfter: 60000  First, I'm surprised that it says that it is a MixedOS, since it is linux. Second, I'm surprised that the hub is advertising browser capabilities at all, since it is a hub only (although perhaps I don't understand DefaultRemoteProxy well enough!).  Since the hub is reporting IE on Windows capabilities, it means that every other request I make for a IE on Windows RemoteWebDriver fails. ([Others have seen this problem as well.](https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/selenium-users/fenxMSFcAYo))  Sample Code: ```  using NUnit.Framework; using OpenQA.Selenium; using OpenQA.Selenium.Support.UI; using OpenQA.Selenium.Remote; using OpenQA.Selenium.IE; using System;  namespace CRMWebFormTesting {      public class UnitTest1 {          protected IWebDriver Driver;         private static Uri remoteWebDriverUri = new Uri("http://192.168.25.80:4444/wd/hub");          [Test]         public void TestMethod1() {             Driver.Navigate().GoToUrl("http://www.google.com");              try {                 WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(Driver, System.TimeSpan.                 FromSeconds(30));                 wait.Until(ExpectedConditions.ElementIsVisible(By.Id("hplogo")));                  Console.WriteLine("Found element.");             } catch (OpenQA.Selenium.WebDriverTimeoutException) {                 Console.WriteLine("Could not find element.");             }         }          [SetUp]         protected void SetUp() {             DesiredCapabilities capabilities = new DesiredCapabilities();              capabilities = DesiredCapabilities.InternetExplorer();             //capabilities = DesiredCapabilities.Chrome();             capabilities.SetCapability(CapabilityType.Platform, new Platform(PlatformType.Windows));              Driver = new RemoteWebDriver(remoteWebDriverUri, capabilities, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));         }          [TearDown]         protected void TearDown() {             Driver.Quit();         }     } } ```

column3: Popu-Menu Problem (bug ?) on Facebook
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Ubuntu 16.04 server (production) / Linux Mint 18 (dev) Selenium Version:  3.0.2 used with ChromeDriver 2.27 through Python 3.5.2 Browser:  Chromium 57.0.2987.98 (64 bit) / Chrome 58.0.3029.81 (64 bit) Browser Version: Chromium 57.0.2987.98 (64 bit) / Chrome 58.0.3029.81 (64 bit)  ## Expected Behavior - I am trying to locate a menu Item using xpath in order to click on it.  ## Actual Behavior - I have a case which works and one in which it does not.  Here is the case which works ![menu ok](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/6010464/25329727/a8e2f18a-28fa-11e7-92fe-b89a98b07f6c.png) And here is the Python code I use:          try:             # wait for the presence of the settings arrow down button             l_settings = WebDriverWait(self.m_driver, 15).until(                 EC.presence_of_element_located((By.XPATH, '//a[contains(@class, "_5lxs")]')))              l_settings.click()         except EX.TimeoutException:             self.m_logger.critical('Did not find settings arrow down button')             self.dump_html()             raise          try:             # wait for the presence of the log-out button             l_logoutButton = WebDriverWait(self.m_driver, 15).until(                 EC.presence_of_element_located(                     (By.XPATH, '//a[@class="_54nc" and contains(@data-gt, "menu_logout")]')))              l_logoutButton.click()         except EX.TimeoutException:             self.m_logger.critical('Did not find logout button')             self.dump_html()             raise  The first click displays the Facebook settings menu and the second selects the "logout" option. This code works without any problem.  The case **which does not work** is the following: ![menu fail](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/6010464/25330067/e8feea3e-28fb-11e7-81ac-57953aed29d1.png) It seems very similar to the previous one (click on a link to make a pop-up menu appear and then select one of the menu items). Here is the code that I use:              try:                # The link to make the pop-up menu appear                 l_modeLink = p_story.find_element_by_xpath(                         './/div[contains(@class, "UFILikeSentence")]//div[@class="_3scp"]' +                         '//div[contains(@class, "uiPopover")]/a')                  l_modeLink.click()             except EX.NoSuchElementException:                 self.m_logger.info('No mode selector')               try:                  # Waiting for the pop-up menu to appear                  l_menu = WebDriverWait(self.m_driver, 10).until(                      EC.presence_of_element_located((By.XPATH, '//ul[@class="_54nf"]')))                   # scanning through all the menu items                  for l_item in l_menu.find_elements_by_xpath('.//div[@class="_3scn"]'):                      l_text = l_item.text                      l_html = l_item.get_attribute('outerHTML')                       # click on the one which contains the string "(unfiltered)"                      if re.search('\(unfiltered\)', l_html+l_text):                           l_item.click()  The first click makes the pop-up menu appear and the second is supposed to select the 3rd menu item. The behavior I obtain is strange but highly repeatable. For the first such pop-up menu on a Facebook page, it works. But for the second (and thereafter), it fails. In the latter case, this is what happens:  - The variable `l_text` **is empty** for all menu items, as if they contained no text. - However, the variable `l_html` contains the expected HTML fragment which **does contain some text!** (This is the reason why I test the presence of the "(unfiltered)" string not only on `l_text` but on `l_html + l_text` - The click fails with an error indicating the element is not visible. However, it IS clearly visible as I can see on the browser as the script is executing. If I add a wait contition on the visibility of the element, it timeouts however long the delay.  As can be seen on the screenshots, the implementation of the two pop-up menus are similar (both are place within a `div` of class `uiContextualLayerPositioner`) However, one is placed at the end of the body element (the one which works) while the one is at the beginning of the global page container div (the one which does not). I do not know if this has any influence.  The behavior is the same both on my dev environement (Mint 18 / Chrome) and on my production environment (Ubuntu 16.04 / Chromium)  ## Steps to reproduce - See code above.  If the issue is with Google Chrome consider logging an issue with chromedriver instead: https://sites.google.com/a/chromium.org/chromedriver/help --> I will do that too

column3: selenium/javascript/node/selenium-webdriver/example/google_search_test.js fails
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Ubuntu 14.04 Selenium Version:   selenium-webdriver@3.3.0 Browser:   Google Chrome 57.0.2987.133 Browser Version:   57.0.2987.133 (64-bit) Node: 6.5.0, 6.9.4, 7.5.0  ## Expected Behavior -  Beginners examples selenium/javascript/node/selenium-webdriver/example/google_search_test.js pass  ## Actual Behavior -  it 'works with promises' fails  ## Steps to reproduce -  First - Hello from Europe/Austria(not Australia, ahaha :bowtie: ). It is a localisation problem, but nevertheless very distracting for a selenium beginner.  First let me quote https://support.google.com/chrome/answer/173424?visit_id=0-636275415019771099-1854089045&rd=1 > Change the language of your Chrome browser (Windows & Chromebook only) You can set Chrome to show all settings and menus in the language you want. This option is only available on Windows and Chromebook computers. On Mac or Linux? Chrome will automatically display in the default system language for your computer. ...  Hm, why, but anyway ...  ```bash joma@kopernikus-u:~/entwicklung/nodews/vuejs-laracasts/episode-selenium-basics/node_modules$ cat /etc/default/locale LANG="en_US.UTF-8" LC_NUMERIC="de_AT.UTF-8" LC_TIME="de_AT.UTF-8" LC_MONETARY="de_AT.UTF-8" LC_PAPER="de_AT.UTF-8" LC_NAME="de_AT.UTF-8" LC_ADDRESS="de_AT.UTF-8" LC_TELEPHONE="de_AT.UTF-8"  LC_MEASUREMENT="de_AT.UTF-8" LC_IDENTIFICATION="de_AT.UTF-8" ``` Dunno why, but google/chrome ignores my very LANG. Other story.  `it('works with generators')` passes, as it uses ncr -> http://www.google.com/ncr. ncr is no-country-redirection. So `until.titleIs` stays the expected english.   `it('works with promises')` does use `https://www.google.com/`(no `/ncr`), so gets `de` localized, then  `until.titleIs` turns "webdriver - Google-Suche".  TL;DR; use `http://www.google.com/ncr` to make these tests work globally.  P.S. Executing ```LANG="en_US.UTF-8" mocha -t 20000 selenium-webdriver/example/google_sea rch_test.js``` passes even without ncr.   P.S.2 ```LANG="en_US.UTF-8" mocha -t 20000 selenium-webdriver/example/google_sea rch_test.js``` does not work anymore. Chrome UI **is** localized to english(settings are in english, notification bar is `Chrome is being controlled by automated test software`). But as of now Google redirects me to `google.at`, although my test requests `http://www.google.com/`. Hence the title turns  german again. :expressionless:

column3: Add Firefox Developer Edition fallback
column4: ## Meta - OS:  OSX 10.11.6 Selenium Version: selenium-python 3.4.3  Browser:  Firefox Developer Edition 56.0b10  ## Issue - In its process to discover the Firefox binary, on Darwin WebDriver currently looks up `/Application/Firefox.app` and `~/Applications/Firefox.app`.  On developer machines, it wouldn't be too unlikely to have [Firefox Developer Edition](https://www.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/developer/) installed as it provides additional devtools and features, but if it *replaces* Firefox on the machine WebDriver will not work.  ## Solution Add `/Application/FirefoxDeveloperEdition.app/Contents/MacOS/firefox-bin` to the lookup list.

column3: Error handling when no Firefox binary is found
column4: ## Meta - OS:  OSX 10.11.6 Selenium Version: selenium-python 3.4.3 Browser: Firefox Developer Edition 56.0b10  ## Issue - On Windows and OSX, if no firefox binary is found (e.g. due to #4687) `_get_firefox_start_cmd` will return an empty string and ultimately an unclear message about capabilities ("Unable to find a matching set of capabilities") rather than the clear RuntimeException it raises for generic unices.

column3: iOS platform does not exist
column4: ## Meta - OS:  OSX Selenium Version:  3.5.2 (head of repo) Browser:  iOS Safari Browser Version:  iOS 10.3  ## Expected Behavior - Using Selenium Grid the platformName would remain unchanged (keep behavior from 3.4)  ## Actual Behavior - With Selenium Grid the platformName is overridden by platform in ImmutableCapabilities because iOS is not defined in Platform.java  ## Steps to reproduce - (already found a temporary fix with help from Simon and Jim) Run an iOS test against SauceLabs with 3.4 and 3.5. As part of NewSessionPayload (in 3.5) when creating the capabilities iOS is an unrecognized platform so platformName (originally iOS) is set to platform (Mac), providing a bad set of capabilities for the test to actually run.

column3: Resource Timing API not showing correct resources in Selenium
column4: ## Meta - OS:  OSX Selenium Version:  3.4.3 Browser:  Firefox Browser Version:  54.0.1   ## Steps To Reproduce - I have geckodriver latest version installed and I am running latest Firefox version. I wrote a selenium script to just open a URL in firefox and keep the browser open (I am not calling driver.close() or driver.quit())  Here is what the script looks like  ``` from selenium import webdriver driver = webdriver.Firefox() driver.get("https://www.nrk.no/") ```    Now, the website is just reloaded again, so that the resources are fetched from cache. NOTE: I refreshed by just pressing enter in the address bar  The number of resources reported by Resource Timing API is < 40. Same is the discrepancy with the number of resources in Developer Tools in Networks tab. This is happening for every website.    This is not happening if I just run plain Firefox and refresh the page in the same way. The resources number match always, irrespective of the number of times I refresh the web page.  ## Expected Behavior - Number of resources for the refresh should almost be same as first reload  ## Actual Behavior - Number of resources for refresh is very less than the first reload

column3: Browser Window not getting Focus Sometimes in Legacy Mode (even with Native Events)
column4: ## Meta - OS:  OpenSUSE 42.2 64-bit Selenium Version:  3.5.3 Browser:  Firefox ESR Browser Version:  FF45ESR and FF52ESR  ## Expected Behavior - When "native event" support is enabled (as we've been doing since Selenium v2), browser window should get focus properly, and it did for v2.53.1 in FF45ESR.  (In our case, certain elements don't act properly without focus.)  ## Actual Behavior - In Legacy Mode and any FF, from FF45ESR to FF52ESR to FF56, native events seem broken in that the browser no longer seems to give the window focus properly after the get() call is made on the driver.  ## Steps to reproduce - Focus works properly in FF52ESR with new gecko driver (non-legacy) mode.  Before I go to the trouble of creating a repro-case, what is the status of "native event" support in Legacy Mode?  Will it be supported?  Or is it going to be left "as is"?

column3: It is not longer possible to check if WebElement is gone from DOM with ExpectedConditions
column4: ## Meta - OS:  N/A Selenium Version:  3.4.0 Browser:  N/A Browser Version:  N/A  On Selenium 3.0.1 it was possible to wait until a WebElement was not longer present in the DOM by: ``` public void waitForElementGone(WebElement webElement, int timeOutInMillis) {   waits(timeOutInMillis)       .until(ExpectedConditions.invisibilityOfAllElements(Collections.singletonList(webElement)));  } ```  Since the Java 8 refactor on ExpectedConditions class this does not longer work as the new `isInvisible()` method is not catching the `NoSuchElementException`: ```     private static boolean isInvisible(WebElement element) {         try {             return !element.isDisplayed();         } catch (StaleElementReferenceException var2) {             return true;         }     } ```  `isInvisible()` should be implemented in a similar way as this other method that it is working correctly: ```     public static ExpectedCondition invisibilityOfElementLocated(final By locator) {         return new ExpectedCondition() {             public Boolean apply(WebDriver driver) {                 try {                     return Boolean.valueOf(!ExpectedConditions.findElement(locator, driver).isDisplayed());                 } catch (NoSuchElementException var3) {                     return Boolean.valueOf(true);                 } catch (StaleElementReferenceException var4) {                     return Boolean.valueOf(true);                 }             }              public String toString() {                 return "element to no longer be visible: " + locator;             }         };     } ```

column3: Safari Technology Preview (STP) can not be used with selenium hub.
column4: ## Meta - OS:  MacOS Sierra 10.12.6 Selenium Version:  3.5.2 (server) Browser:  Safari Browser Version:  TP 37  ## Expected Behavior - When I instantiate a RemoveWebDriver with safari options set to use TP, I expect to to launch a safari TP browser. ## Actual Behavior - But the hub instantiates the stable safari browser 10.1.2. ## Steps to reproduce - Create a single node hub on MacOS with safari as browser. Launch a remote session with technologyPreview capability set to true.  After analysis, the bug seems to be located in [ServicedSession](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/8db389076bd2d5b4384345777908d9b4f8ec2c12/java/server/src/org/openqa/selenium/remote/server/ServicedSession.java#L147) where we do not pass any capabilities when creating the driver service. Therefore, SafariDriverService [will be instantiated with default SafariOptions](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/20ae4f916196ad885923839f1da6455cc74c62af/java/client/src/org/openqa/selenium/safari/SafariDriverService.java#L45). In consequence, [The default Safari browser is used](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/20ae4f916196ad885923839f1da6455cc74c62af/java/client/src/org/openqa/selenium/safari/SafariDriverService.java#L45)

column3: Error parsing capabilities.chromeOptions.mobileEmulation.deviceMetrics.width in Selenium 3.5.0
column4: ## Meta - OS:  macOS 10.12.6 Selenium Version: 3.5.0 Browser:  Chrome Browser Version:  60.0.3112.101 (Official Build) (64-bit)  ## Expected Behavior -  Setting `capabilities.chromeOptions.mobileEmulation.deviceMetrics.width = ` does not raise an error. This behavior worked in Selenium v3.4.0.  ## Actual Behavior -  ```text selenium.common.exceptions.WebDriverException: Message: unknown error: cannot parse capability: chromeOptions from unknown error: cannot parse mobileEmulation from unknown error: 'width' must be an integer   (Driver info: chromedriver=2.31.488774 (7e15618d1bf16df8bf0ecf2914ed1964a387ba0b),platform=Mac OS X 10.12.6 x86_64) (WARNING: The server did not provide any stacktrace information) ```  ## Steps to reproduce -  1. Start a selenium server process  ```bash $ java -Dwebdriver.chrome.driver=.selenium/chromedriver/2.31-x64-chromedriver -jar .selenium/selenium-server/3.5.0-server.jar ```  2. Invoke below python script that will connect to the started selenium server instance and set the capabilities as listed above.  ```python from selenium import webdriver from selenium.webdriver.common.desired_capabilities import DesiredCapabilities  capabilities = {   "browserName": "chrome",   "chromeOptions": {     "args": [       "disable-infobars",       "incognito"     ],     "mobileEmulation": {       "deviceMetrics": {         "width": 360,         "height": 640,         "pixelRatio": 3       },       "userAgent": "Mozilla/5.0 (Linux; Android 5.0; SM-G900P Build/LRX21T) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/58.0.3029.110 Mobile Safari/537.36"     }   },   "platform_tag": "",   "build": "defaultbuild 2017-8-18 13:00",   "tunnelIdentifier": "pandora.fciis.net" }  driver = webdriver.Remote(   command_executor='http://127.0.0.1:4444/wd/hub',   desired_capabilities=capabilities)  driver.get("http://www.python.org") driver.close() ```  The script used above is saved in https://gist.github.com/stephenash/764d21034179d55fe7472dfe1ddd5620. That gist also contains the server output when using selenium v3.4.0 vs v3.5.0, and the full error output for the client.py script when connecting to v3.5.0.  Note that while this example uses python, I've been able to reproduce with nodejs (https://github.com/vvo/selenium-standalone/issues/299#issuecomment-323449530) as well.

column3: Chrome ignores preferences if headless flag is set
column4: ## Meta - OS:  macOS 10.12  Selenium Version: Ruby selenium-webdriver (3.4.4)   Browser:  Chrome  Browser Version: Chrome 60.0.3112.90 / Canary 62.0.3181.0   ## Expected Behavior -  I want to be able to configure preferences when in headless mode. Something like this:  ```ruby Capybara.register_driver :headless_chrome do |app|   Capybara::Selenium::Driver.new(     app,     browser: :chrome,     options: Selenium::WebDriver::Chrome::Options.new(     args: %w[headless disable-gpu],     prefs: {       "profile.managed_default_content_settings.images" => 2     }   ) ) end ```  However it does attempt to load images so the prefs setting isn't sticking.  But if I remove `headless` then the preference works. So headless mode doesn't seem to work with preferences. column3: selenium-webdriver examples broken by Google btnG element not clickable
column4: ## Meta - OS:  macOS 10.11.6 Selenium Version:  3.5.0 Browser:  Firefox, Chrome Browser Version:  Firefox 55, Chrome 60 GeckoDriver Version: 0.18.0 ChromeDriver Version: 2.31.488774  ## Expected Behavior - The [selenium-webdriver README](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/tree/master/javascript/node/selenium-webdriver#usage) inlines an example Node script that uses Firefox to load Google and search for "webdriver". Running that example script should succeed, and a variety of other scripts in the [example/ directory](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/tree/master/javascript/node/selenium-webdriver/example) should similarly succeed.  ## Actual Behavior - The script fails with the cryptic error message "WebDriverError" in Firefox and only a slightly better error message "ElementNotVisibleError: element not visible" if I modify it to use Chrome instead of Firefox. A variety of other scripts in the example/ directory similarly fail.  ## Steps to reproduce - > npm install selenium-webdriver > node node_modules/selenium-webdriver/example/google_search.js  After a bit of debugging, I discovered that the error is triggered by the statement `driver.findElement(By.name('btnG')).click()`, and Firefox appears to be returning the error message "element not interactable" (even though that doesn't get printed to my terminal, which is a different issue).  So it seems like both Firefox and Chrome see the "btnG" button on Google's home page as inaccessible (whether because "not visible" or "not interactable"). Presumably this is because of some change to that page that has broken these examples, not because of a regression in Selenium itself. Nevertheless, it manifests as broken examples in Selenium, which is why I'm filing it here.

column3: Python tests for Firefox don't use Marionette by default
column4: ## Meta - OS:  MacOS  Selenium Version:  latest master  Browser:  Firefox  Running the Python tests via `tox -c py/conftests.py` for Firefox sets the Marionette capability to `False`, which means that we currently do not run the tests with `geckodriver`. Is there a reason why we do not enable Marionette by default? Firefox 47 which was the last version to support the Firefox Driver is unsupported for a long time, same for Firefox 45ESR.  Source: https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/py/conftest.py#L101  @AutomatedTester, is there any reason for that default behavior?  ## Expected Behavior - Running the Python tests should use Marionette by default.  ## Actual Behavior - Marionette is not being used.  ## Steps to reproduce - - Clone the repository - Build Selenium: `./go py_prep_for_install_release` - Run tests: `tox -c py/conftests.py`

column3: Custom Firefox Profile is written to disk twice
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Linux Mint 18.1 (Ubuntu Xenial)  Selenium Version: 3.4.0    Browser:  Firefox   Browser Version:  45 ESR / 55b14 (64-bit)   ## Expected Behavior - Passed profile is written to disk only once. ## Actual Behavior - Profile configured at FirefoxOptions instance used for instantiating FirefoxDriver is written twice. ## Steps to reproduce - - take code below and fill in paths to your Firefox and Gecko Driver Service binaries - set a breakpoint at `org.openqa.selenium.firefox.FirefoxProfile.layoutOnDisk()` - run tests in debug session   ```java   @Test   public void testFFProfileLegacy() {         final FirefoxOptions opts = new FirefoxOptions();         opts.setBinary("");         opts.setLegacy(true);                           final FirefoxProfile profile = new FirefoxProfile();         profile.setPreference("my_test_bool", true);                  opts.setProfile(profile);          final WebDriver wd = new FirefoxDriver(opts);         wd.get("http://www.seleniumhq.org/");     }      @Test   public void testFFProfileMarionette() {         System.setProperty(GeckoDriverService.GECKO_DRIVER_EXE_PROPERTY, "");         final FirefoxOptions opts = new FirefoxOptions();         opts.setBinary("");         opts.setLegacy(false);                           final FirefoxProfile profile = new FirefoxProfile();         profile.setPreference("my_test_bool", true);                  opts.setProfile(profile);          final WebDriver wd = new FirefoxDriver(opts);         wd.get("http://www.seleniumhq.org/");    }  ```

column3: Open intent URL with xdg-open on Ubuntu
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Linux 1b617851a909 4.9.27-moby 1 SMP Thu May 11 04:01:18 UTC 2017 x86_64 x86_64 x86_64 GNU/Linux Selenium Version:   3.4.0 Browser:   Chrome  Browser Version:   Version 58.0.3029.81 (64-bit)  ## Expected Behavior - On opening `intent` links, the driver could not lose access to the browser.  ## Actual Behavior - xdg-open tries to open such content from the URL and the driver stops working.  ---  This is the trace of the error on trying a `driver.refresh` once the 'xdg-open' pops up: ``` objc[4481]: Class JavaLaunchHelper is implemented in both /Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/jdk1.8.0_131.jdk/Contents/Home/bin/java and /Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/jdk1.8.0_131.jdk/Contents/Home/jre/lib/libinstrument.dylib. That makes losing control over the driver, per example the driver is unable to do a navigate.refresh.  ---  Here is a screenshot of the xdg-open pops up: ![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/28141920/26150263/f7e33b72-3afd-11e7-9904-47923f71555c.png)  ---  Also I should comment that this is related to: https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/docker-selenium/issues/488

column3: [py] Crash when a window_switching_tests fails due to an unexpected exception
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Linux  Selenium Version:  git master   This is happening since the switch to use a global driver instance. The problem is that when a test fails with an exception the pytest_exception_interact() is called, which quits the driver, and then the teardown part of the close_windows fixture tries to close the windows, but window_handles fails because the driver process is no longer running. It can easily be fixed just by handling any exception in close_windows after the yield, but I don't know if there's a batter way to do it, like checking if the driver is still running or something like that. If handling exceptions is the only way, that's how I fixed it locally, so I can just submit a PR.  ## Expected Behavior -  The test that failed should be marked as F in the output, and the tests should continue starting a new driver after the failure without crashing.  ## Actual Behavior -  Test is marked as F, and then it crashes   ```test/selenium/webdriver/common/window_switching_tests.py column3: Python method ActionChains.pause implemented incorrectly
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Linux  Selenium Version:  3.6.0  Browser:  Firefox   Browser Version:  55.0.2  ## Expected Behavior - ActionChains.pause to work as described in documentation.  ## Actual Behavior -   ## Steps to reproduce -  The following code ```python from selenium import webdriver` from selenium.webdriver import ActionChains` from selenium.webdriver.common.keys import Keys`  driver = webdriver.Firefox() driver.get("http://www.google.com") elem = driver.find_element_by_name("q") actions = ActionChains(driver) actions.key_down(Keys.CONTROL, elem) actions.pause(1) actions.key_up(Keys.CONTROL, elem) actions.perform() driver.close() ```  generates the following error: ```python Traceback (most recent call last):   File "/media/work/_Down/coding/test.py", line 21, in      actions.pause(1)   File "/usr/local/lib/python3.5/dist-packages/selenium/webdriver/common/action_chains.py", line 319, in pause     self.w3c_actions.pointer_action.pause(self, seconds) TypeError: pause() takes from 1 to 2 positional arguments but 3 were given ```  which is likely caused by copy-paste: ````     def pause(self, seconds):         if self._driver.w3c:             self.w3c_actions.pointer_action.pause(self, seconds)             self.w3c_actions.key_action.pause(self, seconds)         else:             self._actions.append(lambda: self._driver.execute(                 time.sleep(seconds)             ))         return self ````

column3: with release of 3.4.0, 3.3.0 dockerized builds fail
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Linux  Selenium Version:  3.3.0  Browser:  firefox   ## Expected Behavior - we have dockerized tests that use maven, via gradle, to pull in selenium-java:3.3.0; we have been using this in tandem with geckodriver 0.15 for 6 or more weeks now, without a problem.  recently, our automated builds started to fail, despite not upgrading selenium or geckodriver. inspecting the logs, and it became apparent that, despite explicitly pegging to selenium-java:3.3.0, maven had started to pull in selenium-api (and other selenium bits) version 3.4.0! hence our tests began to fail.  attempts to peg to 3.3.0, e.g.  ```     compile (group: 'org.seleniumhq.selenium', name: 'selenium-remote-driver', version: '3.3.0'){force=true}     compile (group: 'org.seleniumhq.selenium', name: 'selenium-support', version: '3.3.0'){force=true}     compile (group:'org.seleniumhq.selenium', name:'selenium-api', version:'3.3.0'){force=true}     compile (group:'org.seleniumhq.selenium', name:'selenium-java', version:'3.3.0'){force=true} ```  were to no avail. yes, we pulled in all or ?mostly? 3.3.0, but tests failed with setWindowPosition (#3893) or `INFO: HTTP Status: '404' -> incorrect JSON status mapping for 'unknown error' (500 expected)` errors.  upgrading to 3.4.0 and geckodriver 0.16. yet other fails  upgrading to firefox 53, and STILL failures. this time org.openqa.selenium.UnsupportedCommandException: POST /session/75ed13ec-8201-2849-adee-6af35c9ed63f/log did not match a known command  this is a complete failblog. how can we expect to maintain stability if selenium updates cause our pegged, dockerized, tests to fail?  ## Actual Behavior -  ## Steps to reproduce -

column3: Unable to add new web-extension xpi to Firefox profile (missing install.rdf)
column4: ## Meta - OS:  FreeBSD 11, Debian Linux  Selenium Version:  3.4.3  Browser:  Firefox   Browser Version:  53.0.3 (64-bit)   ## Expected Behavior - The expected behavior is for selenium to start an instance of Firefox with the web extension as defined in the profile.  ## Actual Behavior - The following stack trace is produced: `Traceback (most recent call last):   File "", line 1, in    File "EnginePlug.py", line 128, in start     self.web=BrowserControls()   File "BrowserControlsProf.py", line 11, in __init__     profile=FirefoxProfile("/home/matthew/basic")   File "/usr/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/selenium/webdriver/firefox/firefox_profile.py", line 92, in add_extension     self._install_extension(extension)   File "/usr/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/selenium/webdriver/firefox/firefox_profile.py", line 271, in _install_extension     addon_details = self._addon_details(addon)   File "/usr/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/selenium/webdriver/firefox/firefox_profile.py", line 348, in _addon_details     raise AddonFormatError(str(e), sys.exc_info()[2]) selenium.webdriver.firefox.firefox_profile.AddonFormatError: ("[Errno 2] No such file or directory: '/tmp/tmpR1MBsu.auto.xpi/install.rdf'", ) ` ## Steps to reproduce - The following section of code is where the error is originating from: ` from selenium import webdriver from selenium.webdriver.firefox.firefox_binary import FirefoxBinary from selenium.webdriver.firefox.webdriver import FirefoxProfile  class BrowserControls():   browser={}    def __init__(self):       profile=FirefoxProfile("/home/matthew/basic")     binary=FirefoxBinary('/usr/local/bin/firefox')     self.browser=webdriver.Firefox(firefox_binary=binary, firefox_profile=profile) `  The /home/matthew/basic directory is a firefox profile directory with a web-extension I am developing and testing added to it. The web-extension is signed for personal (non-official) distribution. Unfortunately, I am not at liberty to share that snippet of code at the moment, but it is a very, very basic plugin that works fine if manually added to the browser after it is started by selenium, or if added to my normal, non-selenium browser.  However, the issue should be reproducible with the dummy extension described here, since this doesn't produce an install.rdf file in the .xpi bundle https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/Add-ons/WebExtensions/Your_first_WebExtension

column3: Selenium "No required SSL certificate was sent" from NGINX
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Fedora 25 Selenium Version:  3.5 Browser Version:  Firefox 55.0.1 (64-bit) Geckodriver: 0.18  ## Expected Behavior - Successfully open the Firefox browser with the starting index.html  ## Actual Behavior - 400 Bad Request No required SSL certificate was sent  ## Steps to reproduce - Run bellow python script. The site requires the certificate to create an SSL connection. Certificate can **NOT** be ignore. It is working if I import certificates(.pfx)  on the certificates section on the firefox. Seems as Selenium doesn't allow to send a certificate.  Code in Python: import unittest from selenium import webdriver from selenium.webdriver.common.keys import Keys from selenium.webdriver.firefox.firefox_binary import FirefoxBinary from selenium.webdriver.common.desired_capabilities import DesiredCapabilities  class webUnitTest(unittest.TestCase): 	""" Main web Unittest class """  	def setUp(self): 		""" Set Up driver for Firefox """ 		caps = DesiredCapabilities.FIREFOX.copy() 		caps['acceptInsecureCerts'] = True 		ff_binary = FirefoxBinary("/usr/lib64/firefox/firefox")  		self.browser = webdriver.Firefox(firefox_binary=ff_binary, capabilities=caps) 		self.browser.get("https://web.company.com") 		#self.browser.maximize_window()  	def test_title(self): 		""" Check Title of web """ 		self.assertEqual("Title", self.browser.title, "Title is not Title")  	def tearDown(self): 		""" Tear Down Browser """ 		browser.close()  if __name__ == "__main__": 	unittest.main()  **Return Error:** 400 Bad Request No required SSL certificate was sent

column3: NullPointerException when too much firefoxes are launched
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Centos linux version 2.6.32, tested and reproduced also on Windows 10 Selenium Version:  3.4.0 (java) + geckodriver 0.16.1  Browser:  Firefox  Browser Version:  45.8.0 (linux) 47.0.2 (windows)   ## Expected Behavior -  According to  waitUntilAvailable function in DriverService class, a WebDriverException should be thrown when Firefox driver server doesn't answer within 20 seconds.   ```  protected void waitUntilAvailable() throws MalformedURLException {     try {       URL status = new URL(url.toString() + "/status");       new UrlChecker().waitUntilAvailable(20, SECONDS, status);     } catch (UrlChecker.TimeoutException e) {       process.checkForError();       throw new WebDriverException("Timed out waiting for driver server to start.", e);     }   } ```   ## Actual Behavior - When process is not correctly started or stopped within 20sec, "process" variable is null so a NullPointerException is thrown on the process.checkForError() line  >  > Caused by: java.lang.NullPointerException > 	at org.openqa.selenium.remote.service.DriverService.waitUntilAvailable(DriverService.java:192) > 	at org.openqa.selenium.firefox.XpiDriverService.start(XpiDriverService.java:94) > 	at org.openqa.selenium.remote.service.DriverCommandExecutor.execute(DriverCommandExecutor.java:78) > 	at org.openqa.selenium.remote.RemoteWebDriver.execute(RemoteWebDriver.java:637) > 	... 27 more   ## Steps to reproduce - It happens after launching many firefoxes tests in parallel  (8 on my computer)

column3: touch.flick implemented not properly in ruby bindings
column4: ## Meta - OS:  any Selenium Version:  3.4.4 Browser:  any  ## Steps to reproduce -  ``` require 'selenium-webdriver'  username = "please put your upwork login here" password = "please put your upwork password here!"  mobile_emulation = { "deviceName" => "Nexus 5" } caps = Selenium::WebDriver::Remote::Capabilities.chrome(     "chromeOptions" => { "mobileEmulation" => mobile_emulation }) driver = Selenium::WebDriver.for :chrome, desired_capabilities: caps driver.extend Selenium::WebDriver::DriverExtensions::HasTouchScreen  driver.get "https://www.upwork.com/"  # go to login # open a menu e = driver.find_element css: '.right-off-canvas-toggle.menu-icon.pull-right' driver.touch.single_tap(e).perform # navigate to login sleep 1 e = driver.find_element xpath: '/html/body/div[1]/div/header[1]/div[2]/aside/nav/ul/li[7]/a' driver.touch.single_tap(e).perform # fill user_name and password e = driver.find_element id: 'login_username' e.send_keys username  e = driver.find_element id: 'login_password' e.send_keys password  e = driver.find_element xpath: '//*[@id="layout"]/div[2]/div/form/div[8]/button' driver.touch.single_tap(e).perform   sleep 10 e = driver.find_element xpath: '//body/ion-nav-view' # swipe left to unlock a menu driver.touch.flick(e, Integer(e.rect.width * (-0.75)), 0, 'normal').perform ``` this code will fails with next exception: ``` in `': unknown error: 'speed' must be a positive integer (Selenium::WebDriver::Error::UnknownError)   (Session info: chrome=60.0.3112.101)   (Driver info: chromedriver=2.30.477690 (c53f4ad87510ee97b5c3425a14c0e79780cdf262),platform=Mac OS X 10.12.6 x86_64) ``` if you modify a  last line like  `driver.touch.flick(e, Integer(e.rect.width * (-0.75)), 0, 'fast').perform` it will work but extremely slow since in this case speed will be 1 pixel per second since ``` module Selenium   module WebDriver     class TouchScreen       FLICK_SPEED = {normal: 0, fast: 1}.freeze ```  ## Solution - replace flick speed values ``` module Selenium   module WebDriver     class TouchScreen       FLICK_SPEED = {normal: 50, fast: 100}.freeze ``` and another thing is to allow user to pass integer values  because current implementation does not allow to do so see original code ``` when 4           element, xoffset, yoffset, speed = args            assert_element element           flick_speed = FLICK_SPEED[speed.to_sym]            unless flick_speed             raise ArgumentError, "expected one of #{FLICK_SPEED.keys.inspect}, got #{speed.inspect}"           end            @bridge.touch_element_flick element.ref, Integer(xoffset), Integer(yoffset), flick_speed ```  so it could be modified like ``` when 4           element, xoffset, yoffset, speed = args            assert_element element           flick_speed =  speed.is_a?(Numeric) && speed > 0 ?                                       Integer(speed) :                                       FLICK_SPEED[speed.to_sym]            unless flick_speed             raise ArgumentError, "expected one of #{FLICK_SPEED.keys.inspect}, got #{speed.inspect}"           end            @bridge.touch_element_flick element.ref, Integer(xoffset), Integer(yoffset), flick_speed ```  P.S. sorry for a miss format but I think I'm already found the root of the issue and I'm able to overcome this difficulty with a monkey patch but its not best solution...

column3: Find Element by ID should not find the root node
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Any Selenium Version:  3.4, but it doesn't really matter, it's an atoms problem Browser:  IEDriver, ChromeDriver, (legacy) FirefoxDriver  ## Expected Behavior -  ## Actual Behavior -  ## Steps to reproduce - Imagine a document with one element: ```html xyz ```  Locating `#child` inside of `#child` shouldn't work, but this fails: ```java WebElement child = driver.findElement(By.id("child")); try {   WebElement childer = child.findElement(By.id("child"));   fail("Should not locate element"); } catch (NoSuchElementException expected) { } ```  I think all the other location strategies work -- CSS selector and tag name both pass this test. So it's just the ID locator atom that's wrong.  Geckodriver/Marionette behaves correctly. (Of course, the W3C spec abolished locating elements by ID anyway; it gets rewritten to a CSS selector.)

column3: service.kill() doesn't unset address_
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Any Browser:  Any Language: JavaScript  ```js afterEach(done => {   const service = chrome.getDefaultService()   if (service.isRunning()) {     service.stop().then(() => {       service.isRunning() // expect: false, actual: true       done()     })   } else {     done()   } }) ```  I came across this oddity. This didn't seem like the intended behaviour. What seems to be going on is that `this.address_` isn't cleared by the `service.kill()` method. Happy to create a PR with a fix, but I wasn't sure if this was intended (seems unlikely) and what other variables need to be cleaned by `.kill()`.

column3: 3.5.2 Server: overriding a default driver service by a user-defined DriverProvider is not working
column4: ## Meta - OS:  any  Selenium Version:  3.5.2, Server  Browser:  any  ## Expected Behavior - A user-defined driver factory for a standard browser is used by the selenium server instead of the default.  ## Actual Behavior - The Selenium server loads a user-defined `DriverProvider` class, e.g., for Firefox, but is still using the default `FirefoxDriverService` although the custom capabilities match the factory key (browserName).  When I was debugging the `ActiveSessionFactory` constructor I encounterd that a new entry is added to the factory map instead of overriding the default. I think reason for this is that unintentially a new `Predicate` key object is generated for user-defined factories, see line 86:   > ...put(browserName(p.getProvidedCapabilities()),...  ## Steps to reproduce - Implement a DriverProvider for Firefox: ```Java import org.openqa.selenium.remote.server.DriverProvider;  public class FirefoxDriverProvider implements DriverProvider {     @Override   public Capabilities getProvidedCapabilities() {     return DesiredCapabilities.firefox();   }    @Override   public WebDriver newInstance(Capabilities capabilities) {     return newInstanceImpl(capabilities); // user-defined driver   } } ```  Add the full class name to the file   > .../META-INF/services/org.openqa.selenium.remote.server.DriverProvider  Run a Firefox test with selenium server and ensure that `newInstance()` of the user-defined class `FirefoxDriverProvider` is executed.

column3: geckodriver ignores environment settings using FirefoxBinary#setEnvironmentProperty()
column4: ## Meta - OS:  any  Selenium Version:  3.5.2 Java binding  Browser:  Firefox geckodriver   ## Expected Behavior - Using `FirefoxBinary#setEnvironmentProperty(...)` additional environment variables are set for the firefox process under test.  ## Actual Behavior - Additional environment variables are not set for geckodriver and firefox processes. Root cause seems to be that the environment properties map is not forwarded to the geckodriver Builder instance.   ## Steps to reproduce - Launch Firefox using `FirefoxBinary `and `FirefoxOptions`: ``` FirefoxBinary binary = new FirefoxBinary(); binary.setEnvironmentProperty("MY_ENV_VAR", "myvalue"); FirefoxOptions options = new FirefoxOptions().setBinary(binary); FirefoxDriver driver = new FirefoxDriver(options); ```

column3: Cannot pass customized DriverService to FirefoxDriver c'tor
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Any  Selenium Version:  3.4.0  Browser:  Firefox   Browser Version:  53.0 (64-bit)   ## Expected Behavior - It should be possible to pass an `DriverService` or `CommandExecutor`  instance as argument to some FirefoxDriver constructor.  ## Actual Behavior - FirefoxDriver constructors always use default DriverService and customized DriverService's cannot be passed as argument to any FirefoxDriver constructor.  ## Steps to reproduce - Attempt to create an instance of FirefoxDriver that takes an DriverService or CommandExecutor as argument. Use-cases where this is necessary: use a specific port for the driver service or some custom environment when creating the browser process.

column3: Scroll element into view with different strategies
column4: ## Meta - OS:  ALL Selenium Version:  3.x Browser:  ALL  Improvement: Implement a way to tell selenium how the scroll element into the view should behave. It could be told by capability or any other way, it's up to you. The most important part is that it should work across all the supported browsers.  Example: ScrollElementIntoView.Top ScrollElementIntoView.Center ScrollElementIntoView.Bottom  This would be nice to tell selenium once when it starts the browser and be able to change if needed during the test run. This is for flexibility. If no value is provided use Top as it is at the moment.

column3: W3C Spec Compliance: deprecate getPlatform and replace with getPlatformName
column4: ## Meta - OS:  All Selenium Version:  3.5.2 (head) Browser:  All Browser Version:  All  ## Expected Behavior - The W3C spec defines platformName to be the source of truth but this is not always the case (noticed while using the grid).  ## Actual Behavior -  In a handful of places (particularly inside the grid) getPlatform is still used which can lead to issues with platform overriding platformName (see https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/issues/4557), these should be migrated so we conform to the spec and provide a path for future users to migrate.  ## Steps to reproduce - N/A  ## Work to do Deprecate Capabilities.getPlatform() and replace with getPlatformName() - push for users to use the W3C proper method. Migrate all internal usages of getPlatform to the new getPlatformName so as to provide a W3C consistent experience.

column3: [WIKI] DesiredCapabilities page table badly formatted
column4: ## Meta - OS:  -  Selenium Version:  -  Browser:  -   Browser Version:  -   ## Expected Behavior - `Used by the selenium server for browser selection` table renders correctly:  | **Key** | **Type** | **Description** | |:--------|:---------|:----------------| | browserName | string   | The name of the browser being used; should be one of `android`,`chrome`,`firefox`,`htmlunit`,`internet explorer`,`iPhone`,`Pad`,`opera`,`safari`. | | version | string   | The browser version, or the empty string if unknown. | | platform | string   | A key specifying which platform the browser should be running on. This value should be one of `WINDOWS`,`XP`,`VISTA`,`MAC`,`LINUX`,`UNIX`,`ANDROID`. When requesting a new session, the client may specify `ANY` to indicate any available platform may be used. For more information see [[GridPlatforms](GridPlatforms.md)] |  ## Actual Behavior - `Used by the selenium server for browser selection` table contains rows with `|` symbols which are causing options to be missed   | **Key** | **Type** | **Description** | |:--------|:---------|:----------------| | browserName | string   | The name of the browser being used; should be one of `{android|chrome|firefox|htmlunit|internet explorer|iPhone|iPad|opera|safari}`. | | version | string   | The browser version, or the empty string if unknown. | | platform | string   | A key specifying which platform the browser should be running on. This value should be one of `{WINDOWS|XP|VISTA|MAC|LINUX|UNIX|ANDROID}`. When requesting a new session, the client may specify `ANY` to indicate any available platform may be used. For more information see [[GridPlatforms](GridPlatforms.md)] |   ## Steps to reproduce -  - Navigate to https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/wiki/DesiredCapabilities - Confirm table only contains first option for `browserName` and `platform`

column3: IEDriverServer causes memory leaks in iexplore.exe
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows 10 Selenium Version: 3.3.1 (Java) Browser:   Internet Explorer WebDriver: IEDriverServer Win32 3.3.0.0 Browser Version:  11.0.10240.17319  ## Expected Behavior - Memory consuming for browser processes shouldn't be affected by WebDriver. E.g. here is memory consuming graph for running test on Chome (about 5000 iterations):  ![chrome_about_5000_iterations_private_bytes](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/16087661/25181632/d6db093a-251a-11e7-95ef-622b0da9b246.png) ## Actual Behavior - Actually there are memory leaks while using Selenium for the automation especially with long-term tests. E.g. here is a graph for running test against IE browser:  ![ie_about_2000_iterations_private_bytes](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/16087661/25181714/10570178-251b-11e7-9cf6-0873f643c124.png)  ## Steps to reproduce - To reproduce the issue you can use simple test below which one will connect to the simple angular app [https://jsfiddle.net/dyyh2yzt/](https://jsfiddle.net/dyyh2yzt/) ``` public class AngularSPAppTest {     public WebDriver driver;     private static final String BROWSER = "ie";     public int i = 0;     @BeforeSuite     public void setupDriver() { 	switch (BROWSER) { 	case "chrome": 	    System.setProperty("webdriver.chrome.driver", "src/main/resources/chromedriver.exe"); 	    ChromeOptions options = new ChromeOptions(); 	    options.setExperimentalOption("excludeSwitches", Arrays.asList("ignore-certificate-errors")); 	    options.addArguments("--disable-extensions"); 	    options.addArguments("disable-infobars");  	    Map prefs = new HashMap(); 	    prefs.put("credentials_enable_service", false); 	    prefs.put("profile.password_manager_enabled", false); 	    options.setExperimentalOption("prefs", prefs); 	    driver = new ChromeDriver(options); 	    break; 	case "ie": 	    System.setProperty("webdriver.ie.driver", "src/main/resources/IEDriverServer.exe"); 	    DesiredCapabilities ieCapabilities = DesiredCapabilities.internetExplorer(); 	    ieCapabilities.setCapability(InternetExplorerDriver.INTRODUCE_FLAKINESS_BY_IGNORING_SECURITY_DOMAINS, 		    false); 	    driver = new InternetExplorerDriver(ieCapabilities); 	    break; 	} 	driver.manage().timeouts().implicitlyWait(10, TimeUnit.SECONDS); 	driver.manage().window().maximize();     }      @BeforeTest     public void goToPage() throws InterruptedException { 	driver.get("https://jsfiddle.net/dyyh2yzt/"); 	Thread.sleep(5000); 	driver.switchTo().frame("result");     }      @Test(invocationCount = 1000000)     public void simpleTest() throws InterruptedException { 	// Thread.sleep(3000); 	WebElement input = driver.findElement(By.xpath("//input[@ng-model='addMe']")); 	input.clear(); 	String text = "item " + i++; 	input.sendKeys(text); 	WebElement button = driver.findElement(By.xpath("//button[@ng-click = 'addItem()']")); 	button.click(); 	WebElement item = driver 		.findElement(By.xpath(String.format("//li[@ng-repeat = 'x in products'][text() = '%s']", text))); 	item.findElement(By.xpath(".//span[@ng-click='removeItem($index)']")).click();     }     @AfterSuite(alwaysRun = true)     public void closeDriver() { 	driver.quit();     } } ```

column3: TouchActions should inherit keyboard Actions
column4: ## Meta - OS:   WSL (Windows Subsystem for Linux) Selenium Version:   3.5.0 Browser:   Chrome --headless with [libudev-stub](https://github.com/therealkenc/libudev-stub)  Browser Version:   60  ## Expected Behavior - `TouchActions` should inherit `sendKeys()` and other keyboard `Actions`, as it currently is for the [Java version of selenium](https://seleniumhq.github.io/selenium/docs/api/java/org/openqa/selenium/interactions/touch/TouchActions.html)  ## Actual Behavior - To tap on a field and then send some keys we have to use `touchActions()` and a separate `sendKeys()`, losing the possibility to chain them all. Could it be useful and comfortable?

column3: getScreenshotAs() function can't get full website screenshot
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows7 Selenium Version:   Selenium 2.53 Browser:   Firefox 45.3.0 ESR  ## Actual Behavior - When I use getScreenshotAs() function to get screenshot,get the screenshot is incomplete,The screenshot's footer is empty. ## Steps to reproduce - public static void screenCapture1(TakesScreenshot drivername, String dirname,String filename) { 		// this method will take screen shot ,require two parameters ,one is 		// driver name, another is file name 		File scrFile = drivername.getScreenshotAs(OutputType.FILE); 		try { 			System.out.println("save snapshot path is:"+dirname+"/" + filename); 			FileUtils.copyFile(scrFile, new File(dirname+ "/"+filename)); 		} catch (IOException e) { 			System.out.println("Can't save screenshot"); 			e.printStackTrace(); 		} 	}

column3: In testSuite a failure as seen as success too!
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows7 Selenium Version:   2.9.1 Browser:   Firefox 52.1.1  When you execute a TestSuite containing several test cases, each test case seen as failure, is enumerated too as success. So enumeration of success is not real and to obtain correct number you have to substract number of test cases seen as failure. Normally a test case is seen as success OR as failure, not possible to have two status! In opposite if a test case is seen as succes it is not added as failure.  Systematic bug! Do you have an idea to fix it?

column3: Windows Server 2012, IE input disabled when running tests in service mode
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows Server 2012 Service Mode Selenium Version:   2.52.0 Browser:   Internet Explorer 11  ## Expected Behavior - Send keys fills input field.   ## Actual Behavior - In service mode IE 11 inputs will not take focus. It is impossible to fill out inputs. Buttons, Check boxes, radios all work fine. It is almost like the inputs are disabled. ```     it('should login', () => {         let userNameInput = $('#username');         let passwordInput = $('#password');         let loginSubmitButton = $('#submit');         let selectLocationButton = $('#select-location');          userNameInput.sendKeys(USERNAME);          passwordInput.sendKeys(PASSWORD);      });```

column3: Very slow text entry on IEDriverServer 3.5.1
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows Server 2012 Selenium Version:   3.5.3 (Java) Browser:   Internet Explorer Browser Version:   11  ## Issue -  When running tests in IE11 via the Selenium Grid (hub is grid version 3.1.0, node is version 3.5.3), if I use IE Driver 32bit 3.5.1, I experience very slow sendkeys() action (as has been documented in the past).   When I switch to IE Driver 32bit 3.4.0, I do not experience this.     I have spent some time researching solutions, and nothing I have found in Github, StackOverflow, etc works.    ## Steps to reproduce -  #### Webdriver definition `DesiredCapabilitiescaps = DesiredCapabilities.internetExplorer(); caps.setBrowserName("internet explorer"); caps.setCapability(InternetExplorerDriver.ENABLE_PERSISTENT_HOVERING, false); caps.setCapability(InternetExplorerDriver.IE_ENSURE_CLEAN_SESSION, true); caps.setCapability(InternetExplorerDriver.NATIVE_EVENTS, false); caps.setCapability(InternetExplorerDriver.REQUIRE_WINDOW_FOCUS, true); caps.setCapability(CapabilityType.ACCEPT_SSL_CERTS, true); caps.setJavascriptEnabled(true); `  I even tried `INTRODUCE_FLAKINESS_BY_IGNORING_SECURITY_DOMAINS`, but that did not help, so I am not continuing to try it.   #### IE settings - All the security zones set to protected mode ON - Advanced > Security> Enable 64-bit processes for Enhanced Protected Mode is unchecked. - Connnections > Lan Settings > Automatically Detect Settings is unchecked  ## Notes This may or not help, but I did not experience this issue until yesterday, and as far as I can tell nothing changed.  I have a test suite of around 500 tests, and when i kicked them off yesterday IE failed after around 50 tests because of a known bug in deleting cookies.  I restarted the suite (making no changes), and they failed after around 12 tests.  I added debugging to find where the tests started to hang, and then the first test failed. I fixed my cookies issue by using `JavascriptExecutor`, but in doing so this slow text issue surfaced.  I still cannot figure out why two days ago I had no issues with cookies or text on 64bit 3.5.1 and two days later I am  having to rewrite my cookie logic and deal with slow text, accomplishing this only on the 32bit driver.  Very, very odd.   Why would v.3.4.0 work, but v3.5.1 not work?  Is there a known issue with this driver as opposed to earlier versions?  Thanks

column3: Selenium 3.4.0 -Java : Selenium 3.4.0 does not works with Grid Configuration
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows 8 Selenium Version:   3.4.0 Browser:   Mozila Firefox  Browser Version:   53.0 (64-bit)  ## Expected Behavior - Selenium 3.4.0 (Java) should open Mozila Firefox browser with success.  ## Actual Behavior - Selenium 3.4.0 (Java) while attempting to open Mozila Firefox browser throws org.openqa.selenium.WebDriverException. ## Steps to reproduce - ![webdriverexception](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/26503213/25553784/5cd040ca-2cda-11e7-907d-ee0dfa5ed6c6.png)  ![seleniumgridconfig](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/26503213/25553798/a168414c-2cda-11e7-9a74-9ce0876945b3.png)  Code Snippet:  ``` package SeleniumGrid;  import java.net.MalformedURLException; import java.net.URL;  import org.openqa.selenium.Platform; import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver; import org.openqa.selenium.remote.DesiredCapabilities; import org.openqa.selenium.remote.RemoteWebDriver; import org.testng.annotations.Test;  public class testFirefoxonGrid  {  	@Test 	public void test1() throws MalformedURLException 	{ 		 		System.setProperty("webdriver.gecko.driver", "C:\\Utility\\BrowserDrivers\\geckodriver.exe"); 		DesiredCapabilities cap = DesiredCapabilities.firefox(); 		cap.setBrowserName("firefox"); 		cap.setCapability("marionette", true); 		cap.setPlatform(Platform.WINDOWS); 		URL url = new URL("http://localhost:4444/wd/hub"); 		WebDriver driver = new RemoteWebDriver(url, cap); 		driver.get("http://google.com/"); 		System.out.println("Title is : "+driver.getTitle()); 		driver.quit(); 		 	} } ```

column3: Platform Capabilities Overwritten Selenium JS 2.53.1 and 2.53.2
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows 7, Windows 8.1 and Window 10 Selenium Version:   2.53.1 and 2.53.2 Selenium Javascript Browser:   Internet Explorer and Edge  Browser Version:   IE 11.103 and Edge (all versions)  ## Expected Behavior - Pass desired capabilities for browser options along with a specific platform value, the framework should retain the original platform value.  The framework should send the very same platform capabilities to my selenium grid, if one is specified by the user.  browserName = internet explorer platform = **Windows 10** version = 11.103 `` ie options below included for completeness`` requireWindowFocus = true enablePersistentHover = true enableElementCacheCleanup = true ie.ensureCleanSession = true ie.forceCreateProcessApi = true   ## Actual Behavior -  When I pass in the below values, the framework (lib/capabilities.js) hardcodes "WINDOWS" as the platform.  ### Original browserName = internet explorer platform = **Windows 10** version = 11.103 `` ie options below included for completeness`` requireWindowFocus = true enablePersistentHover = true enableElementCacheCleanup = true ie.ensureCleanSession = true ie.forceCreateProcessApi = true  ### Framework Normalized Capabilities browserName = internet explorer platform = **WINDOWS** version = 11.103 `` ie options below included for completeness`` requireWindowFocus = true enablePersistentHover = true enableElementCacheCleanup = true ie.ensureCleanSession = true ie.forceCreateProcessApi = true  However, when I don't include the browser options, the framework uses my specified platform capability.  ### Original browserName = internet explorer platform = Windows 10 version = 11.103  ### Framework Normalized Capabilities browserName = internet explorer platform = Windows 10 version = 11.103  ## Steps to reproduce - ~~~~ //internally, this configuration receives a platform value of WINDOWS instead of Windows 10 var webdriver = require('selenium-webdriver'); var session = new webdriver.Builder() .usingServer('http://ondemand.saucelabs.com/wd/hub') .withCapabilities({   "browserName": "internet explorer",   "platform": "Windows 10",   "version": "11.103" }) .setIeOptions({   "options_": {     "requireWindowFocus": true,     "enablePersistentHover": true,     "enableElementCacheCleanup": true,     "ie.ensureCleanSession": true,     "ie.forceCreateProcessApi": true   },   "proxy_": null }) .setEdgeOptions({   "options_": {     "pageLoadStrategy": "eager"   },   "proxy_": null }) .build(); ~~~~

true); 	    driver = new EventFiringWebDriver(new InternetExplorerDriver(ieCapabilities)); 	    break; 	case "firefox": 		System.setProperty("webdriver.gecko.driver", "src/main/resources/geckodriver.exe"); 		FirefoxOptions geckoOptions = new FirefoxOptions() 		        .addPreference("log", "{level: error}") 		        .addCapabilities(new DesiredCapabilities( 		                ImmutableMap.of("pageLoadStrategy", "eager"))) 		        .setLogLevel(Level.SEVERE); 	    driver = new EventFiringWebDriver(new FirefoxDriver(geckoOptions)); 	    break; 	} 	driver.manage().timeouts().implicitlyWait(10, TimeUnit.SECONDS); 	// driver.manage().window().maximize();     }      @BeforeTest     public void goToPage() throws InterruptedException { 	driver.get("http://google.com");     }      @Test     public void moveToElementTest() { 	WebElement target = driver.findElement(By.name("q")); 	Actions actions = new Actions(driver).moveToElement(target); 	actions.build().perform();     }      @Test     public void moveByOffsetTest() { 	Actions actions = new Actions(driver).moveByOffset(500, 500); 	actions.build().perform();     }      @Test     public void moveToElementWithOffsetTest() { 	WebElement target = driver.findElement(By.name("q")); 	Actions actions = new Actions(driver).moveToElement(target, 50, 50); 	actions.build().perform();     }      @AfterSuite(alwaysRun = true)     public void closeDriver() { 	driver.quit();     }  } ```

column3: executeAsyncScript doesn't trigger ScriptTimeoutException properly
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows 7 x64 Selenium Version:   Selenium Java 3.5.3 with ChromeDriver 2.32 Browser:   Reproduced on Chrome 60.0.3112.113 64-bit  Browser Version:   Reproduced on Chrome 60.0.3112.113 64-bit  Detailed (verbosed) log of execution: https://gist.github.com/anonymous/b38e3a0cba84e2ae182a726484aba4c7  ## Expected Behavior - Following code (specifically, executeAsyncScript) should throw ScriptTimeoutException, because setScriptTimeout is set to 0 ns.   ``` System.setProperty("webdriver.chrome.driver", "C:\\chromedriver.exe"); System.setProperty("webdriver.chrome.verboseLogging", "true"); WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver(); driver.manage().timeouts().setScriptTimeout(1, TimeUnit.NANOSECONDS);  String script = "var callback = arguments[arguments.length - 1];" +         "var stringVar = 'abcd';" +          "callback(stringVar);";  Instant beforeScript = Instant.now(); String result = (String) ((JavascriptExecutor) driver).executeAsyncScript(script); System.out.println(result + " took time: " + Duration.between(beforeScript, Instant.now()).toMillis() + " ms"); ```  ## Actual Behavior -  Result successfully returned from script, but ScriptTimeoutException didn't triggered  ## Steps to reproduce -  Just run the code

column3: Chromedriver slower with --headless option
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows 7 x64 Selenium Version:   3.5.2 Browser:   Chrome Browser Version:   60.0.3112.113  ## Expected Behavior - Try to use --headless option with chromedriver to speed up scripts. ## Actual Behavior - All scripts in headless mode run twice as long. ## Steps to reproduce - Any simple tests. I use 2 get requests, load cookies, put data on site and request to site to generate one dynamic page. For me it was more then 1 minute with --headless option and 29 sec without it.

Anyone has any idea what the problem might be? Thanks. Petr

column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows 7 Selenium Version:   3.5.3 Java Browser:   IE 11, IEDriverServer 3.5.1.0  This code works as expected: ``` InternetExplorerOptions options = new InternetExplorerOptions(); options.requireWindowFocus(); InternetExplorerDriver driver = new InternetExplorerDriver(options); driver.get("http://www.amazon.com/"); WebElement dept = driver.findElement(By.xpath(".//*[@id='nav-link-shopall']/span[2]")); WebElement mouseDevice = driver.findElement(By.xpath(".//*[@id='nav-flyout-shopAll']/div[2]/span[7]/span")); WebElement echoall = driver.findElement(By.xpath(".//*[@id='nav-flyout-shopAll']/div[3]/div[7]/div[1]/div[1]/a[3]")); new Actions(driver).moveToElement(dept).pause(1000).perform(); new Actions(driver).moveToElement(mouseDevice).pause(1000).perform(); new Actions(driver).moveToElement(echoall).pause(1000).perform(); new Actions(driver).click().perform(); ```  This code does not work, does not perform acrions: ``` InternetExplorerOptions options = new InternetExplorerOptions(); options.requireWindowFocus(); InternetExplorerDriver driver = new InternetExplorerDriver(options); driver.get("http://www.amazon.com/"); WebElement dept = driver.findElement(By.xpath(".//*[@id='nav-link-shopall']/span[2]")); WebElement mouseDevice = driver.findElement(By.xpath(".//*[@id='nav-flyout-shopAll']/div[2]/span[7]/span")); WebElement echoall = driver.findElement(By.xpath(".//*[@id='nav-flyout-shopAll']/div[3]/div[7]/div[1]/div[1]/a[3]")); new Actions(driver)         .moveToElement(dept).pause(1000)         .moveToElement(mouseDevice).pause(1000)         .moveToElement(echoall).pause(1000)         .click().perform(); ```

column3: Selenium not working in internet explorer
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows 7 Selenium Version:   2.42.0 for JAVA Browser:   IE 11.0.9600  I have my selenium script written to regress a site. It was not maintained properly for a long time. Recently I have executed it and find it failing to start for all the browsers. I have updated the chromeDriver and I could run it on chrome, but it is still failing for IE and FF. Browser is getting invoked, but the scripts are not getting executed. Not  I have the driver IEDriverServer_Win32_2.42.0 and the path is also set..  Browser Version:   IE 11.0.9600  ## Expected Behavior - Browser should open and run the script ## Actual Behavior - IE is getting opened, but the script is not working further.  I am not able to see any errors in the logs also. ## Steps to reproduce -  public static InternetExplorerDriver objDriver;	 System.setProperty("webdriver.ie.driver","C:\\selPath\\IEDriverServer.exe");     objDriver= new InternetExplorerDriver();     objDriver.get("www.google.com");

column3: Please reopen issue 3767
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows 7  Selenium Version:   selenium-webdriver (3.3.0), geckodriver 0.15.0  ruby 2.3.3p222 (2016-11-21 revision 56859) [i386-mingw32]  Browser:   Firefox  Browser Version:   52.0  ## Expected Behavior - The user should be able to switch to an iframe without 1st scrolling it into view. The user should then be able to interact with elements inside of the iframe. This may be related to issue 2377, but I am not sure.  ## Actual Behavior - The user is NOT able to switch to an iframe without 1st scrolling it into view. The code seems to be switching to the iframe, but the user will NOT be able to interact with elements inside of the iframe.  ## Steps to reproduce - Sample html https://jsfiddle.net/0hdtcyjz/40/  On the sample jsfiddle page...  Click the 'Update iFrame' button. This will load an HTML form into the iFrame found at the bottom of the page, but the user would still need to scroll to get to the iframe. Do NOT scroll to the iframe.  Switch to the iframe using something like  driver.switch_to.frame driver.find_element(:id,'iframe_id')  Attempt to click button1 in the frame  driver.find_element(:xpath, "//*[@value='button1']")  Selenium will NOT be able to click the button

Please reopen 3721.  Behavior works in IEDriverServer 2.48, but not latest
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows 7  Selenium Version:   3.3.0  Browser:   IE  Browser Version:   11.0.9600.18617, Update Version: 11.0.40  ## Expected Behavior - Users should be able to obtain browser cookies from PDF-only browser windows. This does not work using IEDriver server 3.3.0.0, but does work with ChromeDriver 2.28.455520 and GeckoDriver 0.15.0 AND IEDriverServer 2.48.  ## Actual Behavior - I get a Net::Timeout exception in Ruby.  ## Steps to reproduce -  Step 1. Open Internet Explorer  Step 2. Navigate to a pdf (e.g., http://myserver/my_pdf.pdf)  Step 3. Verify that the PDF is displayed in the main browser window.  Step 4. Attempt to read the browser's cookies. I'm using Ruby so for me, it's something like... cookie_string = ""  # Read the cookie hash... $driver.manage.all_cookies.each { |cookie| 	# consolidate the cookie hash to a string              # (e.g., cookie_name1=cookie_val1;cookie_name2=cookie_val2;etc...)     	cookie_string = cookie_string + "#{cookie[:name]}=#{cookie[:value]};"   }  puts "COOKIES! -> #{cookie_string}"

column3: "Port" leaking in C# WebDriver.dll
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows 10, Windows Server 2008 R2 Selenium Version:   WebDriver 3.4.0 Browser:   Firefox and Chrome  Browser Version:   Firefox: 53.0.3 (32 bits) Chrome: Version 59.0.3071.86 (Official Build) (64-bit)  ## Expected Behavior - WebDriver suppose to close the ports after each commands sent to ChromeDriver or GeckoDriver  ## Actual Behavior - WebDriver keeps the ports open until the WebDriver quit(). This caused the ports run out from the OS when I had 8 parallel tests running together without open and close ChromeDriver or FirefoxDriver.  ## Steps to reproduce -   Run the Selenium Tests with ChromeDriver or FirefoxDriver with any simple action, e.g. Navigate to a website. Repeat this step for 1000 time.  Open a Windows Command Prompt, type: netstat -a -b   You will find the ChromeDriver/GeckoDriver holds up about 1000 ports without releasing.  I have amended the code in OpenQA.Selenium.Remote.DriverServiceCommandExecutor.cs, line 37 old code: this(driverService, commandTimeout, true) new code: this(driverService, commandTimeout, false)  and  OpenQA.Selenium.Remote.HttpCommandExecutor.cs, line 46: old code: : this(addressOfRemoteServer, timeout, true) new code: : this(addressOfRemoteServer, timeout, false)  Retest again with the above step, we can see the ChromeDriver / Gecko Driver doesn't hold up the port any more.  It seems for HttpWebRequest object, even it is out of scope, if its' KeepAlive property is true, the .net runtime holds it until the WebDriver is quit and closed.  In theory, I can't think of HttpCommandExecutor should have HttpWebRequest should have KeepAlive = true as it looks like HttpCommandExecutor is running stateless commands. Maybe you can consider to remove the passing in of the attribute to avoid future problem.  Kind regards  Ken Han  Self Service Tech Lead Fairfax Media Australia

column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows 10 64bit  Selenium Version:   selenium 3.4.0  Browser:    Firefox Version 53 using 0.16.1 geckodriver and   Steps to reproduce -  We are trying to install a new extension that we developed and it does not contain an install.rdf because this technique is now legacy as mentioned [here ](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/Add-ons/Install_Manifests). The problem is that using the 0.16.1 geckodriver with selenium 3.4 does not seem to support this new kind of extensions and throws a : java.io.FileNotFoundException C:\Users(username)\AppData\Local\Temp\unzip3999903548710354720stream\install.rdf (The system cannot find the file specified)  Of course manually the extension installs. You can get it from [here](https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/mooltipass-extension/) I have asked at geckodriver github and they said it is a selenium issue

column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows 10  Selenium Version:    Browser:   Firefox 55.0.3 (64-bit)  Error Message : There was an unexpected error. Msg: TypeError: window.editor.infoPanel is undefined Url: chrome://selenium-ide/content/selenium-ide.xul, line: 1, column: 1 onclick@chrome://selenium-ide/content/selenium-ide.xul:1:1   Since Firefox version 48, Mozilla requires all add-ons to be signed. Until recently, Firefox support in Selenium was exclusively provided by an add-on. As this add-on is not currently signed, this solution does not work with the latest Firefox releases. As an alternative, Mozilla are working on a WebDriver specification compliant implementation named GeckoDriver. Please note that the specification is not complete, and that Selenium itself does not comply with the specification at this time. This means that features previously available through Selenium will not be available using GeckoDriver.  Any issue logged here for Firefox 48 or later will be closed as a duplicate of #2559. Our recommendation is to switch to GeckoDriver, or to continue testing on Firefox 45 until GeckoDriver is a viable option for you. If you are interested in helping us to sign the add-on to restore support for later Firefox versions, please see the following comment for what's needed: https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/issues/2942#issuecomment-259717567  If the issue is with Google Chrome consider logging an issue with chromedriver instead: https://sites.google.com/a/chromium.org/chromedriver/help  If the issue is with Microsoft Edge consider logging an issue with Microsoft instead: https://developer.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-edge/platform/issues/  If the issue is with Firefox GeckoDriver (aka Marionette) consider logging an issue with Mozilla: https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/buglist.cgi?product=Testing&component=Marionette  If the issue is with Safari, only Safari 10+ is supported. Please log any Safari issue with Apple: https://bugreport.apple.com/  If the issue is with PhantomJS consider logging an issue with Ghostdriver: https://github.com/detro/ghostdriver  -->  Browser Version:     ## Expected Behavior -  ## Actual Behavior -  ## Steps to reproduce -
