column3: WebDriverWait is immediately raising a BROWSER_TIMEOUT exception rather than waiting for the given amount of time
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows 10 Selenium Version:   3.5.0 Browser:   Firefox 55.0.1  Browser Version:     ## Expected Behavior - Running Selenium 3.5.0 in a grid, I would expect a ```WebDriverWait``` to run for a given amount of time, then a ```Message: OpenQA.Selenium.WebDriverTimeoutException``` exception to be raised.  ## Actual Behavior - The wait fails immediately with a ```Message: System.InvalidOperationException : Session [2647d75b-987e-4797-99d3-e49eb1c4227a] was terminated due to BROWSER_TIMEOUT``` exception.  Downgrading Selenium to 3.3.0 resolves this and the wait works correctly.  ## Steps to reproduce - Hub config; ``` {   "port": 4444,   "newSessionWaitTimeout": -1,   "servlets" : [],   "withoutServlets": [],   "custom": {},   "capabilityMatcher": "org.openqa.grid.internal.utils.DefaultCapabilityMatcher",   "throwOnCapabilityNotPresent": true,   "cleanUpCycle": 5000,   "role": "hub",   "debug": true } ```  Test ``` using System; using NUnit.Framework; using OpenQA.Selenium; using OpenQA.Selenium.Remote; using OpenQA.Selenium.Chrome; using OpenQA.Selenium.Firefox; using OpenQA.Selenium.Support.UI;  namespace UnitTestProject1 {     [TestFixture]     public class UnitTest1     {          public UnitTest1()         {         }          [Test]         public void TestMethod1()         {             IWebDriver driver;                          FirefoxOptions options = new FirefoxOptions();             options.BrowserExecutableLocation = @"C:\Program Files\Mozilla Firefox\firefox.exe";              driver = new RemoteWebDriver(new Uri("http://localhost:4444/wd/hub"), options.ToCapabilities());             driver.Navigate().GoToUrl("https://google.com");              WebDriverWait waits = new WebDriverWait(driver, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));             IWebElement element = waits.Until(ExpectedConditions.ElementIsVisible(By.Id("THISELEMENTIDDOESNOTEXIST")));         }     } } ``` Run the above code sample with Selenium 3.5.0, geckodriver 0.18 and Firefox.

column3: Misleading error message
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows 10 Selenium Version:   3.4.0 Browser:   Browser independent  ## Expected Behavior - Selenium should report a timeout error (i.e. "Timed out waiting for driver server to start" + e) after trying to poll the /status endpoint on a driver for 20 seconds as per DriverService's waitUntilAvailable()  ## Actual Behavior - Selenium tries to get an exit code after timing out by calling checkForError(). This method can eventually throw an exception itself when the driver is still running but is not responsive, which results in a misleading error message. Here's a stacktrace:  `java.lang.IllegalStateException: The process has not exited yet therefore no result is available ... 	at org.apache.commons.exec.DefaultExecuteResultHandler.getException(DefaultExecuteResultHandler.java:76) 	at org.openqa.selenium.os.UnixProcess.checkForError(UnixProcess.java:174) 	at org.openqa.selenium.os.CommandLine.checkForError(CommandLine.java:183) 	at org.openqa.selenium.remote.service.DriverService.waitUntilAvailable(DriverService.java:192) 	at org.openqa.selenium.remote.service.DriverService.start(DriverService.java:181)`  ## Steps to reproduce - Sadly, we haven't been able to find the reason why our IE driver can't accept requests every so often. The bug is flaky and difficult to reproduce, but a more accurate error message would make it easier to debug.

column3: Chrome extension not being loaded by ChromeDriver
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows 10  Selenium Version:   3.5.2 Browser:   Chrome version 57 ChromeDriver version: 2.29  ## Expected Behavior - When I load Chrome browser using ChromeDriver, the extension should be loaded with the browser. ## Actual Behavior - No extension is loaded with the browser. You will see that this doesn't work. column3: GetScreenshot
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows 10  Selenium Version:   .Net PackageL Selenium WebDriver 3.4.0  Browser:   Internet Explorer  Browser Version:   Version: 11.1480.14393.0 Update Version: 11.0.44  ## Expected Behavior - Screenshot is taken of the browser's current viewport (without scrolling back to the top).  ## Actual Behavior - Before the screenshot is taken, the browser scrolls back to the top of the page and then the screenshot is taken. In Edge, Chrome, and Firefox, this is not the behavior. Those browsers take the screenshot of the current viewport without scrolling to the top.  ## Steps to reproduce - ```C# var driver = new InternetExplorerDriver(); driver.Manage().Window.Position = new Point(0, 0); driver.Manage().Window.Size = new Size(1280, 800);  driver.Manage().Timeouts().ImplicitWait = TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10);  // navigate to the base url driver.Navigate().GoToUrl("http://www.engadget.com");  // just wait a bit for the page to fully load Thread.Sleep(5000);  // scroll down 100 px driver.ExecuteScript("window.scrollTo(0, 100)");  // take a screenshot var screenshotDriver = driver as ITakesScreenshot; Screenshot screenshot = screenshotDriver.GetScreenshot(); var capturedScreen = new Bitmap(new MemoryStream(screenshot.AsByteArray));  capturedScreen.Save("C:\\screenshot.png"); ```

column3: Firefox minimize in between running test.
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows -7 64 bit Selenium Version:   3.5.1, 3.5.2, 3.5.3, 3.6.0 Gecko Driver 0.18.0 Browser:   Firefox  Browser Version:   55.0.3, 56  ## Expected Behavior - Browser should run full Test in maximize.  ## Actual Behavior - Firefox minimize in between running test.   [FireFox Minimize.zip](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/files/1354778/FireFox.Minimize.zip)    For example:-(Run this code, test case run but firefox minimize)   package testCases;  import org.testng.annotations.Test;   import org.testng.annotations.BeforeTest;  import java.util.List; import java.util.concurrent.TimeUnit;  import org.openqa.selenium.By; import org.openqa.selenium.Dimension; import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver; import org.openqa.selenium.WebElement; import org.openqa.selenium.firefox.FirefoxDriver; import org.openqa.selenium.firefox.FirefoxProfile; import org.openqa.selenium.remote.CapabilityType; import org.openqa.selenium.remote.DesiredCapabilities; import org.openqa.selenium.support.ui.ExpectedConditions; import org.openqa.selenium.support.ui.WebDriverWait; import org.testng.Assert; import org.testng.annotations.AfterTest;  public class FireFx { 	 	public WebDriver driver; 	   @Test   public void doSearch() throws InterruptedException { 	   	  WebElement element = driver.findElement(By.name("q")); 	    element.sendKeys("Cheese!\n");  	    element.submit();  	    // wait until the google page shows the result 	    WebElement myDynamicElement = (new WebDriverWait(driver, 10)) 	              .until(ExpectedConditions.presenceOfElementLocated(By.id("resultStats")));  	    List findElements = driver.findElements(By.xpath("//*[@id='rso']//h3/a"));  	    // this are all the links you like to visit 	    for (WebElement webElement : findElements) 	    { 	        System.out.println(webElement.getAttribute("href")); 	    } 	    Thread.sleep(2000); 	    WebElement element1 = driver.findElement(By.linkText("Cheese - Wikipedia")); 	    element1.click(); 	    Thread.sleep(2000); 	    Assert.assertEquals("Cheese - Wikipedia", driver.getTitle()); 	  System.out.println("Successfully!!!");   }      @BeforeTest   public void beforeTest() { 	   	  System.setProperty("webdriver.gecko.driver", "Path\\geckodriver.exe"); 	   		driver = new FirefoxDriver(); 	  driver.get("http://www.google.com"); 	   driver.manage().window().maximize(); 	  driver.manage().timeouts().implicitlyWait(10, TimeUnit.SECONDS); 	     }    @AfterTest   public void afterTest() { 	    driver.close();     }  }

column3: Dotnet - Attempt to save a screenshot to a directory which does not exist throw a cryptic generic GDI error
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows Selenium Version:   3.5.1 Browser:   any  Browser Version:   any  When we try to save a screenshot to a directory which does not exist, It throws with the following error: ``` A generic error occurred in GDI+ ```  ## Expected Behavior - It should either create the directory or throw an explicit `DirectoryNotFoundException`  ## Actual Behavior - It throws a cryptic generic GDI exception  ## Steps to reproduce -  Add the following to an existing test ```csharp                  var testScreenShotPath = "C:\\PathToADirectoryWhichDoesNotExists";                                 var path = Path.Combine(testScreenShotPath, ${Guid.NewGuid()}.jpg");                 var screenshot = ((ITakesScreenshot)BrowserInstance).GetScreenshot();                 screenshot.SaveAsFile(path, ScreenshotImageFormat.Jpeg); ```  Run the test  Additional reference can be found [on Stackoverflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/29973934/a-generic-error-occurred-in-gdi-screenshot-saveasfile-externalexception)

column3: selenium-webdriver 3.4.1 or above breaks Selenium::WebDriver.for
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows Selenium Version:   3.4.2 Browser:   Chrome  Browser Version:     ## Expected Behavior - Being able to launch another browser with default capabilities as supported by version 3.4.0, with the [syntax described on the wiki](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/wiki/Ruby-Bindings)  driver = Selenium::WebDriver.for :remote, desired_capabilities: :firefox  or  driver = Selenium::WebDriver.for :remote, desired_capabilities: :chrome  ## Actual Behavior -  NoMethodError:        undefined method `capabilities' for :firefox:Symbol  or  NoMethodError:        undefined method `capabilities' for :chrome:Symbol  This syntax used to work with version 3.4.0, but it does not work with 3.4.1 or 3.4.2

column3: How to specify Firefox version in Selenium 3.4.0 Grid
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Windows  Selenium Version:   3.4.0  Browser:   Firefox  Browser Version:   52  ## Expected Behavior - The Selenium remote webdriver can choose a node with the correct Firefox version by setting the version in the capabilities  ## Actual Behavior - Server responses with: "Unrecognized channel: 52" The problem comes with these two commits:  https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/commit/d773d2ae4ae2c17b8983bfdb25994490ef35b805#diff-1945a3d6d32eb94f85054cf3218bb7f1 https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/commit/d2378dd1d1b15c0e87ddc293dd7e74ef53443dd2#diff-230a6397be96d5d56ea1fd43ffda7b0d  Now the version in the capabilities has to be a channel and not a version anymore. Was this intended? If so, how can i specify a Firefox version from the Selenium Grid?  ## Steps to reproduce - ``` DesiredCapabilities capabilities = DesiredCapabilities.firefox(); capabilities.setPlatform(Platform.LINUX); capabilities.setVersion("52"); new RemoteWebDriver(this.seleniumHubUrl, capabilities); ```

column3: Cannot set proxy with Firefox
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Ubuntu 17.04 Selenium Version:   3.4, Java Browser:   Firefox -->  Browser Version:   55.0a1  ## Expected Behavior - Firefox should use proxy settings.   ## Actual Behavior -  Exception:   ``` CrawlService org.openqa.selenium.InvalidArgumentException: httpProxy was not of the form host[:port] ```   ## Steps to reproduce -  I am unable to get a Proxy working with Firefox. I have tried several methods, including the usual:  ``` proxy.setHttpProxy("http://0.0.0.0" + ":" + server.getPort()); DesiredCapabilities reqs = new DesiredCapabilities(); capabilities.setCapability(CapabilityType.PROXY,proxy); ``` and  ```          JsonObject json = new JsonObject();         json.addProperty("proxyType", "manual");         json.addProperty("httpProxy", "http://0.0.0.0");         json.addProperty("httpProxyPort", server.getPort());         json.addProperty("sslProxy", "http://0.0.0.0");         json.addProperty("sslProxyPort", server.getPort());          capabilities.setCapability(CapabilityType.PROXY, json); ``` and  ```          JsonObject jp =  new JsonParser().parse("{proxy:{" +         "proxyType:" + Proxy.ProxyType.MANUAL + "," +                 "httpProxy:\"" + "0.0.0.0" + "\"," +                 "httpProxyPort:" + server.getPort() + "," +                 "sslProxy:\"" + "0.0.0.0" + "\"," +                 "sslProxyPort:" + server.getPort() + "," +                 "ftpProxy:\"" + "0.0.0.0" + "\"," +                 "ftpProxyPort:" + server.getPort() + "," +                 "socksProxy:\"" + "0.0.0.0" + "\"," +                 "socksProxyPort:" + server.getPort() +                 "}}").getAsJsonObject();  capabilities.setCapability("requiredCapabilities", jp);  ```  Each of these gives the same error, even if I use the server address `http://localhost` or (BrowserMobProxy) `server.getClientBindAddress().getHostAddress()`  I can confirm the proxy works with ChromeDriver.

column3: webdriver.Builder().forBrowser('chrome').build() hangs indefinitely
column4: ## Meta - OS:   ubuntu (linux) Selenium Version:   "selenium-webdriver": "^3.4.0", Browser:   chrome  Browser Version:   Google Chrome 58.0.3029.81   ## Expected Behavior - All tests should run without getting error on getting webdriver ## Actual Behavior - call to build webdriver hangs  ## Steps to reproduce - I am using mocha and selenium to do end to end integration testing. I am using beforeEach and afterEach hook to initialize browser and kill it after each test. Here is my js file which has both the methods  ```     const webdriver = require('selenium-webdriver')     require('selenium-webdriver/chrome')     require('chromedriver')     global.driver = {}          // setup     beforeEach(async function () {       this.timeout(60000)       try {         driver = await new webdriver.Builder().forBrowser('chrome').build()         await driver.manage().window().setSize(1600, 900)       } catch (ex) {         console.log(ex.stack)       }          })          afterEach(async function () {       this.timeout(60000)       await driver.quit()     }) ```  Now when i run the test suit on jenkins i very frequently see this ("email already registered" is a test name)      ✓ email domain not allowed (4167ms)         1) "before each" hook for "email already registered"               39 passing (9m)       1 pending       1 failing            1)  "before each" hook for "email already registered":          Error: Timeout of 60000ms exceeded. For async tests and hooks, ensure "done()" is called; if returning a Promise, ensure it resolves.  The thing to notice is that once this error comes the subsequent tests do not run. My test suit has 100s of tests and in the run above it quit once it encountered this beforeEach error and didn't run next set of tests.

column3: chrome driver takes 131 seconds to start headless browser
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Ubuntu Selenium Version:   3.5.0 Browser:   Chrome  Browser Version:   Google Chrome 60.0.3112.101 (64 bit)  ## Expected Behavior - Start chrome driver in less than a minute ## Actual Behavior - Chrome driver starts in exactly 131 seconds every time (issues started randomly out the blue) ## Steps to reproduce - It's just simple code, i start up Xvfb (virtual frame buffer) and i start the chrome driver, but it takes 131 seconds to start. Here is the selenium debug log, and in addition i log the time it takes to start to webdriver.   ``` 08/18/2017 03:34:03 PM Testing driver: https://chromedriver.storage.googleapis.com/2.24/chromedriver_linux64.zip 08/18/2017 03:34:07 PM POST http://127.0.0.1:52807/session {"capabilities": {"alwaysMatch": {"browserName": "chrome"}, "firstMatch": [{}]}, "desiredCapabilities": {"platform": "ANY", "browserName": "chrome", "version": "", "chromeOptions": {"args": [], "extensions": []}}}    08/18/2017 03:36:15 PM Finished Request 08/18/2017 03:36:15 PM DELETE http://127.0.0.1:52807/session/9c3894efdb69dc989966cc37e6f1fd22 {"sessionId": "9c3894efdb69dc989966cc37e6f1fd22"} 08/18/2017 03:36:15 PM Finished Request 08/18/2017 03:38:23 PM completed in 131 seconds ```  I haven't did any update prior to this problem, the issue just appeared randomly, starts up in a few seconds and i can run my test suite. It currently still works on mac os, just not for linux.  Thank You,

column3: In MS Edge v14+, SelectElement fails to deselect options from HTML  controls
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Tested on Linux/Mono version 5.2.0.215 Likely affects any OS with DotNet Selenium Version:   Reproduced on `Selenium.Support` (NuGet package v3.4.0) Appears that it will also affect v3.5.1 (based on a brief code review) Browser: Microsoft Edge Browser Version:   Reproduced with Edge 15 on Windows 10  ## Expected Behavior - ### Deselecting single elements Given you have an instance of `OpenQA.Selenium.Support.UI.SelectElement` and: * It wraps a visible HTML `` element * That select element has the `multiple` attribute * The select element has more than one option currently-selected.  When you make use of any of the **DeselectByXyz** methods from the `SelectElement` instance, indicating one of the currently-selected options (either by index, underlying value or displayed text).  Then the indicated option should be deselected and any other options which were previously selected should remain so.  ### Deselecting all elements Given you have an instance of `OpenQA.Selenium.Support.UI.SelectElement` and: * It wraps a visible HTML `` element * That select element has the `multiple` attribute * The select element has more than one option currently-selected.  When you make use of the **DeselectAll** method from the `SelectElement` instance.  Then all of the options in the select element should be deselected.  ## Actual Behavior - In Edge, the Deselect operation is functioning like "Select single option".    ### Deselecting single elements In the first scenario (deselecting single elements), the actual result is that now the *only* element selected is the element which you had requested to deselect.  ### Deselecting all elements In the second scenario (using deselect-all) the result is that: * The first item (in markup order) which was previously selected before **DeselectAll** was invoked is now selected * All other previously-selected items are now deselected  ## Steps to reproduce - I have a test case for this, and records from a failed CI build.  Probably the Sauce Labs test log is the most useful, as it shows a breakdown of all of the API calls made to WebDriver.  * **[HTML markup used in the test case]** - *You can ignore the non-standard `metal:` attributes in the markup - they have no bearing on the test*   * There is [some JavaScript associated with the page] which keeps some other elements on the page in-sync with the `` controls and read their values * **[Test fixture]** - *This is written in a Screenplay testing style (that being the project where I found this) but rest-assured, the deselection lines of test code just lead to a plain SelectElement and its deselect methods* * **[Travis build log]** - *This is for Edge, the other jobs in the same build (current latest Chrome, Firefox, Internet Explorer and Safari) all pass this same test*   * Notably, near the bottom of the build log is a Screenplay report, which indicates which features/scenarios were being executed and in what order.  Lines 2870 through 2904 are where the deselect tests fail. * **[Sauce Labs test logs]** - *This log was produced using the Travis build job linked above, and the order in which the tests appear in the Screenplay report are the same as they were executed in Sauce Labs*   * Notably, command 15: `POST element/4/click` appears to be the troublesome one.  MS Edge appears to be interpreting this as "Select this option and only this option" where all other browsers treat it as "toggle selection"   * This is evident in the associated Sauce Labs screenshot - the element which was clicked is the one which reads "Carrot" which has the value (bold text near the bottom of the screen) "veg".  However, it should have been deselected, not selected.  [HTML markup used in the test case]: https://github.com/csf-dev/CSF.Screenplay/blob/985fef9f2e9de92ad8d0ec4c052cea15e9a635db/Tests/CSF.Screenplay.WebTestWebsite/Views/PageTwo/Index.pt [some JavaScript associated with the page]: https://github.com/csf-dev/CSF.Screenplay/blob/985fef9f2e9de92ad8d0ec4c052cea15e9a635db/Tests/CSF.Screenplay.WebTestWebsite/Scripts/PageTwo.js [Test fixture]: https://github.com/csf-dev/CSF.Screenplay/blob/985fef9f2e9de92ad8d0ec4c052cea15e9a635db/Tests/CSF.Screenplay.Web.Tests/Actions/DeselectTests.cs [Travis build log]: https://travis-ci.org/csf-dev/CSF.Screenplay/jobs/265696662 [Sauce Labs test logs]: https://saucelabs.com/beta/tests/6275bc4aca324b209a97c563efd3ccd9/commands#15  ## Research I have performed so far I have a feeling that this might be related to [issue #5437605] on Microsoft's Edge issue tracker (which was migrated from [this previous report]).  If it is, then Microsoft consider it "functioning as specified" for Edge to interpret clicks as single-item selection (for a `` element).  It seems that they would want WebDriver to do more than just a normal click (such as sending modifier keys) in order to get the desired functionality.  This would mean that `SelectElement` does not support Edge as-is?  I'm not sure where to go next from here.  Is it a Selenium bug or an Edge bug?  Seems that might be up for some debate.  [issue #5437605]: https://developer.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-edge/platform/issues/5437605/ [this previous report]: https://connect.microsoft.com/IE/feedback/details/2020772/-microsoft-edge-webdriver-cannot-select-multiple-on-select-html-tag

column3: ExpectedConditions.visibilityOfElement(element) does not work to find element
column4: ## Meta - OS:   OSX 10.12.6 Selenium Version:   3.4.0 Browser:   Firefox 54.0.1, geckodriver 0.18 Chrome 59.0.3071.115, chromedriver 2.30 It happens on Firefox and Chrome both, it does not look like a FF specific issue.  Browser Version:   Firefox 54.0.1 (64-bit) Chrome 59.0.3071.115 (64-bit)  ## Expected Behavior - Element should be found by using ExpectedConditions.visibilityOfElement(element)  ## Actual Behavior - Element is not found by using ExpectedConditions.visibilityOfElement(element)  ## Steps to reproduce - Please execute this code, I have mentioned the comments in the code for which line is not working as expected.  import org.junit.After; import org.junit.Before; import org.junit.Test; import org.openqa.selenium.By; import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver; import org.openqa.selenium.WebElement; import org.openqa.selenium.firefox.FirefoxDriver; import org.openqa.selenium.support.ui.ExpectedConditions; import org.openqa.selenium.support.ui.WebDriverWait;  public class ExplicitWaitTest {  	private WebDriver driver; 	private String baseUrl = "https://letskodeit.teachable.com/p/practice";  	@Before 	public void setUp() { 		System.setProperty("webdriver.gecko.driver", ""); 		driver = new FirefoxDriver(); 		driver.manage().window().maximize(); 	}  	@Test 	public void testWithExplicitTime() { 		driver.get(baseUrl); 		driver.findElement(By.xpath("//div[@id='navbar']//a[contains(text(),'Login')]")).click();  		WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(driver, 3);  		// ExpectedConditions.visibilityOf(element) -> This method is not finding the element 		WebElement emailField = wait.until( 				ExpectedConditions.visibilityOf(driver.findElement(By.id("user_email")))); 		 		// ExpectedConditions.visibilityOfElementLocated(locator) -> This is finding the element correctly 		// WebElement emailField = wait.until( 		//		ExpectedConditions.visibilityOfElementLocated(By.id("user_email"))); 		emailField.sendKeys("test data"); 	}  	@After 	public void tearDown() throws InterruptedException { 		Thread.sleep(2000); // just for looking 		driver.quit(); 	} }

column3: window.stop() on a website results in timeout with Chromedriver
column4: ## Meta - OS:   OS X 10.12.6  Selenium Version:   3.4.0  Browser:   Chrome  Language: NodeJS  Browser Version:   60.0.3112.113 (Official Build) (64-bit)  ## Expected Behavior - When navigating to a website that executes window.stop(), by using driver.get(), Selenium shouldn't become unresponsive. Instead, after the navigation has been completed, the test case should continue. Even though window.stop() causes the page to stop loading prematurely, it doesn't change the fact that the navigation has been completed.  ## Actual Behavior - [SEVERE] Timed out receiving message from renderer: 59.326 [SEVERE] Timed out receiving message from renderer: -0.002  ## Steps to reproduce - driver.get() to a page that executes the JS: ```window.stop()```, it will hang and timeout with the error above.

column3: Chrome ignores .pac file
column4: ## Meta - OS:   OS X 10.12 Selenium Version:   3.4.0 (NodeJS) Browser:   Chrome Browser Version:   Version 60.0.3112.78 (Official Build) (64-bit)  ## Expected Behavior - Driver.get makes request to "http://my-test-site.com" via the proxy specified in the .pac file.  ## Actual Behavior - Driver.get makes request to "http://my-test-site.com" without using proxy.  ## Steps to reproduce - ``` var webdriver = require('selenium-webdriver'); var chrome = require('selenium-webdriver/chrome'); var proxy = require('selenium-webdriver/proxy');  var service = new chrome.ServiceBuilder(config['CHROMEDRIVER_PATH']).build(); chrome.setDefaultService(service);  var options = new chrome.Options();  driver = new webdriver.Builder() .forBrowser('chrome') .setChromeOptions(options) .setProxy(proxy.pac("http://url-to-my-pac-file.com/file.pac")) .build();  driver.get('http://my-test-site.com'); ```  Additional info: 1) I can see from "url-to-my-pac-file.com" logs that the .pac file gets downloaded. 2) If I put gibberish in the .pac file, I still get the same result ie. seems like it doesn't get parsed by Chrome. 3)  options.addArguments(`--proxy-server=http://myproxy:1000`); works properly

column3: Selenium::WebDriver::Error::ServerError Error 500
column4: ## Meta - OS:   macOS Sierra 10.12.4 Selenium-Webdriver Version:   3.4.4 Browser:   Chrome  WebDriver Version:   59.0.3071.115  ## Expected Behavior -  The code should be able to get the driver and start running tests on the node.  ## Actual Behavior -  I have set up a selenium grid and a google chrome node using docker and when trying to connect to the hub to get the driver I get an Error 500.  Full error: /Users/apuri/.rvm/gems/ruby-2.4.0/gems/selenium-webdriver-3.4.4/lib/selenium/webdriver/remote/response.rb:72:in `assert_ok': status code 500 (Selenium::WebDriver::Error::ServerError) 	from /Users/apuri/.rvm/gems/ruby-2.4.0/gems/selenium-webdriver-3.4.4/lib/selenium/webdriver/remote/response.rb:32:in `initialize' 	from /Users/apuri/.rvm/gems/ruby-2.4.0/gems/selenium-webdriver-3.4.4/lib/selenium/webdriver/remote/http/common.rb:83:in `new' 	from /Users/apuri/.rvm/gems/ruby-2.4.0/gems/selenium-webdriver-3.4.4/lib/selenium/webdriver/remote/http/common.rb:83:in `create_response' 	from /Users/apuri/.rvm/gems/ruby-2.4.0/gems/selenium-webdriver-3.4.4/lib/selenium/webdriver/remote/http/default.rb:107:in `request' 	from /Users/apuri/.rvm/gems/ruby-2.4.0/gems/selenium-webdriver-3.4.4/lib/selenium/webdriver/remote/http/common.rb:61:in `call' 	from /Users/apuri/.rvm/gems/ruby-2.4.0/gems/selenium-webdriver-3.4.4/lib/selenium/webdriver/remote/bridge.rb:170:in `execute' 	from /Users/apuri/.rvm/gems/ruby-2.4.0/gems/selenium-webdriver-3.4.4/lib/selenium/webdriver/remote/bridge.rb:103:in `create_session' 	from /Users/apuri/.rvm/gems/ruby-2.4.0/gems/selenium-webdriver-3.4.4/lib/selenium/webdriver/remote/bridge.rb:54:in `handshake' 	from /Users/apuri/.rvm/gems/ruby-2.4.0/gems/selenium-webdriver-3.4.4/lib/selenium/webdriver/remote/driver.rb:39:in `initialize' 	from /Users/apuri/.rvm/gems/ruby-2.4.0/gems/selenium-webdriver-3.4.4/lib/selenium/webdriver/common/driver.rb:58:in `new' 	from /Users/apuri/.rvm/gems/ruby-2.4.0/gems/selenium-webdriver-3.4.4/lib/selenium/webdriver/common/driver.rb:58:in `for' 	from /Users/apuri/.rvm/gems/ruby-2.4.0/gems/selenium-webdriver-3.4.4/lib/selenium/webdriver.rb:86:in `for' 	from grid.rb:3:in `'   ## Steps to reproduce - create a docker-compose.yml with the following:  hub:     image: 'selenium/hub'     ports:         - '4444:4444'  chrome:     image: 'selenium/node-chrome-debug'     hostname: chrome     ports:         - '5909:5900'     links:         - hub  Run docker-compose up -d  Once it's up and running, you should be able to navigate to localhost:4444 and see the selenium grid page. Clicking the console should bring you to the page with the nodes.  The ruby script that I have is:  require 'selenium-webdriver'  @driver = Selenium::WebDriver.for(   :remote,   url: "http://localhost:4444/wd/hub", desired_capabilities: :chrome) # you can also use :chrome, :safari, etc.   Running this gives me the error, I've tried 0.0.0.0 instead of localhost too with the same result. I've also tried mapping to a different port but it doesn't work. I have selenium-webdriver v 3.4.4. [Selenium-Docker.zip](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/files/1174561/Selenium-Docker.zip)

column3: Selenium 3.5.0 - Python - set_page_load_timeout() issue
column4: ## Meta - OS:   macOS Sierra 10.12.2 Selenium Version:  3.5 Driver:  Chomedriver 2.31 Python: 3.6.1   [](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/45850978/chromedriver-browser-timeout-go-back-to-previous-page-error-python-selenium/45867310#45867310)  ## Expected Behavior -  Expect driver to timeout, return control, and drop the exception.  ## Actual Behavior -  Driver hits timeout, return control, but further .get() return timeout error.  ## Steps to reproduce -  This does not work  ``` from selenium import webdriver  driver = webdriver.Chrome(executable_path='../helpers/drivers/chromedriver_2_31') driver.set_page_load_timeout(0.1)  driver.get('http://www.abc.com')  driver.set_page_load_timeout(10) driver.get('http://www.abc.com') ```  This Does   ``` driver = webdriver.Chrome(executable_path='../helpers/drivers/chromedriver_2_30') driver.set_page_load_timeout(0.1)  driver.get('http://www.abc.com')  driver.set_page_load_timeout(10) driver.get('http://www.abc.com') ```  [https://stackoverflow.com/questions/45850978/chromedriver-browser-timeout-go-back-to-previous-page-error-python-selenium/45867310#45867310](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/45850978/chromedriver-browser-timeout-go-back-to-previous-page-error-python-selenium/45867310#45867310)

column3: WebDriverException, Status code was: -6
column4: ## Meta - OS:   macOS Sierra  10.12.4  Selenium Version:   3.4.0  Browser:   Chrome   -->  Browser Version:   61.0.3124.4 64-bit  ## Expected Behavior - Open a chrome browser.  ## Actual Behavior - App crashes with:  ``` Traceback (most recent call last):   File "accountmaker.py", line 37, in      driver = webdriver.Chrome(executable_path=CHROMEDRIVER_DIR + 'chromedriver') #,chrome_options=chrome_options)   File "/usr/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/selenium-3.4.3-py2.7.egg/selenium/webdriver/chrome/webdriver.py", line 62, in __init__     self.service.start()   File "/usr/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/selenium-3.4.3-py2.7.egg/selenium/webdriver/common/service.py", line 96, in start     self.assert_process_still_running()   File "/usr/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/selenium-3.4.3-py2.7.egg/selenium/webdriver/common/service.py", line 109, in assert_process_still_running     % (self.path, return_code) selenium.common.exceptions.WebDriverException: Message: Service /Users/makalele/Documents/rozne/chromedriver unexpectedly exited. Status code was: -6 ```  ## Steps to reproduce - ``` from selenium import webdriver CHROMEDRIVER_DIR = '/Users/makalele/Documents/rozne/' sys.path.append(CHROMEDRIVER_DIR) driver = webdriver.Chrome(executable_path=CHROMEDRIVER_DIR + 'chromedriver') ```  path is right for 100%, I've also added it to $PATH.  Where can I find what status codes mean and where's the problem?

column3: Incompatible W3C patterns between Ruby bindings and server
column4: ## Meta - OS:   MACOS Darwin Selenium Version:   Ruby bindings: 3.5.1  Standalone server: 3.5.1 Browser:   IOS Simulator safari  ## Error ``` java.lang.IllegalArgumentException: W3C payload contained keys that do not comply with the spec: [platformVersion] 	at org.openqa.selenium.remote.server.NewSessionPayload.validateSpecCompliance(NewSessionPayload.java:179) ```  ## Step to reproduce: 1) Start selenium standalone server as hub 2) Start appium and register to hub 3) Start test with following config by appium ruby bindings ```     automationName: 'xcuitest'     platformName: 'ios'     platform: :mac     platformVersion: '10.3'     browserName: 'safari'     deviceName: 'iPhone 6s'     newCommandTimeout: 1200     marionette: false     autoAcceptAlerts: false     autoDismissAlerts: true     showIOSlogs: true     noReset: true ```  In step 3, in fact appium will call selenium ruby binding W3C::Capabilities.from_oss to generate w3c capabilities and to do a handshake(https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/rb/lib/selenium/webdriver/remote/bridge.rb#L183)  The W3C defined platform_version is a KNOWN w3c pattern: https://seleniumhq.github.io/selenium/docs/api/rb/Selenium/WebDriver/Remote/W3C/Capabilities.html  However in selenium standalone server side, you don't define 'platformVersion' is a valid w3c patterns https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/java/server/src/org/openqa/selenium/remote/server/NewSessionPayload.java#L63  In W3C definition: https://www.w3.org/TR/webdriver/, "PlatformVersion" is not defined. So could u please remove it from Selenium Ruby bindings.  Thanks

column3: [SafariDriver] Unable to Login to Webpage
column4: ## Meta - OS:   mac OS Sierra Version 10.12.5  Selenium Version:   3.4.0  Browser:   Safari 10.1.1 (12603.2.4)   ## Expected Behavior - Safari automated browser opens and follows nightwatch test cases.  Correct login credentials should be accepted and the user should be directed to the main page of the website.    ## Actual Behavior - Safari opens as expected and successfully runs any test cases that do not involve loging into the webpage. When it attempts to submit the correct login information, the safari page enters a loading state and the TC assertion fails because it is unable to confirm that we're now on the app main screen.    Interestingly enough, if I interrupt the automation test and attempt to login to the page manually using the automated safari instance, I get the same error. Normal Safari does not have this issue. I can login as expected. To me, this suggests an issue with Safari itself. Is that consistent with what others thing   ## Steps to reproduce - I'm using nightwatch and have the following two files. "testSafariError.js" and "safariErrorPage.js" Please run the following: _nightwatch --e 'safari' --test testSafariError.js_   **"testSafariError.js"**  ```export default {    after: (client) => {     client.end();   },    'Login/Home - Login - Login with correct credentials': (client) => {     const loginPage = client.page.safariErrorPage();     loginPage.navigate();     client.pause(2000);     loginPage.login('{username}', '{password}');      // after successful login     // we are redirected to projects page     client.pause(4000);     client.assert.urlContains('projects');   }, }; ```    **"safariErrorPage.js"**  ```const loginCommands = {   clickElementVisible(element) {     return this       .waitForElementVisible(element)       .click(element);   },    clickElementPresent(element) {     return this       .waitForElementPresent(element)       .click(element);   },    login(email, pass) {     return this       .waitForElementVisible('@emailInput')       .setValue('@emailInput', email)       .clearValue('@passInput')       .setValue('@passInput', pass)       .clickElementVisible('@loginButton');   }, };  const loginElements = {   emailInput: 'input[type=email]',   passInput: 'input[name=password]',   loginButton: 'button[type=submit]', };  export default {   url: '{Page URL}',   commands: [loginCommands],   elements: {     emailInput: {       selector: loginElements.emailInput,       locateStrategy: 'css',     },     passInput: {       selector: loginElements.passInput,       locateStrategy: 'css',     },     loginButton: {       selector: loginElements.loginButton,       locateStrategy: 'css',     },   }, }; ```

column3: org.openqa.selenium.safari.SafariDriver#toString fails with org.openqa.selenium.WebDriverException
column4: ## Meta - OS:   MAC OS Sierra - 10.12.5 (16F73)  Selenium Version:   3.5.1  Browser:   Safari  Browser Version:    10.1.1  ## Expected Behavior - When one creates a new noargs SafariDriver and call toString() on it, the toString() should return a correct string representation of the driver.  ## Actual Behavior - When one creates a new noargs SafariDriver and calls toString() on it this fails with the exception  ``` org.openqa.selenium.WebDriverException: Unrecognized platform: macOS Build info: version: '3.5.1', revision: '9c21bb67ef', time: '2017-08-17T15:26:08.955Z' ```  ## Steps to reproduce -  ``` import org.junit.Test; import org.openqa.selenium.safari.SafariDriver;  public class SafariDriverTest {      @Test     public void testSafariDriverToString(){         SafariDriver safariDriver = new SafariDriver();         safariDriver.toString();     } } ```

column3: [SafariDriver] Random Unknown error
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Mac OS Siera 10.12.5 Selenium Version:   3.4.0 Browser:   Safari 10 Browser Version:   10  ## Expected Behavior - Tests run 100% of the time no errors  ## Actual Behavior - Tests randonly fail on Safari browser running on Mac OS ## Steps to reproduce -  I have CI system. It consists ofJenkins Master server (version 2.60.2) running on Ubuntu 16.04Jenkins slaves Swarm Slave (version 3.4.1) running on Ubuntu 16.04Selenium hub (version 3.4.0) running on Ubuntu 16.044 Selenium nodes for Safari Browser (version 3.4.0) Running on Mac OS Siera 10.12.5 . With Safari 10.Im testing Java Script project that uses Mocha+Karma to run tests.Most of the time everything is working as it should. But sometimes i have error like this one.  `{"message":"[get(\"http://my-jenkins-slave-hostname:9876/?id=39481\")] Error response status: 13, UnknownError - An unknown server-side error occurred while processing the command. Selenium error: com.google.gson.stream.MalformedJsonException: Use JsonReader.setLenient(true) to accept malformed JSON at line 1 column 8 path $","status":13,"cause":{"value":{"stacktrace":"com.google.gson.JsonSyntaxException: com.google.gson.stream.MalformedJsonException: Use JsonReader.setLenient...`  It looks like some nodes of selenium sometimes fail randomly. All nodes are exact replicas of same image (Im using Mac Stadium to manage Mac OS nodes)  Ive tried to configure Karma to give more details in logs, ive tried to increase timeouts, but no luck. Error message stays the same. How can i troubleshoot such problem? Any ideas?

column3: Python Selenium element.is_displayed returning true even when element is not visible on the page
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Linux Ubuntu 16.04 Selenium Version:   3.4.3 Browser:   Chrome  Browser Version:   60.0.3112.113  ## Expected Behavior - I am testing the functionality of a hamburger nav that displays a menu sidebar when clicked. The menu is hidden by setting `transform:TranslateX` to -17rem via css. Before clicking hamburger icon, the x property of the menu sidebar is -272 (not visible, not displayed). The actual starting and ending pixels of the element are -272 (left edge) to 0 (right edge). After clicking, the x property is 0 (you can see the menu on the page). The actual starting and ending pixels of the element are 0 (left edge) to 272 (right edge).  When I use the `element.is_displayed()` method before clicking, the method returns True even though the element is clearly, definitely not visible on the page. The expected behavior is that before clicking the hamburger icon to open the menu sidebar, the `element.is_displayed()` returns False  ## Actual Behavior - `element.is_displayed()` returns True even though element is not visible  ## Steps to reproduce - ``` from selenium import webdriver from selenium.webdriver.common.by import By import time  options = webdriver.ChromeOptions() options.add_argument('--ignore-certificate-errors') options.add_argument("--test-type") options.binary_location = "/usr/bin/google-chrome" driver = webdriver.Chrome(chrome_options=options) driver.get("http://www.wesh.com")  #disable flex ad driver.execute_script("""         setInterval(function() {             var $flex = document.querySelector("#ad-flex");             //$flex.style.display = "none";             $flex && $flex.parentNode && $flex.parentNode.removeChild($flex);         }, 1);         """)  #get menu sidebar, which is not visible initially unless you click the hamburger nav icon sidebar = driver.find_element_by_css_selector("nav.sidepanel") hamburger_nav = driver.find_element_by_css_selector("a.header-button.header-sidepanel-button")         sidebar_visible_before = sidebar.is_displayed() hamburger_nav.click() time.sleep(.5)   sidebar_visible_after = sidebar.is_displayed()  print("visible before click", sidebar_visible_before) print("visible after click", sidebar_visible_after) driver.quit() ```

column3: testRightClick needs update when chrome 60 is released.
column4: ## Meta - OS:   Linux and Windows Selenium Version:   head Browser:   Chrome >60  Browser Version:    >60   The testRightClick will fail with chrome 60  https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/javascript/atoms/test/mouse_test.html#L194  Chrome has made the change deliberately:   https://chromium.googlesource.com/chromium/src/+/bafc23e1920cc799c03159c39e29878e26071db0  So the selenium test will need to be changed when 60 is released.  The diff will be something like ``` @@ -203,8 +203,8 @@      assertEvents(        mouseoverAndMoveEvents(greenDiv, 0),        mousedownEvents(greenDiv, 2), -      mouseoutEvents(greenDiv, b({ie: 0, wk: 2, ff: 0})), -      mouseoverAndMoveEvents(redDiv, b({ie: 2, wk: 2, ff: 0})), +      mouseoutEvents(greenDiv, b({ie: 0, wk: 0, ff: 0})), +      mouseoverAndMoveEvents(redDiv, b({ie: 2, wk: 0, ff: 0})),        mouseupEvents(redDiv, 2),        goog.events.EventType.CONTEXTMENU, redDiv, b({ie: 0, wk: 2, ff: 2})      ); ```

column4: ## Meta - OS:   Hub: Debian 8, Servers: Windows 2012 R2 Selenium Version:   3.4.0 (both hub and servers) Browser:   Chrome  Browser Version:   N/A  ## Expected Behavior - Grid should hook up and run.  ## Actual Behavior - `new RemoteWebDriver(new Uri("http://[hostname]:4444/wd/hub"), DesiredCapabilities.Chrome(), TimeSpan.FromMinutes(15));` throws a InvalidOperationException with an empty string as the message, with the following stack trace:  ``` at OpenQA.Selenium.Remote.RemoteWebDriver.UnpackAndThrowOnError(Response errorResponse)    at OpenQA.Selenium.Remote.RemoteWebDriver.Execute(String driverCommandToExecute, Dictionary`2 parameters)    at OpenQA.Selenium.Remote.RemoteWebDriver.StartSession(ICapabilities desiredCapabilities)    at OpenQA.Selenium.Remote.RemoteWebDriver..ctor(ICommandExecutor commandExecutor, ICapabilities desiredCapabilities)    at OpenQA.Selenium.Remote.RemoteWebDriver..ctor(Uri remoteAddress, ICapabilities desiredCapabilities, TimeSpan commandTimeout) ```  ## Steps to reproduce - Update to web driver 3.4.0, instantiate a new web driver.   ---  I was able to roll back to 2.3.0 of the .NET libs and the issue goes away, the worst part is I'm getting an empty error message which is leaving me to believe it's this line: https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/dotnet/src/webdriver/Remote/RemoteWebDriver.cs#L1384  Being as the other lines that throw InvalidOperationExceptions should at least give me an empty string with formatting in it.  I  have the hub set up with full logging, I see absolutely nothing come in prior to this error.

column3: Exception thrown setting Firefox binary
column4: ## Meta - OS:   As tested MAC but the issue will appear on all OSes Selenium Version:  3.5.3 Browser: Firefox (though Chrome is likely to be affected as well since we can set the binary as part of DefaultRemoteProxy.beforeSession(...) )   Browser Version:  55.0.3  ## Expected Behavior No exception would be thrown while trying to set the binary location for Firefox  ## Actual Behavior  (relevant chunk of the stack trace)  Aug 29, 2017 3:28:11 PM org.openqa.grid.web.servlet.handler.RequestHandler beforeSessionEvent SEVERE: Error running the beforeSessionListener : null java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException 	at com.google.common.collect.ImmutableMap.put(ImmutableMap.java:495) 	at org.openqa.grid.selenium.proxy.DefaultRemoteProxy.beforeSession(DefaultRemoteProxy.java:228) 	at org.openqa.grid.web.servlet.handler.RequestHandler.beforeSessionEvent(RequestHandler.java:165) 	at org.openqa.grid.web.servlet.handler.RequestHandler.process(RequestHandler.java:105) 	at org.openqa.grid.web.servlet.DriverServlet.process(DriverServlet.java:84) 	at org.openqa.grid.web.servlet.DriverServlet.doPost(DriverServlet.java:68)  ## Steps to reproduce -  Attempt to set the location of the Firefox binary during testing.   ## Known Location/Issue  During the upgrade from Selenium 2.53.7 to Selenium 3, WebDriverRequest.extractDesiredCapability() switched to returning an ImmutableMap from a standard map. Then, when we attempt to modify it to inject the binary location as part of DefaultRemoteProxy, it throws an exception since modification of the map is not allowed.

column3: [ruby] How to add debuggerAddress experimental option?
column4: ## Meta - OS:   archlinux Selenium Version:   gem selenium-webdriver (3.4.4) Browser:   google-chrome-stable 60.0.3112.78  ## Discription I want to attach selenium to existing session of chrome, and then tweak pages using my chrome profile, but from terminal I have found that this is [feasible using debuggerAddress](https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromedriver/issues/detail?id=710#c3)  ## Excerpt -  ``` Launch Chrome from command prompt: chrome.exe --remote-debugging-port=8181  Sample Code: 		ChromeOptions options = new ChromeOptions(); 		options.setExperimentalOption("debuggerAddress", "127.0.0.1:8181"); 		 		WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver(options); 		driver.manage().timeouts().implicitlyWait(1, TimeUnit.MINUTES); 		driver.get("http://www.google.com"); 		driver.findElement(By.name("q")).sendKeys("test"); 		driver.quit();  ```  ## Steps to reproduce - ``` // close all chrome windows $ google-chrome-stable --remote-debugging-port=4444 // chrome opened with my profile $ pry >  require 'selenium-webdriver' >  Selenium::WebDriver::Chrome.path = '/usr/bin/google-chrome-stable' >  Selenium::WebDriver::Chrome.driver_path = '/usr/bin/chromedriver' >  options = Selenium::WebDriver::Chrome::Options.new >  # options.add_experimental_option("debuggerAddress", "127.0.0.1:4444") # how???? >  driver = Selenium::WebDriver.for :chrome, options: options  ```

column3: HTTP TRACE method activated
column4: ## Meta - OS:   any Selenium Version:   any, including 3.4.0 Browser:   any  ## Expected Behavior - HTTP TRACE method disabled  ## Actual Behavior - HTTP TRACE method activated on Selenium Hub port  ## Steps to reproduce - ``` >curl  -X TRACE http://localhost:4444/ TRACE / HTTP/1.1 User-Agent: curl/7.33.0 Accept: */* ```  We use Selenium in a Production environment and the Selenium Hub doesn't pass the vulnerability audit due to HTTP TRACE method activated  Is there a way to disable that HTTP method when starting the Selenium Hub?

column3: Selenium Click functionality does not work consistently
column4: ## Meta - OS:      Windows/Linux (Cent OS & Ubuntu)  Selenium Version:       Any WebDriver version Browser:       Chrome/Firefox and IE (Any version)  ## Expected Behavior - Click operation should always work when no exception is thrown  ## Actual Behavior - Click action works something and sometime it does not. It shows the element is actually being clicked, as for link and buttons we can see dotted border around the object. However the action on that click is not triggered. I tried .Click() / Actions Class/ Click using JS/ Press Enter button on element but none is working all the time.  ## Steps to reproduce - I wish I could have provided the steps but this is happening on multiple webpages on click action. Many people around world is facing this issue. Save can be checked on stackoverflow or other forums. Element is present on the page and page is completely loaded when I took screenshot. I have seen this issue with Java and Python web drivers.   ## Suggestions & Observations - I think selenium is sending the click but browser (IE/FF/chrome) are not ready to process it. May be its binding to JS is not done or something like that. If that is the case then is there a way selenium can find if the browsers are ready to perform click. I guess selenium already check for DOM status. Please  see if anything else which can solve the problem

column3: Incomplete documentation
column4: ## Meta - OS:    Selenium Version:  3.5.3  Browser:     Browser Version:     ## Steps to reproduce -  Can I RESPECTFULLY say that I find the [Selenium official Python documentation](https://seleniumhq.github.io/selenium/docs/api/py/api.html) incomplete?  For example, the documentation for `selenium.webdriver.remote.webelement` fails to point out that `find_elements*` method always return a list (eventually empty), while `find_element*` return the element directly or raises a `selenium.common.exceptions.NoSuchElementException`  The `switch_to` documentation of `selenium.webdriver.remote.webdriver.WebDriver` is non-existent (literally) There is a documentation for `switch_to_active_element()` and the like which says that the methods are deprecated and you should use `driver.switch_to.active_element` instead. But what does the `switch_to` methods do at all? What does it mean to switch to the default element? Or to an alert? Or to a default content?  The example of `selenium.webdriver.remote.webelement.WebElement` 's  `get_property()` function is wrong. It says  > # Check if the "active" CSS class is applied to an element. > text_length = target_element.get_property("text_length")  At least the comment is wrong, which seems to have been copy-pasted from the `get_attribute(name)` function  > # Check if the "active" CSS class is applied to an element. > is_active = "active" in target_element.get_attribute("class")  Maybe it's just me, or maybe I have found the wrong link from the documentation (the link is on pypi page of selenium). Selenium is a great piece of software, but I think it would be event better if the documentation was better

column3: In selenium, when I land on a web page or open a web page, I am using driver.switchTo.activeElement() to find which element(Say element textbox2) on the web page is receiving the focus among say 20 elements(say textbox1, textbox2, radio1, radio2, chkbox1, chkbox2, label1, label2, so on) the moment I land on the page. So we can say that the default focus is on some element(say textbox2) when I land on the page.  How can I find whether it is in Window or frame programatically ? Ofcourse I can inspect through Firebug and find out whether it is in Window or iframe manually but I don't want to do manual inspection but get it programatically by using some Selenium method or Javascript function. Do we have something like getXpath() method in Selenium or Javascript to extract the Xpath of the element ? Any other way to know if not through Xpath to know if the element is in Window or iframe(frame) ?

column3: Browser long starts - DriverService waitUntilAvailable timeout should be parameterized
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows10, Linux CentOs 7  Selenium Version:   3.4.0 Browser:   All  ## Expected Behavior - On some specific environment or after many tests, browsers can be a bit long to start (more than 30sec) so we must be able to set a custom timeout when Driver.waitUntilAvailable() function is called. For example we can have a setLaunchTimeout(timout) function on WebDriver class or a configuration key.  ## Actual Behavior - Timeout is set to 20sec with no way to change it. We have firefoxes than starts in 30 or 40 sec after performing tests.  ## Steps to reproduce -  Launch more than 5 firefoxes on the same computer, the 6th one should start in more than 20sec

column3: System went to deadlock while using sendKeys for text fields.
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 7 Selenium Version:   3.4.0 & 3.5.3 Browser:   Internet Explorer, Google Chrome Browser Version:   IE 11 (64-bit), Chrome 56.0 (64-bit)  ## Expected Behavior - SendKeys command should type the value in the field and should move ahead.  ## Actual Behavior - SendKeys typing the value in the same field continuously. The script went to deadlock as the sendkeys is repeated for the same text field. ## Steps to reproduce - This issue isn't coming frequently but when it's coming it's making the script in deadlock.  I'm using the Selenium Standalone Server (3.4.0) with the Java for current automation script. It's the private site on the local server I'm working on automation. I faced sometimes the sendkeys command is repeating only for the same fields continuously. I tried same with Selenium Standalone Server (3.5.3) as well but the things remain same for that as well.   I'm posting the IE driver logs from the script where you can find about the script repetition on the same field. I'm attaching the video for same as well for more reference. column3: Unable to Start Firefox Using the Legacy Driver on a 3.5.3 Grid
column4: ## Meta - OS:  Windows 10  Selenium Version:  3.5.3  Browser:  Firefox  Browser Version:  52.3.0 ESR  Selenium Bindings: .NET 3.5.2  I'm currently testing out 3.5.3 to see if I can finally upgrade my grid from 3.3.1.  I've decided to stick with Firefox 52 ESR and the legacy Firefox driver instead of using geckodriver and the latest Firefox due to existing issues in geckodriver.  I'm running into an issue trying to start an instance of Firefox using the legacy driver.  It works in two instances but not in the third.  ### Using the Browser Directly, No Standalone or Grid This works properly.  Firefox opens and my tests execute properly.  This is the code I'm using to start the browser. `var ffOptions = new FirefoxOptions { UseLegacyImplementation = true };` `IWebDriver d = new FirefoxDriver(ffOptions);`  ### Using the Browser via Selenium Server Standalone This also works properly.  I start the jar without any options like this: `java -jar .\3.5.3.jar -enablePassThrough false`    I start the browser like this: `var legacyFfOptions = new FirefoxOptions { UseLegacyImplementation = true };` `DesiredCapabilities capabilities = (DesiredCapabilities)legacyFfOptions.ToCapabilities();` `IWebDriver driver = new RemoteWebDriver(RemoteServerUrl,                     capabilities,                     TimeSpan.FromSeconds(ConfigReader.BrowserTimeout / 1000));`  ### Using the Browser via Grid Setup (Hub/Node) This does not work.  When my test tries to start up the browser, I'm getting an error at the hub which I will paste below.   I start the hub like this: `java -jar .\3.5.3.jar -enablePassThough false -role hub`  I start my node like this: `java -jar \3.5.3.jar -enablePassThough false -role node -hub http://10.1.14.195:4444`  The browser is started the same way as when I'm hitting a standalone server. column3: When using FirefoxDriver+geckodriver, Action.mouseMoveTo() thows an UnsupportedCommandException
column4: ## Meta - OS: OpenSUSE Linux 42.2 64-bit Selenium Version: 3.5.3 Browser: Firefox 52.3.0 ESR GeckoDriver Version: 18  ## Expected Behavior - When FirefoxDriver is created with a geckodriver specified, and mouseMoveTo() eventually called on a WebElement, it works as expected, without throwing an exception ## Actual Behavior - UnsupportedCommandException thrown ## Steps to reproduce - In Java, first create a FirefoxDriver, and open a URL: ``` System.setProperty("webdriver.gecko.driver", "/tmp/geckodriver"); RemoteWebDriver driver = new FirefoxDriver(); driver.get("https://github.com/SeleniumHQ"); ``` then call moveToElement: ``` WebElement elm = driver.findElement(By.xpath("//a[contains(@href, '/SeleniumHQ')]")); Actions actions = new Actions(driver); actions.moveToElement(elm).perform(); ```  Note that I found this issue:  **"UnsupportedCommandException mouseMoveTo with 3.4 on firefox with geckodriver 0.16.1 #4008"**  which would at first seem to be the same, but it was closed by jimevans as being the same as  **"Grid does not handle w3c capabilities correctly #3808"**  but #3808 is ALSO closed, with the apparent fix/workaround of adding "-enablePassThrough true" to the Java command-line invocation of a standalone Selenium server.    Well, I'm not using Grid or a standalone Selenium server, so how do I pass this option?  Why is #3808 closed when as of Selenium v3.5.3, I'm still hitting the issue?  Is there a way to set "enablePassThrough" in the DesiredCapabilities when I call the constructor for FirefoxDriver?  Note, I'm using the geckodriver with FirefoxDriver, not the legacy mode, and I don't want to use the legacy mode as I want to support FF 55+.  Is FirefoxDriver no longer supported?  As recently as 10 days ago, someone has been tweaking the FirefoxDriver.java source, so it doesn't look like it's dead.

column3: Underlying webdriver instance does not support javascript error shown when using Edge
column4: ## Meta - **OS:**  Windows10 **Selenium Version:**     Ruby gem - selenium-webdriver 3.5.1   Selenium-Standalone-Server 3.5.0 (also tested with 3.5.3) **Browser:**  Edge  **Browser Version:**  15.15063 (64bit)  ## Expected Behavior - Not getting the Javascript support error since it's enabled and also works fine with with selenium 3.4.0 (both webdriver gem and standalone server) with the same Edge browser and same reproduce steps.  ## Actual Behavior - When performing an action like watir element.flash (or fire_event), I get this Javascript error and the test fails. This happens only on Edge (not on Chrome or FF), when I use selenium-webdriver 3.5.1 and selenium-standalone-server 3.5.0 (or 3.5.3).   ## Steps to reproduce - ```ruby require 'watir' url = "http://localhost:4444/wd/hub" caps = WebDriver::Remote::Capabilities.new caps[:browserName] = "MicrosoftEdge" browser = Watir::Browser.new( 	:remote, 	:url => url, 	:desired_capabilities => caps) browser.goto "https://www.google.com" element = browser.input(:id => 'lst-ib') element.flash ``` I get the error: ```ruby irb(main):008:0* browser = Watir::Browser.new( irb(main):009:1* :remote, irb(main):010:1* :url => url, irb(main):011:1* :desired_capabilities => caps) You can now pass values directly into Watir::Browser opt without needing to use :desired_capabilities => # irb(main):012:0> irb(main):013:0* browser.goto "https://www.google.com" => "https://www.google.com" irb(main):014:0> element = browser.input(:id => 'lst-ib') => #"lst-ib", :tag_name=>"input"}> irb(main):015:0> element.flash Selenium::WebDriver::Error::UnsupportedOperationError: underlying webdriver instance does not support javascript         from C:/Ruby23/lib/ruby/gems/2.3.0/gems/selenium-webdriver-3.5.1/lib/selenium/webdriver/remote/oss/bridge.rb:569:in `assert_javascript_enabled'         from C:/Ruby23/lib/ruby/gems/2.3.0/gems/selenium-webdriver-3.5.1/lib/selenium/webdriver/remote/oss/bridge.rb:267:in `execute_script'         from C:/Ruby23/lib/ruby/gems/2.3.0/gems/selenium-webdriver-3.5.1/lib/selenium/webdriver/common/driver.rb:213:in `execute_script'         from C:/Ruby23/lib/ruby/gems/2.3.0/gems/watir-6.8.1/lib/watir/browser.rb:265:in `execute_script'         from C:/Ruby23/lib/ruby/gems/2.3.0/gems/watir-6.8.1/lib/watir/js_snippets.rb:12:in `execute_js'         from C:/Ruby23/lib/ruby/gems/2.3.0/gems/watir-6.8.1/lib/watir/js_execution.rb:48:in `block in flash'         from C:/Ruby23/lib/ruby/gems/2.3.0/gems/watir-6.8.1/lib/watir/elements/element.rb:678:in `element_call'         from C:/Ruby23/lib/ruby/gems/2.3.0/gems/watir-6.8.1/lib/watir/js_execution.rb:48:in `flash'         from (irb):15         from C:/Ruby23/bin/irb.cmd:19:in `' irb(main):016:0> ```  ## Side note - I created this ticket here on request of @titusfortner @Blackbaud-TitusFortner (see link below to Watir-general group) I did raise this issue with MS: [MS-dev-edge-issues](https://developer.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-edge/platform/issues/13599112/) And I did ask questions in the Selenium and Watir groups: [Selenium-users](https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/selenium-users/2FE3arNRanU) [Watir-general](https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/watir-general/KRehp-T0V-8)

column3: C# selenium 3.5 grid configuration throws W3C payload IllegalArgumentException with Chrome browser
column4: ## Meta - **OS:**  Hub-Win10 or Win7, Node-Win8_1 or Win7 **Selenium Version:**  selenium standalone jar version 3.5, selenium c# binding version 3.5, chrome driver server version 2.31 **Browser:**  Chrome  **Browser Version:**  60.0.3112.90 (Official Build) (64-bit) ## Expected Behavior - Browser opens up ## Actual Behavior - Exception (from the Hub console): ``` 2017-08-11 14:54:09.443:WARN:osjs.HttpChannel:qtp1795799895-13: /wd/hub/session java.io.IOException: org.openqa.grid.common.exception.GridException: Cannot extract a capabilities from the request: {"desiredCapabilities":{"browserName":"chrome","version":"","platform":"WIN8_1","javascriptEnabled":true},"capabilities":{"firstMatch":[{"browserName":"chrome","javascriptEnabled":true}]}}         at org.openqa.grid.web.servlet.DriverServlet.process(DriverServlet.java:135)         at org.openqa.grid.web.servlet.DriverServlet.doPost(DriverServlet.java:68) . .  . . Caused by: java.lang.IllegalArgumentException: W3C payload contained keys that do not comply with the spec: [javascriptEnabled]         at org.openqa.selenium.remote.server.NewSessionPayload.validateSpecCompliance(NewSessionPayload.java:167)         at java.util.stream.ReferencePipeline$11$1.accept(Unknown Source)         at java.util.stream.ReferencePipeline$3$1.accept(Unknown Source)         at java.util.LinkedList$LLSpliterator.forEachRemaining(Unknown Source)         at java.util.stream.AbstractPipeline.copyInto(Unknown Source)         at java.util.stream.AbstractPipeline.wrapAndCopyInto(Unknown Source)         at java.util.stream.ReduceOps$ReduceOp.evaluateSequential(Unknown Source)         at java.util.stream.AbstractPipeline.evaluate(Unknown Source)         at java.util.stream.ReferencePipeline.collect(Unknown Source)         at org.openqa.selenium.remote.server.NewSessionPayload.validate(NewSessionPayload.java:152)         at org.openqa.selenium.remote.server.NewSessionPayload.(NewSessionPayload.java:134)         at org.openqa.grid.web.servlet.handler.WebDriverRequest.extractDesiredCapability(WebDriverRequest.java:70)         at org.openqa.grid.web.servlet.handler.SeleniumBasedRequest.(SeleniumBasedRequest.java:102)         at org.openqa.grid.web.servlet.handler.WebDriverRequest.(WebDriverRequest.java:40)         at org.openqa.grid.web.servlet.handler.WebDriverRequestFactory.createFromRequest(WebDriverRequestFactory.java:30) . .  ``` ## Steps to reproduce - Set up a selenium grid configuration with the node machine having chrome browser i.e. run the following: **Hub:** java -jar "C:\SeleniumDrivers\selenium-server-standalone-3.5.0.jar" -role hub **Node:** java -jar "C:\SeleniumDrivers\selenium-server-standalone-3.5.0.jar" -role node -host xxx.xxx.xxx.xxx -port 5555 -hub http:// xxx.xxx.xxx.xxx:4444/grid/register -browser "browserName=internet explorer,version=11.0" -browser "browserName=chrome" -browser "browserName=firefox"  Try running the following lines with selenium c# binding 3.5 ``` DesiredCapabilities capability = DesiredCapabilities.Chrome(); capability.SetCapability(CapabilityType.Platform, "WIN8_1"); IWebDriver driver = new RemoteWebDriver(new Uri("http://localhost:4444/wd/hub"), capability, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(210)); driver.Manage().Timeouts().ImplicitlyWait(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10)); driver.Manage().Window.Maximize(); driver.Navigate().GoToUrl("http://google.com");  ``` [consoleException.txt](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/files/1218980/consoleException.txt)

column3: AttributeError: 'Options' object has no attribute 'binary'
column4: ## Meta - #### OS:   $uname -a   Linux archdeekus 4.11.3-1-ARCH #1 SMP PREEMPT Sun May 28 10:40:17 CEST 2017 x86_64 GNU/Linux    #### Selenium Version:   $pip3 show selenium   Name: selenium   Version: 3.4.3   Summary: Python bindings for Selenium   Home-page: https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/   Author: UNKNOWN   Author-email: UNKNOWN   License: Apache 2.0   Location: /usr/lib/python3.6/site-packages   Requires:    #### Browser:   $firefox -v   Mozilla Firefox 55.0.3    #### Browser Version:   55.0.3(64-bit)    ## Expected Behavior - Instance of Firefox starting  ## Actual Behavior - Error thrown:   ```Process Process-1: Traceback (most recent call last):   File "/usr/lib/python3.6/multiprocessing/process.py", line 249, in _bootstrap     self.run()   File "/usr/lib/python3.6/multiprocessing/process.py", line 93, in run     self._target(*self._args, **self._kwargs)   File "ProxLoadMe.py", line 186, in retrieve_source     switcher = parse_file(hoster, name, currthreads, iterator)   File "ProxLoadMe.py", line 197, in parse_file     driver = init_webdriver()   File "ProxLoadMe.py", line 51, in init_webdriver     return webdriver.Firefox(firefox_options=options, log_path="geckodriver.log")   File "/usr/lib/python3.6/site-packages/selenium/webdriver/firefox/webdriver.py", line 118, in __init__     if firefox_options.binary is not None: AttributeError: 'Options' object has no attribute 'binary' ```  ## Steps to reproduce - ``` def init_webdriver():     from selenium import webdriver     from selenium.webdriver.chrome.options import Options     options = Options()     options.binary_location = "/usr/bin/firefox"     options.add_argument("-headless")     return webdriver.Firefox(firefox_options=options, log_path="geckodriver.log")  driver = init_webdriver() driver.close() ``` Using options.binary = "/usr/bin/firefox" following error appears:   ``` Process Process-1: Traceback (most recent call last):   File "/usr/lib/python3.6/multiprocessing/process.py", line 249, in _bootstrap     self.run()   File "/usr/lib/python3.6/multiprocessing/process.py", line 93, in run     self._target(*self._args, **self._kwargs)   File "ProxLoadMe.py", line 186, in retrieve_source     switcher = parse_file(hoster, name, currthreads, iterator)   File "ProxLoadMe.py", line 197, in parse_file     driver = init_webdriver()   File "ProxLoadMe.py", line 51, in init_webdriver     return webdriver.Firefox(firefox_options=options, log_path="geckodriver.log")   File "/usr/lib/python3.6/site-packages/selenium/webdriver/firefox/webdriver.py", line 120, in __init__     if firefox_options.profile is not None: AttributeError: 'Options' object has no attribute 'profile' ``` /usr/lib/python3.6/site-packages/selenium/webdriver/firefox/webdriver.py references to /usr/lib/python3.6/site-packages/selenium/webdriver/firefox/options.py, which contains:   ``` def __init__(self):         self._binary = None         self._preferences = {}         self._profile = None         self._proxy = None         self._arguments = []         self.log = Log() ``` Calling webdriver.Firefox(log_path="geckodriver.log") simply opens Firefox.

column3: FirefoxDriver fails to identify an element based on XPath, which is getting uniquely identified in FirePath and ChromeDriver
column4: ## Meta - ## OS:   _Windows 10 64-bit_  ## Selenium Version:   _WebDriver for Java v3.4_  ## Browser:   _Firefox_   ## Browser Version:   _53.0.3 (64-bit)_  ## Test Script Source Code -  1. 		System.setProperty("webdriver.chrome.driver", "D:\\selenium\\drivers\\chromedriver.exe"); 2. 		WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver(); 3. 		//System.setProperty("webdriver.gecko.driver", "D:\\selenium\\drivers\\geckodriver.exe"); 4. 		//WebDriver driver = new FirefoxDriver(); 5. 		driver.get("http://www.amazon.in/"); 6. 		driver.findElement(By.xpath(".//input[@id='twotabsearchtextbox']")).click(); 7. 		driver.findElement(By.xpath(".//input[@id='twotabsearchtextbox']")).sendKeys("iPhone 7 256GB"); 8. 		driver.findElement(By.xpath("(.//input[@class='nav-input'])[1]")).click(); 9. 		driver.findElement(By.xpath(".//*[@id='result_1']/div/div/div/div[2]/div[1]/div[1]/a/h2")).click();  ## Expected Behavior - Line 9 of source code should identify an element uniquely based on XPath. It was inspected and found to be getting identified uniquely using Firebug & Firepath in Firefox browser.   ## Actual Behavior - Line 9 of source code identifies an element uniquely based on XPath. It was inspected and found to be getting identified uniquely using Firebug & Firepath in Firefox browser.  But, when the test script runs it is showing an exception at Line 9 saying ElementNotFound. However, the same code runs well in Chrome using ChromeDriver, i.e., the element is getting identified uniquely in chrome.  ## Steps to reproduce -  1. Create a java source file importing all selenium libraries. 2. Create a class with Main method 3. Paste the source code given above 4. Compile and run the program 5. Uncomment chrome driver code, and comment firefox driver code and re-compile and re-run, and see the difference in outcome for both drivers.
