column3: How do I manually/mouse dismiss a javascript.alert() and get back the the body of the web page
column4: ## Meta -  OS:  GCC 4.4.7 20120313 (Red Hat 4.4.7-17)]   python: 2.6.6 (r266:84292, Aug 18 2016, 15:13:37)   Browser:  firefox-52.1.0-2.el6.centos.x86_64  Selenium Version:  2.53.2  Browser Version:     ## Expected Behavior - the text of the current body should be return successfully, even if the user manually dismissed the alert.  ## Actual Behavior - selenium.common.exceptions.UnexpectedAlertPresentException:  ... Message: Unexpected modal dialog  ## Steps to reproduce -  c.f. https://stackoverflow.com/questions/44568402/how-do-i-manually-mouse-dismiss-a-javascript-alert-and-get-back-the-the-body-o  Basically, when an alert is popped up in javascript, I can `dismiss()` it from python perfectly OK, by calling `selenium.webdriver.common.alert.Alert(browser).dismiss()`.  However, if the "browser user" dismisses the alert by clicking `[OK]` (on screen) with their mouse, then the browser alert gets "Lost in Space" the `body.text` can no longer be accessed from python.  FYI: The objective of the originating code is it allow the *browser user* intervene *on screen* in testing and manually response to specific alerts.      #!/usr/bin/env python     import os,sys,time     import selenium.webdriver     import selenium.webdriver.support.expected_conditions          print dict(python=sys.version,selenium=selenium.__version__)          path=os.path.join(os.getcwd(),"hello_worlds.html")     url="file:///"+path          open(path,"w").write("""       Head Title       Hello, worlds!      """)          browser=selenium.webdriver.Firefox()     browser.get(url)          body=browser.find_element_by_tag_name("body")     print "BODY:",body.text          try:            for enum,world in enumerate("Mercury Venus Earth Mars Asteroids Jupiter Saturn Uranus Neptune".split()):              if "Earth" in world: world+=": So do MANUALLY dismiss! {Click [OK] now!!!}"         else: world+=": AUTO PILOT... please DONT dismiss! {done via selenium.dismiss()!}"              browser.execute_script('alert("Hello, %s!")'%world)         if selenium.webdriver.support.expected_conditions.alert_is_present():           print selenium.webdriver.common.alert.Alert(browser).text              time.sleep(enum+5)         if "Earth" not in world: selenium.webdriver.common.alert.Alert(browser).dismiss()              print "BODY:",body.text          finally:       browser.quit()  Output: (Crash at Earth)      {'python': '2.6.6 (r266:84292, Aug 18 2016, 15:13:37) \n[GCC 4.4.7 20120313 (Red Hat 4.4.7-17)]', 'selenium': '2.53.2'}     BODY: Hello, worlds!     Hello, Mercury: AUTO PILOT... please DONT dismiss! {done via selenium.dismiss()!}!     BODY: Hello, worlds!     Hello, Venus: AUTO PILOT... please DONT dismiss! {done via selenium.dismiss()!}!     BODY: Hello, worlds!     Hello, Earth: So do MANUALLY dismiss! {Click [OK] now!!!}!     BODY:     Traceback (most recent call last):       File "./js_alert.py", line 37, in          print "BODY:",body.text     ...     selenium.common.exceptions.UnexpectedAlertPresentException: Alert Text: Hello, Earth: So do MANUALLY dismiss! {Click [OK] now!!!}!     Message: Unexpected modal dialog (text: Hello, Earth: So do MANUALLY dismiss! {Click [OK] now!!!}!) The alert disappeared before it could be closed.  The strange thing is that if the *browser user* triggers another alert (on **another** page even!), then a `selenium.dismiss()` will pull `body.text` back from limbo and selenium with *from then* will operate as per (my) expectations.  Any suggestions on how to get the browser back to the `page.body`?  (And escape the alert)  My best guess is that the alert is coming from here.... ``` fxdriver.modals.closeUnhandledAlert = function(response, driver, accept) {   var text = driver.modalOpen;   fxdriver.modals.isModalPresent(function(present) {     var errorMessage = 'Unexpected modal dialog (text: ' + text + ')';     if (present) {       try {         if (accept) {           fxdriver.modals.acceptAlert(driver);         } else {           fxdriver.modals.dismissAlert(driver);         }       } catch (e) {         errorMessage +=         ' The alert could not be closed. The browser may be in a ' +         'wildly inconsistent state, and the alert may still be ' +         'open. This is not good. If you can reliably reproduce this' +         ', please report a new issue at ' +         'https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/issues ' +         'with reproduction steps. Exception message: ' + e;       }     } else {       errorMessage += ' The alert disappeared before it could be closed.';     }     response.sendError(new WebDriverError(bot.ErrorCode.UNEXPECTED_ALERT_OPEN,                                      errorMessage, {alert: {text: text}}));   }, 2000); }; ```

column3: Unable to click using chromedriver without scrolling into the view
column4: ## Meta -  I updated chromedriver 2.32 and chrome to 61 and started getting error   OS:   `Linux 4.4.0-1032-aws x86_64`  Selenium Version:   `2.3.0, Python`  Browser:   `chromedriver=2.32.498513  `  WebDriverException: Message: unknown error: Element is not clickable at point (106, 1302)  ``` (Driver info: chromedriver=2.32.498513 (2c63aa53b2c658de596ed550eb5267ec5967b351),platform=Linux 4.4.0-1032-aws x86_64) Browser Version:   chrome=61.0.3163.91 ``` ## Expected Behavior -  ## Actual Behavior - WebDriverException: Message: unknown error: Element is not clickable at point (106, 1302)   ## Steps to reproduce - Unable to click the element without scrolling into the view.   Chrome driver release notes: `https://sites.google.com/a/chromium.org/chromedriver/downloads` ``` Supports Chrome v59-61  Changes include: Fixes a bug where Chromedriver fails to click due to page scrolling changes in Chrome 61+. Fixes a bug where Chromedriver fails to delete cookies in Chrome 62+. Implemented spec-compliant new session handshake. Fixes a bug where Chromedriver fails to retrieve default prompt text in Chrome 62+. Changes to the way automation extension is loaded on Mac and Windows. The latest WebDriver atoms have been imported. Supports new spec compliant endpoints for executing scripts. Fixes a bug where Chromedriver fails to send characters 3 and # keys on Mac Chrome 62+. Removed dependency of GLIBC 2.18. Updates to capabilities processing as per new w3c spec. Ensures sending keys to non-prompt dialog returns correct errors as per new w3c spec. Ensure that file exists while sending keys to file input field. For details, please refer to the notes. The latest version is recommended, and bugs will not be fixed in previous versions. ```

column3: Using non-alphanumeric characters in SendKeys sends the incorrect keys
column4: ## Meta ## OS: Windows 10 Pro Selenium Version: 3.5.1 (C#) IDE: Visual Studios Enterprise 2017 Selenium Server: 3.5.2 Server OS: Windows 7 Enterprise Browsers: Chrome & IE Browser Versions: 60.0.3112.113 (Official Build) (32-bit) & 11.0.9600.18762 (Update v11.0.45) Chrome Driver Version: 2.31 IE Driver Version: 3.4.0  ## Description ## When I use driver.SendKeys(key) and the key is non-alphanumeric, like Keys.CONTROL or Keys.TAB. It will send junk, like "?" and "." instead of the actual key.   ## Details ## I recently updated my company's Grid to v3.5.1 from 2.37.0. Along with it, I updated Selenium to 3.5.1, the chrome driver to 2.31, and installed the Firefox gecko driver. Locally, when I run tests they run fine. However, when I use SendKeys while utilizing a remote web driver it sends the incorrect key code in Chrome and IE. The only difference between chrome on the server and locally is that the server version is 32bit and my local version is 64 bit (this shouldn't really be a problem because the only version for chrome driver is 32-bit for windows anyways). I thought this was just a chrome driver problem because the problem resolved itself in FireFox when I updated  to Selenium to 3.5.1. However, when I tried IE I have the same issue.  ## Example ## I apologize that I can not provide the exact code; my company's project is not open source. However, I have been able to reproduce this issues consistently on each webpage I visit using the above specifications. Here's some pseudo code if that helps:  * Navigate to https://www.cognitoforms.com/forms/build.  * After document load, switch to the 'c-build' frame * Add a text field to the form (driver.FindElement(By.ClassName("c-forms-setting-add-field")).FindElement(By.CSS("[data-code='Text']")).Click() * send keys to the "Label" field (driver.FindElement(By.Id("c-forms-settings-field")).FindElement(By.Tag("input")).SendKeys(Keys.CONTROL + "a");)   This used to select all the text in the input field and now just sends "?a". Also, sorry if there's some syntax errors, I wrote it on the fly.

column3: The setup FirefoxProfile in FirefoxOptions wipes the logging setting
column4: ## Meta  OS:  Windows 10 Selenium Version:  3.4.0 Browser:  Firefox + geckodriver 0.18.0 Browser Version:  54.0.1 (32bit)  ## Expected Behavior - If we set some profile in options and set the loglevel OFF - loglevel apply OFF Something like in [DEF.txt](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/files/1201668/DEF.txt)   ## Actual Behavior - By default, the console displays a little information when working with Firefox If we connect the profile in settings, then the loglevel is reset and we see a lot of unnecessary information in the console -  [PROFILE.txt](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/files/1201670/PROFILE.txt) If we set the loglevel to OFF and set some profile in options, then it does not apply Now (profile + Level.OFF) it like - [PROFILE_OFF.txt](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/files/1201671/PROFILE_OFF.txt)  ## Steps to reproduce - ``` FirefoxOptions options = new FirefoxOptions(); FirefoxProfile myProfile = new FirefoxProfile(); options.setProfile(myProfile); options.setLogLevel(Level.OFF);             WebDriver driver = new FirefoxDriver(options); driver.close(); ```  If we set only setLogLevel - [LEVEL_OFF.txt](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/files/1201672/LEVEL_OFF.txt) - correct work.

column3: sendKeys() method doesn't insert text to React-Select input
column4: ## Meta  OS:  Windows 10   Selenium Version: 3.5.3  Browser: Internet Explorer  ## Description  Hello to everyone!  We are having problem with insertion of text using sendKeys() method to React-Select input element since IEDriverServer 3.4.0 version. With version 3.3.0 all works normal, but with all newer versions of IEDriverServer, text is not inserted to input element of React-Select element (first select element on demo page: http://jedwatson.github.io/react-select/). Also, this issue exists only if nativeEvents capability is set to false (we are forced to run tests on that way).  Browser Version:  Internet Explorer 11.1358.14393.0 IEDriverServer Version: 3.4.0 and newer.   ## Expected Behavior   Text is inserted to select input element using sendKeys() method.  ## Actual Behavior   Text is not inserted to select input element using sendKeys() method.  ## Steps to reproduce   Demo page: http://jedwatson.github.io/react-select/ -  issue can be reproduced on first select element ("States" select) on demo page.  Steps to reproduce:  1. Run attached script with IEDriverServer version: 3.3.0 - option "Tasmania" will be selected from select element   2. Run attached script with IEDriverServer version: 3.4.0 or newer - option "Tasmania" will not be selected from select element because text is not inserted in select filter  Reproduction script: ```             DesiredCapabilities capabilities = new DesiredCapabilities();             JSONObject jsonCapabilities = new JSONObject();              jsonCapabilities.put("nativeEvents", false);             capabilities.setCapability("se:ieOptions", jsonCapabilities);              WebDriver driver = new InternetExplorerDriver(capabilities);              driver.get("http://jedwatson.github.io/react-select/");              WebElement select = driver.findElement(By.cssSelector(".section .Select"));              WebElement selectInput = select.findElement(By.cssSelector(".Select-input > input"));              selectInput.sendKeys("Tasmania");              WebElement selectOption = select.findElement(By.cssSelector(".Select-option"));              selectOption.click();              driver.quit();   ```

column3: Error: ENOENT: no such file or directory
column4: ## Meta OS: macOS Sierra Version 10.12.4 Selenium Version:   3.4.0  ## Steps to reproduce `$ npm install selenium-server@3.4.0`  `$ ./node_modules/.bin/selenium`  Then receive following error: ``` events.js:160       throw er; // Unhandled 'error' event       ^  Error: ENOENT: no such file or directory, open '/Users/ ....... /node_modules/selenium-server/lib/runner/../../logs/selenium.out' ```  I go ahead and make a `/logs` directory `$ mkdir ./node_modules/selenium-server/logs/`  Then `$ ./node_modules/.bin/selenium`  Run perfectly fine with the expected behaviour: ``` Selenium is started. All output can be found at: /Users/ ....... /node_modules/selenium-server/lib/runner/../../logs ``` And creates the 2 files in the new directory (selenium.out & selenium.err)  I tested different versions and it starts giving that error at v3.1.0. v3.0.1 works fine and creates the logs directory on npm install

column3: SendKeys throws error "Cannot set the selection end" on Input Fields of type Email / Number
column4: ## Meta OS: any Browser:  any Selenium Version:   current (3.5 master) usecase problem on 2.9.1 IDE   ## Steps to reproduce / Actual Behavior When attempting to sendKeys (Selenium IDE) on an input field of type email or number, the error of "Cannot set the selection end" is thrown.  ## Expected Behavior  The input field value should change to the appropriate text value entered like it does with other types or nontype input fields.  ## Why this is happening The sendKeys command calls the selection.js goog.dom.selection.setText function which checks for the ability to use selectionStart (via goog.dom.selection.useSelectionProperties_ function), which returns false, and thus throwing the error.   Per the W3 standards (https://www.w3.org/TR/html5/forms.html#the-input-element) the number/email input field types do not need to apply to selectionStart. I really want to know why not... but assuming that the browsers all follow this, thus is the reason why I am receiving null when checking the selectionStart on these type of input fields.  ## Suggestions I consider this an issue because I feel as though this is a very common usecase to have, especially when validating login forms and currently I don't know of a workaround for sendKeys on these fields. Either a new method of sending text needs to be changed (or added for theses cases) or at the very least it should be documented that it doesn't work.  Thanks in advance for the support!

column3: REMOTE_HOST is not replaceable with SE_OPTS
column4: ## Meta OS:  Linux using Docker Selenium Version:  3.4.0  ## Summary The removal of REMOTE_HOST breaks usage scenarios where port mapping is needed.  ## Example Setting up a selenium grid via docker as explained here:  #432.  It's essentially this `docker run -d --name node101 -p XXXXXX:5555 -e HUB_PORT_4444_TCP_ADDR=192.168.2.103 -e HUB_PORT_4444_TCP_PORT=4444 -e SE_OPTS="-host 192.168.2.103 -port XXXXXX" selenium/node-chrome:3.4.0` nodeConfig contains :   `"port": 5555`  What this is expected to do: Multiple nodes running on one host: The nodes running at port 5555 inside containers that expose this port to be unique for the host (XXXXXX). When registering to the hub the node shall tell that exposed port to the hub instead of the internal.  What it actually does: SE_OPTS  overwrites the nodes port setting, which will make it use this port (XXXXXX) inside the container which will break the port mapping.  ## Conclusion REMOTE_HOST allowed to tell the node the exposed port (without overwriting its port setting), so that it could then tell the hub to use it, making port mapping actually possible.  ## Related tickets  #307, #481, #432

column3: SlowLoadableComponent ignores UnableToLoadMessage
column4: ## Meta OS:  All  Selenium Version:  3.4.0 .NET  Browser:  Any  Browser Version:  Any  ## Expected Behavior When a SlowLoadableComponent instance throws a timeout exception on load, the message should include the UnableToLoadMessage.  ## Actual Behavior When a SlowLoadableComponent instance throws a timeout exception on load, the UnableToLoadMessage is not included into the message.  ## Steps to reproduce  1. Write a PageObject class and extend it from SlowLoadableComponent. 2. In the EvaluateLoadedStatus method, set a custom message to UnableToLoadMessage property. 3. Call the .Load() method of the PageObject. 4. Notice that the generic timeout message is thrown out and the UnableToLoadMessage is ignored.  ```     class ExamplePage : SlowLoadableComponent     {         // ...         protected override bool EvaluateLoadedStatus()         {             UnableToLoadMessage = "Unable to load example reason";             return false;         }     }      // ...      function TestMethod()     {         // throw, but the message does not include "Unable to load example reason"         new ExamplePage(...).Load();       }  ```  ## Source Code Bug Location https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/dotnet/src/support/UI/SlowLoadableComponent%7BT%7D.cs#L107-L108

column3: Session ID and Capabilities omitted from TimeoutException when used with EventFiringWebDriver.
column4: ## Expected Behavior - TimeoutExceptions thrown by WebDriverWait should include Session ID and Capabilities when instantiated with an EventFiringWebDriver. ## Actual Behavior - Session ID and Capabilities are omitted from TimeoutExceptions thrown by WebDriverWait when it is instantiated with an EventFiringWebDriver. ## Steps to reproduce - Running the following snippet will produce a TimeoutException that lacks the Session ID and Capabilities of the WebDriver instance used to instantiate the WebDriverWait. Commenting out the second line will enable the TimeoutException to include the Session ID and Capabilities.  `WebDriver driver = new InternetExplorerDriver();` `driver = new EventFiringWebDriver(driver);` `WebDriverWait driverWait = new WebDriverWait(driver, 1);` `driver.get("www.google.com");` `driverWait.until(ExpectedConditions.titleIs("Foobar"));`

column3: Python docstring examples for execute_script() and execute_async_script() are not helpful
column4: ## Expected Behavior - The "Usage" examples would be working examples.  ## Actual Behavior - The "Usage" examples are not working examples.  ## Steps to reproduce - I think the docstrings from https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/py/selenium/webdriver/remote/webdriver.py#L512, which uses `driver.execute_script('document.title')` as the example usage for both execute_script() and execute_async_script(), are used to create the [readthedocs.io Python docs](http://selenium-python.readthedocs.io/api.html#selenium.webdriver.remote.webdriver.WebDriver.execute_script), so those docstrings should be fixed to have examples like this: ```python result = driver.execute_script('return document.title') ``` and ```python result = driver.execute_async_script(""" var done = arguments[0]; asyncFuncWithCallback(function (retVal) {     done(retVal); }); """) ```

column3: Fixed the usage information in documentation of "save_screenshot".
column4: "save_screenshot" method was assigned from "get_screenshot_as_file" as result of that it's usage information was "driver.get_screenshot_as_file('/Screenshots/foo.png')" which is wrong. So I defined a separate method which is calling "get_screenshot_as_file" but with it's correct usage information as "driver.save_screenshot('/Screenshots/foo.png')"  Fixes #3651  - [x] By placing an `X` in the preceding checkbox, I verify that I have signed the [Contributor License Agreement](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#step-6-sign-the-cla)
